<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Extradited And Held Without Bail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The first person to be brought to the United
States from Colombia to face murder charges since the Colombian
government permitted U.S. extraditions was ordered held without
bail Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Baez is charged in a federal indictment with
racketeering, murder and robbery, among other charges.
</P>
<P>
   He is accused of murdering retired New York City police
Detective Donald Pagani during an August 1999 robbery of a meat
company. Baez was charged along with seven others with
participating in a racketeering organization that conspired to
commit armed robbery, murder and issue threats of violence as it
stole jewelry, money and narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Rice Jr., the agent in charge of the federal Drug
Enforcement Administration's New York office, said Baez's
extradition sends a ''clear and strong message that individuals
involved in violence and narcotics trafficking cannot hide behind
political boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in New York on Monday, after being held in Colombia
since December, when he was arrested at the request of the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombian government amended its constitution in December
1997 to allow extradition to the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
