<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pierce Improves, Celtics Moves On  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Paul Pierce, the Boston Celtics' most complete
player, is getting better after undergoing surgery for stab wounds.
But what about his team?
</P>
<P>
   The once dominant club, already deficient in many areas, begins
training camp next Monday with even more questions than coach Rick
Pitino faced before Pierce was wounded in a downtown nightclub
early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   His condition was upgraded Tuesday from fair to good following
surgery Monday to repair his damaged lung, according to officials
at the New England Medical Center. They said stab wounds to
Pierce's face, neck and back were superficial.
</P>
<P>
   WHDH-TV in Boston reported early Wednesday that arrest warrants
had been issued, but had not yet been served. The station did not
identify who was targeted in the arrest warrants. Boston police
would not confirm or deny the report.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce was drafted out of Kansas in 1998 with the 10th pick,
much later than expected. In his second NBA season, he was second
on the Celtics in scoring with 19.5 points per game. He played
forward and guard, and was a favorite of fans who made the other
half of Boston's Big Two -- Antoine Walker -- a target for their
boos.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a huge blow for the Celtics,'' Cedric Maxwell, a
former Celtics player and now a team broadcaster, said Tuesday.
''There's a lot of apathy about the Celtics. Paul Pierce was one
bright spot that you looked at, that people really loved about the
Celtics. That energy, right now, is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fans remember the Celtics' 16 NBA titles, but others recall
the 14 seasons that have passed without one and expected Walker and
Pierce to help break that streak. For now, the burden falls on
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Len Bias and Reggie Lewis were to be the cornerstones of the
team after the Larry Bird era ended. But Bias died of a cocaine
overdose after being drafted in the first round in 1986, and Lewis
collapsed and died of a heart ailment in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Seven more years have passed -- the Celtics have had losing
records in all of them -- and Pierce apparently will play again.
Even with him, the Celtics seemed headed for their sixth straight
non-playoff season.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino has said he may step down if the Celtics aren't
successful next season, his fourth with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''How does this affect his decision-making because now, to me,
he's with half his team,'' Maxwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 6-foot-7, 220-pound Pierce is lucky he wasn't hurt
more seriously, the timing of his return is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Celtics have center Vitaly Potapenko, forwards
Walker, Tony Battie, Adrian Griffin, Eric Williams and rookie draft
choice Jerome Moiso, and guards Kenny Anderson, Robert Pack, Randy
Brown, Chris Carr and Calbert Cheaney.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, Antoine's going to be looked upon to take more of a
scoring burden,'' Maxwell said. ''How will the fans react to
Antoine?''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell expects Pierce to heal physically. But Pierce's
emotional recovery could take longer.
</P>
<P>
   ''The biggest thing that people aren't looking at is how he will
react when he comes back. Will he be looking over his shoulder?''
Maxwell said. ''You have to remember (tennis player) Monica Seles.
She was attacked when she was playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Her assailant was captured and it took her a while to overcome
psychological scars and return to tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ''Suppose you don't catch this guy'' who stabbed Pierce, Maxwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   A police spokeswoman said people connected to the rap group Made
Men were being investigated, but no motive was given. The group
denied involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's family issued a statement, saying, ''Paul is in good
spirits and is looking forward to putting this ordeal behind him
and returning to what he does best -- playing basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Maxwell said, is important to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all still caught up in, 'he was, he was.' He will be
again,'' Maxwell said. ''It's up to this team to hold on. I think
it's going to be very difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
