<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 arrested at Shea after beer bottle thrown at Rocker  </HEADLINE>
By BEN WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A 22-year-old man was charged Tuesday night with
throwing a beer bottle that landed near Atlanta Braves relief
pitcher John Rocker on the mound at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Also arrested in the fracas was the fan's friend Brian Peterson,
22, who pleaded guilty in 1998 to manslaughter, along with his
girlfriend, in the death of their newborn son at a motel room in
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, vilified by New Yorkers after disparaging them in a
magazine article last year, was loudly booed when he sprinted out
of the Braves bullpen in the eighth inning to face the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepared to warm up, a beer bottle came flying out of the
first-base box seats and hit about 10 feet from Rocker. Within a
minute, police were leading a man out of the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox picked up the bottle and carried it
toward the dugout, discarding it before he reached the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have anything to say,'' Rocker said after the Braves
beat the Mets 7-1 to clinch the National League East championship.
</P>
<P>
   The man accused of throwing the beer bottle, Raymond Maniaci, of
Wyckoff, N.J., was charged with reckless endangerment.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, also of Wyckoff, was charged with obstructing
governmental administration and disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets confirmed that Peterson is the same man involved in the
infant death in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Peterson and his child's mother, Amy Grossberg, pleaded
guilty after the November 1996 death of their newborn son in
Newark, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson was given a two-year sentence, six months shorter than
Grossberg's, after he agreed to testify against her. Peterson was
released from prison after serving 1&AMP;frac12; years, and Grossberg was
released eight months early.
</P>
</TEXT>
