<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parents To Fight Standardized Tests  </HEADLINE>
By LIZ SIDOTI
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Hundreds of Ohio parents hold rallies to
denounce standardized tests. In Virginia, a mother of five drives
six hours several days a week to lobby for revised academic
standards. A Nevada mother with similar concerns runs for the state
school board.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 18 months, parents who oppose the way standardized
tests are used have mobilized in at least 36 states. Twenty states
now have exams that high school students must pass to graduate, and
all states except Iowa and Nebraska test children.
</P>
<P>
   ''This issue is striking very close to home because parents are
seeing the impact of these tests in their living and breathing
kids,'' said Karen Hartke, a project director with the National
Center for Fair &AMP; Open Testing in Cambridge, Mass. ''They're so
passionate about this issue that they have created a movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that the exams place too much stress on
children, miscalculate their abilities, limit what they are taught,
and weigh too much in determining whether they are held back.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the tests ensure solid education by holding
schools and students accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ''For decades, we've graduated students without the skills they
need, and swept the problem under the rug,'' said William Guenther,
president of Mass Insight Education, a Boston-based organization
that works to improve student achievement in Massachusetts' public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that standardized tests in core subjects can focus
attention on areas where students aren't proficient to ensure they
get the help needed to learn basic skills.
</P>
<P>
   Parents across Ohio argued Tuesday at more than 30 public forums
that proficiency tests are hurting and not helping schoolchildren.
The Ohio Education Association, the state's largest teacher union,
sponsored the events.
</P>
<P>
   Several Ohio lawmakers in the past six months have proposed
changing one or more of the four tests students must take in the
fourth, sixth, ninth and 12th grades. Gov. Bob Taft this summer
formed a commission to examine the testing system.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they're (lawmakers) feeling the pressure mainly
because of the parents,'' said Charles Johnson, a Columbus father
of three who founded Parents Against Unfair Testing. ''They
probably thought that we were just going to roll over and not get
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll conducted by the commission found that 62 percent of
Ohioans supported a law taking effect in 2001 that will require
students to repeat a year if they fail the reading portion of the
fourth-grade proficiency test. The poll questioned 1,002 people;
its margin of error was plus or minus 3.1 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   To become more knowledgeable about standardized tests, parents
have been reading education journals, talking to teaching experts,
joining Internet networks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're much more dangerous than we used to be,'' said Julie
Woestehoff, a member of Parents United for Responsible Education,
which has worked to reform education in Chicago since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ''We used to address what I call bread-and-butter issues ...
things that are really easily grasped by parents,'' she said. But
the group switched its focus as controversy swelled over the local
use of standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, vocal parents got lawmakers to scale back plans
for a high school exit exam that would have been the sole criterion
for graduation. Beginning in 2002, the exam will be one of several
factors in determining whether a student graduates.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, Mickey VanDerwerker and other parents in a
learning-standards reform group spend several days each week
lobbying politicians in Richmond, a three-hour drive from
VanDerwerker's home.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's imperative we speak with one voice to make changes
happen,'' VanDerwerker said. ''This is a political problem that
requires political solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Trusty-Murphy, of Carson Valley, Nev., tried a
different tactic to catch policy-makers' attention: She sought to
become one.
</P>
<P>
   The member of Nevada's Citizens Against Standardized Testing
Abuse ran for a state school board position. Although she lost,
Trusty-Murphy said the 4,600 votes she received encourages her to
run for the Legislature next year and shows ''there's a lot of
people thinking my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartke, of The National Center for Fair &AMP; Open Testing, says the
nation is seeing only the beginning of the backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every day we get calls from concerned parents,'' Hartke said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The National Center for Fair &AMP; Open Testing:
http://www.fairtest.org
</P>
<P>
   Mass Insight Education: http://www.massinsight.com/meri/
</P>
<P>
   Parents United for Responsible Education: http://pureparents.org
</P>
<P>
   Mass Insight Education: http://www.massinsight.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
