<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Falls Short Of Yugoslavia Goal  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The administration line for Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic is that he should be ''out of power, out of
Serbia and in The Hague.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good sound bite but administration officials privately
acknowledge that the goal of dispatching Milosevic to The Hague for
trial on war crimes charges has always been a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   A more realistic hope for the administration over the short term
is that Milosevic will emerge from the current electoral process
either severely weakened or driven from office altogether by
disaffected voters.
</P>
<P>
   It would be icing on the cake if he were to suffer the added
humiliation of being hauled before the court, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, officials say, is that any attempt to arrest the
Yugoslav leader would be tantamount to a suicide mission, given the
size of his security detail.
</P>
<P>
   He is among dozens of Serbs, Croats and Muslims who have been
indicted but who have yet to be taken into custody by the court,
officially known as the International Criminal Tribunal for the
former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   There is not much hope that Milosevic will be bundled off to The
Hague even if his main opponent in last Sunday's presidential
elections, Vojislav Kostunica, eventually assumes office. He first
must win an Oct. 8 runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica has derided the Hague tribunal, calling it ''a
political institution.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not even international ... it's an American tool for
exerting pressure, and it even makes and changes its own rules
during trials, which is legally unthinkable,'' he has said.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal handed down indictments against Milosevic and four
top aides two months after the U.S.-led NATO air war over
Yugoslavia began in March 1999. It was the first time an
international court has charged a sitting head of state with war
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said there was a credible basis to believe that
the five were ''criminally responsible'' for the deportation of
740,000 Kosovo Albanians and for the murder of 340.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica's sharp criticism of the tribunal made him a difficult
target for Milosevic during the campaign. The opposition leader
also defended the performance of the Yugoslav Army during the
Kosovo strife last year and was strident in his denunciations of
the 11-week NATO air war. In his race against Milosevic, he steered
clear of American officials, mindful that anti-Milosevic
nationalists might be offended.
</P>
<P>
   His tactics proved to be good politics. Milosevic appears to be
weaker now than at any time since assuming power more than a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration believes vote count manipulations by
Yugoslav officials deprived Kostunica of a first round, absolute
majority, victory on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While showing hostility toward the West, Kostunica would be a
far different president than Milosevic, U.S. officials believe.
They say he could be counted on to rule democratically and to
refrain from stirring up ethnic hatreds -- all in sharp contrast to
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The administration still insists that Milosevic be delivered to
The Hague, but it has been less vocal about the issue lately.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has been focusing on the
Yugoslav election campaign -- and the prospect that Milosevic will
emerge from the process totally discredited by his own
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Albright told a Senate committee Tuesday that the authorities in
Belgrade ''have used every trick in the book to prevent a fair
campaign, rig the election and distort the results. In so doing,
they have fooled no one.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly now, Milosevic is a figure of the past. For too long,
his lawlessness has weakened Yugoslavia; his cronies have robbed
Yugoslavia; and his mismanagement has all but bankrupted
Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
