<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, Sept. 27, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
28 Killed In Greece Ferry Sinking
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- A Greek ferry carrying 511 passengers and crew sank
after hitting a reef near the Aegean Sea island of Paros, coast guard officials
said. At least 28 people on board were killed and about 50 were unaccounted for.
A port official also suffered a heart attack and died after hearing news of the
sinking, the coast guard said. The ferry boat Express Samina sank after hitting
a reef late Tuesday in rough seas about two miles off the popular resort island,
officials said. Survivors said panicked passengers started jumping overboard
when the ship listed and began sinking after striking the rocky outcrop.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Street Fights Distract At IMF Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) -- Raging street protests and plumes of tear gas
received as much attention as droning speeches about debt relief and the war on
poverty on the opening day of the annual meeting of the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund. More delegates peered out of windows to catch a
glimpse of the chaos out in the streets than sat in the cavernous convention
hall by the end of Tuesday. Manuel was just one of the agency's top officials
insisting the demonstrators have it all wrong, that the IMF and World Bank are
not the enemies of the world's 2.8 billion poor, but the biggest lenders to poor
countries needing cash infusions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Sees 'Really Close Race'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- George W. Bush said today that recent swings in the polls
point to a ''really close race'' against rival Al Gore and that he is eager to
go ''toe to toe'' with him next week in the first televised debate. The
Republican presidential nominee also predicted the FBI would soon find out how a
bootleg tape of his debate preparations ended up with the Gore camp. ''I believe
we're going to get to the bottom of it and I look forward to finding out who it
was,'' Bush said in an interview on CNN's ''Larry King Live.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Milosevic Calls For Runoff Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Slobodan Milosevic conceded Tuesday that his
challenger finished first in Yugoslavia's presidential election and declared a
runoff -- defying demands at home and abroad that he step down. Opposition
candidate Vojislav Kostunica rejected an Oct. 8 runoff, calling it a ''fraud''
and insisting that he won Sunday's election outright. The opposition called for
a rally Wednesday night in downtown Belgrade to ''celebrate its victory'' --
apparently hoping for a show of strength to demonstrate to Milosevic the
public's refusal of a runoff.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
L.A. Transit Talks Break Off
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Talks between the Los Angeles regional transit
agency and the union broke off today as bus and rail operators remained on
strike for an 11th day. James Williams, chief negotiator for the United
Transportation Union, blamed the Metropolitan Transportation Authority for
refusing to consider an offer put forward by state mediators. MTA officials,
meanwhile, confirmed that the talks had broken off, but disputed the union's
statement that they had rejected the offer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 194.17
points, or 1.22 percent, to 15,734.45 at the end of the morning session.
Investors turned bearish after the Dow Jones industrial average fell 176.83
points to 10,631.32 at Tuesday's close. The Nasdaq composite index lost 52.12 to
end at 3,689.10.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Williams Beats Dementieva For Gold
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- There seems no stopping Venus Williams, who beat
the 18-year-old Elena Dementieva 6-2, 6-4 Wednesday (Tuesday night) to win an
Olympic gold medal. The victory extended Williams' winning streak to 32 matches,
and she became only the second player to win Wimbledon, the U.S. Open and the
Olympics in the same year. Steffi Graf accomplished the feat in 1988. After
completing her latest victory in 58 minutes, Williams waved to the crowd, bowed
and twirled happily at the net. Then she borrowed an American flag from the
stands and waved it with a big smile.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Braves Clinch NL East
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves clinched the NL East to win their record
ninth straight division title, beating the New York Mets 7-1 tonight behind John
Burkett's pitching and Chipper Jones' home run. With John Rocker back at Shea
Stadium -- and dodging a beer bottle on the mound -- Atlanta prevented the Mets
from wrapping up the wild card spot. New York would be assured of that berth,
however, if both Arizona and Los Angeles lost later in the evening.
AP NewsBrief By PAULINE M. MILLARD 
</P>
