<HEADLINE> Undersea Earthquake Jolts Indonesia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- An earthquake beneath the Indian Ocean
jolted parts of Indonesia's Bengkulu province Wednesday morning,
but there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries, the
Meteorology and Geophysics Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude 5.4 quake that struck just after 9 a.m. was
centered some 85 miles to the west of the coastal town of Manna. It
was felt in the provincial capital of Bengkulu, about 300 miles
northwest of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a 7.9 quake killed at least 100 people and wrecked
hundreds of buildings and homes in Bengkulu.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia, the world's largest archipelago nation, is prone to
seismic upheavals.
</P>
</TEXT>
