<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suu Kyi's Democrats Fight To Survive  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW PENNINGTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Twelve years of defiance have won
worldwide respect for Myanmar's democracy heroine, Aung San Suu
Kyi. But back home under military rule, she is struggling to keep
her decimated party alive.
</P>
<P>
   Her National League for Democracy, which marks its 12th
anniversary Wednesday, has been weakened by resignations forced by
the regime. Party offices have been closed and members arrested.
Dozens of its elected lawmakers who refuse to stand down are
detained in state ''guest houses'' until they change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Suu Kyi, 55, recently raised the stakes in her war of wills with
the dictatorial regime by defying, twice in one month, the
restrictions on her movements, the latest last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in doing so, the 1991 Nobel Peace laureate has pushed her
party to the brink in its confrontation with the junta, which has
weathered decades of international isolation and criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the past 2&AMP;frac12; years the NLD has managed a series of planned
confrontations with the government to test how far it could go and
to generate international support,'' said David Steinberg, director
of Asian Studies at Georgetown University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has been an effective strategy ... But at some point the
military may say 'enough is enough' and declare the party
illegal,'' he said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday a government statement denounced ''The so-called 'war
of endurance' and 'stop me if you dare' campaigns orchestrated by
NLD.'' It said every government step ''has been challenged,
ridiculed and impeded,'' delaying Myanmar's ''orderly transition to
a multiparty democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The regime came to power 12 years ago and maintains it is a
transitional administration, but shows no tolerance of dissent.
Experience shows it turns the screw tighter against the NLD every
time Suu Kyi tries to assert her political rights.
</P>
<P>
   After a nine-day standoff last month when Suu Kyi's motorcade
was blocked on its way south of the capital, she was forced back to
Yangon and confined to her home for two weeks. The party said at
least 11 NLD members were arrested and for the first time the party
headquarters was raided and searched.
</P>
<P>
   When she was tried to travel by train on Thursday to Myanmar's
second city, Mandalay, authorities said all tickets were sold out
and placed restrictions again on party leaders. Suu Kyi is under
virtual house arrest once more and party vice chairman Tin Oo
detained in a government guest house.
</P>
<P>
   The party also is treading on dangerous ground by insisting it
will draft a constitution for Myanmar. The government regards that
as a crime punishable by up to 21 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The NLD was formed in 1988, two weeks after the junta took power
in what was then known as Burma.
</P>
<P>
   The military gunned down thousands of protesters nationwide, but
two years later organized general elections. The NLD, bolstered by
Suu Kyi's popularity as the daughter of Myanmar's late independence
hero, Aung San, won 82 percent of the seats. Still, the military
refused to yield.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the NLD set up a proxy parliament. Many of the
392 members elected in 1990 were forced to resign or were
disqualified on technicalities. Today, the military says, only 109
remain valid members of a would-be parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the military claimed some 50,000 party members had
resigned, and an official press commentary said that less than 10
percent of the original membership remains. The NLD dismissed the
figures as fictitious but has none of its own.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. State Department report published in February accused the
regime of waging ''a systematic nationwide campaign to destroy the
NLD without formally banning it.''
</P>
<P>
   Suu Kyi, who was released from six years of house arrest in
1995, tenaciously clings to the popular mandate, but with hundreds
of supporters behind bars, she has little room for maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the recent worsening of the deadlock may be the
beginning of the endgame that might lead to the banning of the NLD,
but only if the regime is ready to weather a storm of international
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   The regime will face international scrutiny in the coming
months, which will likely deter it from taking drastic action, said
Josef Silverstein, a Myanmar expert at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Myanmar is to attend a meeting in Laos between
foreign ministers of Southeast Asia and Europe, whose relations
have been snarled for three years by a dispute over Yangon's
participation.
</P>
<P>
   With Europe now ready to engage them, Myanmar's partners in the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations would not be pleased to see
the junta crossing any red lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 0137 </TRAILER>
