<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foerster a Force in Sailing's 470  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- After waiting four years, what's one
sunny, windless day to sailors trying to win a gold medal?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. 470 class skippers Paul Foerster of Rockwall, Texas, and
J.J. Isler of San Diego were ready to sail for Olympic medals
Wednesday (Tuesday night EDT) when thunderstorms messed up the
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The men's and women's races eventually were postponed a day, but
not before some of the sailors went through the equivalent of both
a rain delay and a false start.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the looks of things out there, it was pretty good that we
didn't have a race,'' said Bob Merrick of Portsmouth, R.I.,
Foerster's crewman. ''The wind just totally shut off.''
</P>
<P>
   Storms passing over Sydney Harbor in the morning created
unstable winds and rough water at the harbor entrance, so officials
kept the boats in all classes in the marina for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The skies gradually cleared, and race officials finally sent out
the 470 women, figuring there wasn't time to squeeze in the men's
race as well. But while it was a gorgeous, sunny day on the water,
there was one problem -- only 4 knots of wind, if that. So after
bobbing around for a half hour or so, the boats came back in. Both
fleets will try again on Thursday (Wednesday night EDT).
</P>
<P>
   Isler, 36, and her crewmember, Pease Glaser, 38, of Long Beach,
Calif., are the oldest of the 470 sailors. Glaser is making her
Olympic debut, but had been through the trials three times before.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pease and I probably spent more races postponed than most of
these girls have sailed races,'' said Isler, the 1992 bronze
medalist. ''It's hard to know what other people are thinking, but
you know everyone's nervous. The good thing about our trial system
is we know we can sail well even when we're nervous and under that
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The two U.S. crews tried to stay out of the sun to conserve
their energy. Foerster and Merrick watched some other Olympic
sports on TV in the sailors' lounge.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gosh, it seems like we sat around and did nothing,'' Merrick
said. ''There's not much you can do about it. It's our job to stay
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting races in light, shifting wind can be disastrous,
especially in races with such huge consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney's winds are so shifty that during the first 49er fleet
race in this regatta, the wind turned around 180 degrees, leaving
the leaders practically dead in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't mind the really shifty conditions, but you want it to
be a fair race,'' Merrick said. ''It looked like it was so light
out there that it wouldn't be a fair race.''
</P>
<P>
   Foerster was in second place, behind the Australian crew. Isler
was third, behind Australia and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Races in the Star, Finn and Laser classes also were postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Foerster won the silver medal in the Flying Dutchman in 1992,
but then the class was dropped from the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got a job and got married. Got a cat and a dog,'' Foerster
said matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   It's that low-key approach that had him in medal contention.
</P>
<P>
   Foerster was disappointed but not devastated when the Flying
Dutchman was replaced by the Laser class. He had sailed it in two
Olympics and also won world championships in 1991 and '92.
</P>
<P>
   ''I worked really hard in that boat and then when they changed
it, it was like, 'I don't want to try another boat for '96,' ''
Foerster said. ''But for 2000, I said, 'Oh, I'll give it a shot.'
''
</P>
<P>
   So he switched to the 470 class, which is a little smaller than
the Flying Dutchman but also a two-person boat. He and Merrick,
himself a former college All-American, immersed themselves in
training, including an intense schedule in overseas regattas.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall in the 470 Olympic trials, Foerster and Merrick beat
1992 Olympic silver medalists Morgan Reeser and Kevin Burnham.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been three years of really, really hard work to get
enough ability to have a chance to win here,'' Foerster said. ''The
FD is a harder boat to sail, but the thing about the 470 is, when
it's easier to sail, that means you can have a lot more people that
are good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old Foerster, a mechanical engineer, has met big
challenges before. After enrolling at the University of Texas in
1983, he walked onto the sailing team. Even though he didn't come
up through a junior sailing program like most of the other team
members, he ended up a three-time All-American.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 0154 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
