<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Opposition Rejects Runoff  </HEADLINE>
By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav opposition leaders have
rebuffed President Slobodan Milosevic's claim that he earned enough
votes to force a runoff in presidential elections, pledging to
defend the will of the people by all means short of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic defied international and domestic appeals for him to
step down Tuesday, announcing a runoff election against opposition
leader Vojislav Kostunica, who insists he won Sunday's election
outright.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica quickly counterattacked, rejecting a runoff and
planning a massive rally Wednesday night in downtown Belgrade to
defend the results.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are talking about political fraud and blatant stealing of
votes,'' Kostunica said in a statement. ''This is an offer which
must be rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders demanded the chance to inspect the election
commission's returns and insisted on restraint after the federal
commission's volatile announcement, its first since the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The commission reported that Kostunica finished first with 48.22
percent while Milosevic earned 40.23 percent. Under Yugoslav law, a
runoff is required since none of the candidates received more than
50 percent. It was set for Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   State television said the turnout was 64 percent, far below the
74 percent figure given by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The runoff announcement came despite growing international calls
for Milosevic to accept an opposition victory.
</P>
<P>
   Even before it was declared, President Clinton insisted the will
of the people must be respected. The United States also pledged
Tuesday to lead an international campaign to pressure Milosevic
into accepting the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite the government's attempts to manipulate the vote, it
does seem clear that the people have voted for change,'' Clinton
said. ''The question is, will the government listen in response?''
</P>
<P>
   During a foreign policy address at Georgetown University in
Washington, Clinton dangled the possibility that ''the doors to
Europe and the world will be open again to Serbia,'' provided the
wishes of the people were taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   A runoff would be critical for Milosevic because it would give
him time to maneuver and create more favorable conditions for the
next round. It would also give him enough time to clamp down on
opposition media and activists and resume his nationalist campaign
portraying Kostunica as a ''NATO lackey and Western stooge.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica, a dour law professor who surprised Milosevic with his
widespread appeal, tried to cut off the Yugoslav strongman's means
of escape, declaring that there was ''no single reason, not moral
or political, by which we would accept such trampling on the
electoral will of the citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The victory is obvious and we will defend it by all nonviolent
means,'' he said. ''The people have given their political 'no' to
Milosevic and his policies. Our first duty is to carry out that
verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the opposition would, however, avoid ''careless moves
which could raise tensions in society, which could lead to
unforeseeable consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, opposition leader Zoran Djindjic demanded an urgent
session of the State Electoral Commission to inspect the official
returns, claiming the government had taken votes from Kostunica and
given them to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have no reason to respond nervously,'' Djindjic said. ''We
will demand to see the election material. We will copy them all,
compare and see where the votes went missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the commission releases partial returns and
Djindjic said earlier that the opposition feared the delay might be
aimed at giving the government time to fabricate bogus votes from
Kosovo, where the U.N. administrators permitted Serbs to vote.
</P>
<P>
   There had been fears of public unrest if the government sought
to claim a Milosevic victory or call a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   ''Milosevic has again proven that he is ready to do very nasty
things to stay in power,'' said Dragisa Burzan, a deputy prime
minister in Montenegro, the small republic that along with Serbia
forms Yugoslavia. ''It would be a fatal mistake for the opposition
if it accepted the runoff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
