<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Williams Will Have Olympic Medal  </HEADLINE>
By TIM DAHLBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Ricardo Williams Jr. will have an
Olympic medal to take home to his infant son, whose picture he
proudly tapes to his ankle before every fight.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to make it a nice shiny one for Ricardo Williams III.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't come for no bronze,'' Williams said. ''I came for a
gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams assured himself of at least a bronze medal Wednesday,
fighting his way into the 139-pound Olympic boxing semifinals with
a 17-12 win over Russia's Alexandre Leonov.
</P>
<P>
   He became only the second American boxer to reach the
semifinals, where he will face big punching Cuban Diogenes Luna on
Friday for the right to fight for Olympic gold.
</P>
<P>
   ''May the best man win,'' Williams said. ''I've trained too hard
for this. I don't want it to go down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams joined 119-pound teammate Clarence Vinson in the
semifinals, with two more Americans still with a chance to get into
the medal rounds Wednesday night. Earlier Wednesday, Jose Navarro's
Olympics came to an end when he lost to Jermone Thomas of France at
112 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to take a medal home like I dreamed of doing,''
Navarro said. ''But I'm going to learn from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams will be taking a medal home to Cincinnati and his
6-month-old son. He has fought through the Olympics with a picture
of his son sitting in front of an American flag taped to his left
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who might be the slickest boxer on the U.S. team, used
a big third round in which he landed a number of left hands to turn
a fight that had been tied early into the round into a 13-8
advantage. Williams was able to coast much of the last round,
ending the fight by dancing away from his Russian opponent for a
17-12 win.
</P>
<P>
   ''I fight best when I'm moving,'' Williams said. ''When I was
little, that was the first thing my father told me to do -- move,
move, move.''
</P>
<P>
   The win gave Williams a semifinal bout against Luna and a chance
to improve the 2-8 record American fighters have had against Cubans
in the last three Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to treat it like any other bout,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luna is one of six Cubans in the semifinals, with three others
yet to fight their quarterfinal bouts. Though Luna won Wednesday,
Cuban super heavyweight Alexis Rubalcaba was eliminated in perhaps
the most crowd-pleasing fight of the games by Mukhtarkhan
Dildabekov of Kazakstan.
</P>
<P>
   Dildabekov took three standing 8-counts from the massive Cuban,
but gave Rubalcaba two standing 8-counts of his own in brawling his
way to a 25-12 win.
</P>
<P>
   Luna, meanwhile, showed tremendous punching power in stopping
his Egyptian opponent with a right hand in the second round that
sent him reeling across the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Cuban boxers, though, Luna comes right at his
opponent. That may play into the plan of the left-handed Williams,
who likes to counterpunch off an opponent's miss.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to feed him a lot of lefts,'' Williams said.
''Aggressive guys are ones who take a lot of punches. I'm ready to
give a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Tom Mustin said the key for Williams will be to stay
away from Luna's right hand and stick to his game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got great punching power, but he can be hit fairly
easy,'' Mustin said of the Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   The win by Williams came several fights after Navarro lost a
23-12 decision to Thomas of France.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro was in the fight, losing 14-11, when the third round
apparently ended early. But he was dominated in the final round as
Thomas picked him apart with counterpunches as Navarro tried to be
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did my best,'' he said. ''I just had nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   After starting the Olympics with 11 straight wins, U.S. boxers
are now 18-7 overall, with one other boxer eliminated for not
making weight.
</P>
<P>
   The team will already fall short of the total medals of the 1996
team, which won one gold and five bronze in Atlanta. But Mustin
wasn't giving up hope.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not over yet,'' the U.S. coach said. ''If we can get the
rest of the these guys through it won't be a disappointment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
