<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Arrested For Throwing Bottle  </HEADLINE>
By BEN WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A pair of 22-year-old men were arrested at Shea
Stadium after a beer bottle landed near Atlanta Braves relief
pitcher John Rocker as he prepared to warm up.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Maniaci of Wyckoff, N.J., was accused of throwing the
bottle Tuesday night and charged with reckless endangerment, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also arrested was Maniaci's friend, Brian Peterson, 22, who
pleaded guilty in 1998 to manslaughter -- along with his girlfriend
-- in the death of their newborn son at a motel room in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, vilified by New Yorkers after disparaging them in a
magazine article last year, was loudly booed when he sprinted out
of the Braves bullpen in the eighth inning to face the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   As he approached the mound, a beer bottle came flying out of the
first-base box seats and hit about 10 feet from Rocker. Within a
minute, police were leading a man out of the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox picked up the bottle and carried it
toward the dugout, discarding it before he reached the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have anything to say,'' Rocker said after the Braves
beat the Mets 7-1 to clinch the NL East championship.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, also of Wyckoff, was charged with obstructing
governmental administration and disorderly conduct, police said.
The Mets confirmed Peterson was the same man involved in the 1996
infant death in Newark, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson was given a two-year sentence, six months shorter than
girlfriend Amy Grossberg's, after he agreed to testify against her.
Peterson was released from prison after serving 1&AMP;frac12; years and
Grossberg was released eight months early.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 0221 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
