<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beach Volleyball Said Changing  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- In an Olympic tournament of magic
moments for beach volleyball, one of the most enduring was a match
that had nothing to do with medals or glory.
</P>
<P>
   An injury forfeit by the Mexican men's team left a sellout crowd
at Bondi Beach stadium grumbling about the hour-long wait for the
next game.
</P>
<P>
   Americans Rob Heidger and Kevin Wong, who advanced without
hitting a ball, could have gone off to practice or have lunch.
Instead, Wong grabbed the stadium microphone and did what came
naturally -- he got a game going.
</P>
<P>
   Wong goaded NBC analyst Mike Dodd, a silver medalist at the
Atlanta Olympics, into donning an extra game uniform and taking the
court. Mexico's Juan Ibarra, whose Olympics had just ended because
of his partner's injury, stuck around to team with Dodd against
Wong and Heidger.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath a sun-filled blue sky, the four played for the fun of
it, leaping and diving in a friendly but inspired competition. The
crowd cheered and danced in a celebration of beach culture.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the essence of our sport, it's just four guys going out on
a beach with a ball,'' Wong said afterward. ''We all were once at
that stage where we weren't professionals. It's not that hard to
recreate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Other magic came from expected sources -- the celebrating that
greeted home favorites Natalie Cook and Kerri Pottharst's gold
medal in the women's competition; a flag-waving outburst when
Americans Dain Blanton and Eric Fonoimoana upset favored Brazilians
Ze Marco de Melo and Ricardo Santos for the men's gold; the
never-ending party by Brazilian fans, with pounding drums and
gyrating bodies, as their heroes won three of the six medals.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers got exactly what they wanted, with the high-profile
competition on a picturesque beach attracting more than 160,000
spectators over the 10 days of competition. One of NBC's signature
shots showed Pacific waves carrying surfers to the white sand
behind the 10,000-seat stadium where rock music blared and fans
clapped, stomped and sang the days away.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Acosta, president of the international volleyball
federation FIVB, said the 2001 beach volleyball world tour already
had commitments for $4 million in prize money, a boost over past
years due to the Olympic exposure.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, he said, the success of the Sydney tournament
convinced some skeptical International Olympic Committee members
that beach volleyball and its blatant promotion of audience
entertainment belonged in the games. IOC President Juan Antonio
Samaranch handed out the men's medals Tuesday, signaling that
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is something that only beach volleyball is bringing to
the Olympic spirit -- the joy for life,'' Acosta said.
</P>
<P>
   With growth comes change. Acosta announced the sport next year
would use rally scoring -- with a point awarded each time the ball
is put in play -- instead of the traditional side-out system in
which only the serving team can score.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the switch is television.
</P>
<P>
   Under rally scoring, the matches last an hour so that television
schedules remain intact. Side-out scoring can have long stretches
with no points, resulting in matches like the 80-minute
quarterfinal in which Brazil's Ze Marco de Melo and Ricardo Santos
ousted John Child and Mark Heese of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Players and others close to the game oppose the move, saying it
destroys fundamental elements of the beach game, such as the mental
toughness needed for prolonged side-out matches.
</P>
<P>
   By awarding a point for what is now siding out -- winning the
rally to regain the right to serve -- the rally system benefits
less-talented teams, said Gene Selznick, 70, a beach volleyball
legend from when the sport first became organized in southern
California after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ''You haven't earned anything that way. It's not competitive,''
Selznick said. ''I understand the television issue, but don't ruin
sports because of television.''
</P>
<P>
   Acosta said a final decision on which system to use would come
after 2001, but he signaled the likely result, noting indoor
volleyball already changed to rally scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are getting more interest from television around the world.
We are having more sponsors coming to volleyball,'' Acosta said.
''Then why should we let beach volleyball drown because they want
to keep playing side-out?''
</P>
<P>
   He called it part of an evolution, with rally scoring requiring
a different kind of player than those from the beach culture.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will not be possible to play the rally point system with
the same attitude or with the same type of players,'' he said. ''A
new type of players are coming. They have to be more aggressive,
accept challenges, and win over fear. They are a different type and
we like this type.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the new type would play for the fun of it to entertain
fans, like the old days on the beach, remains to be seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
