<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kolat Seeks Wrestling Gold  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Cary Kolat may be the best wrestler in
the world without a championship to prove it. He can't think of a
better stage to win that first gold medal than the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Kolat, one of the most decorated U.S. amateur wrestlers ever but
one who has known mostly bad luck -- or is it bad karma? -- in
world-class competition, wrestles his first match Thursday
(Wednesday night EDT).
</P>
<P>
   Also hitting the mats for the United States as Olympic wrestling
segues from Greco-Roman to freestyle are former world champion
Sammie Henson; Brandon Slay, the first Texan to make a U.S. Olympic
wrestling team; and Melvin Douglas, who, at 37, is nearly twice as
old as Greco-Roman medalist Garrett Lowney.
</P>
<P>
   Freestyle wrestling usually flies under the radar of sports-fan
detection in the United States, even in an Olympic year, yet it has
been one of the most consistent U.S. medal-producers, with 44 gold
medals and 99 medals overall.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite the optimistic forecasts of the three-man U.S.
head coaching staff (that's one head coach for every 2.667
wrestlers), the United States may have trouble matching its 1996
Atlanta haul of three gold medals and five medals.
</P>
<P>
   First, the 10 weight classes have been cut to eight, reducing
the opportunities for medals. Second, the three 1996 gold medalists
-- Kurt Angle, Tom Brands and Kendall Cross -- have retired, at least
from amateur wrestling. (Angle can be seen in Australia, but only
on late-night telecasts of WWF matches from the United States.)
</P>
<P>
   Also, several Americans are at weights in which dominating
wrestlers have emerged since Atlanta, including 167&AMP;frac12; pounds, where
Slay contends with three-time world champion Buvaisa Saitiev of
Russia, and 213&AMP;frac34; pounds, where Douglas, seventh in Atlanta at a
lighter weight class, replaces the more successful Angle.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I think it's exciting being on this team,'' said Kolat,
who might be the top U.S. gold-medal hope. ''I think the U.S. team
is a bad draw for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolat can become the fourth consecutive American to win at 138&AMP;frac34;
pounds (63 kg), joining Randy Lewis (1984); John Smith (1988-1992),
now one of the U.S. tri-coaches; and Tom Brands (1996), whose
brother, Terry, wrestles Friday at 127&AMP;frac34; pounds (58 kg).
</P>
<P>
   ''Cary is the best wrestler in the world right now,'' said West
Virginia assistant coach Zeke Jones, who is working with Kolat in
Sydney. ''Nobody has been as consistent as him.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, it would seem, as star-crossed.
</P>
<P>
   Kolat, so renowned as a high school wrestler that his name is on
the road sign leading into tiny Rices Landing, Pa., finished
second, third and fourth in the last three world championships.
Twice in those three years, he was stripped of victories he won on
the mat.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the appeals and protests that led to those two
reversals, Kolat is personally responsible for two international
rule changes.
</P>
<P>
   Following a 1997 loss in which an opponent gained advantage by
untying his own shoes on the mat, wrestlers now must tape their
shoes. Also, all protested matches now are re-wrestled, rather than
the decision being awarded to the protesting wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   Kolat, now 27 and a former two-time NCAA champion at Lock Haven,
said Sydney affords the perfect opportunity to make up for those
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't intend to be the guy that people say should have been
or could have been,'' Kolat said.
</P>
<P>
   Henson, also a two-time NCAA champion at Clemson, was a 1998
world champion who had an uneven 1999 season at 119 pounds (54 kg).
A different wrestler has won the world championship at the weight
the last three years, so there is no overwhelming favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am working very hard to eliminate technical mistakes and
turn it into perfection,'' Henson said. ''Perfection equals a gold
medal. I won't be shy. I want to win this thing with all of my
heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
