<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Coach Has Sydney Presence  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN LEICESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Even from thousands of miles away in
China, the famed coach who pushed Chinese runners to world record
times is still having a hand in the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   Excluded from the Olympics after six of his runners failed drug
tests, Ma Junren was still at trackside Wednesday in virtual form,
following the progress of his last remaining Olympic competitor by
telephone as she qualified for the final of the women's 10,000
meters.
</P>
<P>
   Ma and Chinese sports official Cui Dalin kept an open line
throughout much of the race. Cui relayed back split times and the
track position of runner Li Ji as the race progressed and shouted
commands to her on nearly every lap.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's running normally, she's following the runner in front,''
Cui told Ma by mobile telephone as the race neared its end.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's off!'' he suddenly added as Li picked up her pace on the
last lap. The 19-year-old placed sixth in 32 minutes, 28.96
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Ma's telephonic presence was the latest bizarre twist in his
on-again, off-again Olympic saga.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese sports officials left Ma and his runners out of the 1998
Asian Games after he refused to put them through qualifying. But
after a dismal showing in long- and middle-distance events by China
at those games, they brought Ma back for the Olympics in hopes of
reviving the nation's saging fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 10 days before the start of Olympic competition, China
announced that it was cutting 27 athletes from its team, among them
six of the seven runners Ma had been expected to take to Sydney. Ma
too was cut, leaving only his runner Li in the squad.
</P>
<P>
   China's track and field association said all six of the runners,
among them a former 5,000-meter world record holder, had failed
blood tests that checked for the banned performance-enhancing drug
EPO, or erthyropoietin.
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese Olympic Committee spokeswoman, He Huixian, also
confirmed that ''the overwhelming majority'' of the dropped 27
athletes had suspicious EPO blood test results, but refused to
provide a breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Ma and his runners, meanwhile, suddenly left the high-altitude
camp on the Tibetan plateau where they had been training for the
Olympics, Chinese media said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cui, head of sports in the northern Chinese province of
Liaoning, where Ma has his training center, denied that the
runners' tests had shown elevated red blood cell counts, a possible
sign of EPO use.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are many reasons'' for the runners absence, he said,
refusing to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether they come or not is very normal. There are many major
competitions, whether it be the Olympics, the World Championships,
or the World Cup,'' Cui added. ''Some they take part in, others
they don't. It depends on the situation of Ma and his runners and
all sorts of reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Cui said Ma was back in Liaoning, but is not in good health.
</P>
<P>
   Ma's crew of long- and middle-distance women runners, known as
''Ma's army,'' stunned the sports world with a slew of world
records in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The chain-smoking, gravel-voiced coach attributed their success
to his regimen of daily marathons and tonics of Chinese caterpillar
fungus, worm and turtle soup. He denied suggestions of doping.
</P>
<P>
   Li's personal best for the 10,000 meters is 32:14.97, minutes
behind the world record of 29:31.78 held by another of Ma's former
runners, Wang Junxia, who shattered the record in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Cui denied that Ma was directing Li's race from afar. ''He was
not giving any help. I was just telling him the times, how fast she
had run 1,000 meters, 2,000 meters,'' said Cui.
</P>
<P>
   But after tele-conferring with Ma as Li was running on the far
side of the track, Cui would jump to his feet as she ran past his
stand and shout commands.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pay attention to your pace,'' he said on one lap. ''Just run
with her, that's fine,'' he said on another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
