<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Basketball Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By JIM O'CONNELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Australia went outside to dominate
inside.
</P>
<P>
   With centers Jenny Whittle and Lauren Jackson combining for five
3-pointers, Australia advanced to the women's Olympic basketball
semifinals with a 76-48 victory over Poland and 7-foot-2 Margo
Dydek on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The first four field goals of the game for Australia (6-0) were
a jumper by the 6-5 Jackson and three 3-pointers by the 6-6
Whittle, matching her total for the tournament. When forward Carla
Boyd hit a 3 with 15:27 left in the first half, the home country
had a 16-4 lead and Dydek had been negated as an inside force.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew I was going to get a chance to shoot a lot of 3s
because Dydek doesn't like to come out. So I knew I had to be on
target tonight,'' Whittle said.
</P>
<P>
   Australia, which will play the winner of the Brazil-Russia
quarterfinal in the semifinals, has gotten this far in the Olympics
twice -- 1988, when it finished fourth, and 1996, when it won the
bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't be any more excited than we are about making the
semifinals,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dydek, who plays for the WNBA's Utah Starzz, entered the
quarterfinals as the tournament's leading scorer (22.0), rebounder
(12.2) and shot blocker (3.0).
</P>
<P>
   Her numbers against Australia were 12 points on 5-for-15
shooting, 12 rebounds and one blocked shot.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought our two bigs did a fantastic job on Dydek,''
Australia coach Tom Maher said. ''We got a lot of open shots and
played a lot of good defense. A coach would have to be stupid to
say he's not pleased with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson finished with 17 points and nine rebounds, while Whittle
had 16 points and seven rebounds. Whittle was 4-for-6 from 3-point
range; Jackson was 1-for-3 on 3s and had six blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We knew we had to play hard against Margo and we did,''
Jackson said. ''Really, we did what we've been doing all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia pulled away from a 43-28 halftime lead, again using
long jumpers as Whittle hit a 3 and another shot where her foot was
on the line as part of an 11-4 opening run.
</P>
<P>
   Elzbieta Trzesniewska also had 12 points for Poland (3-3), which
was making its first Olympic appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ''We came here hoping to win a medal and now that won't
happen,'' Trzesniewska said. ''Maybe people didn't think so, but we
showed we could be able to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
