<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ivorian Junta Boss Isolated  </HEADLINE>
By GLENN McKENZIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- Nine months after Ivory Coast's
first coup, junta boss Gen. Robert Guei is increasingly isolated
among African leaders and beleaguered at home by a simmering ethnic
and political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of a visit by a delegation of influential African
presidents looking for peaceful solutions to a political crisis
that threatens war, Guei rejected outside interference Tuesday and
said Ivorians could manage their own problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of the chiefs of state who came can impose what must be
in Ivory Coast,'' Guei told a throng of 300 supporters outside
presidential offices in the main city of Abidjan. ''We have all the
solutions to all our problems.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments seemed likely to fuel concerns of mounting
instability in Ivory Coast, long a West African economic powerhouse
and financial center in a region fraught by civil wars and
instability.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Nigeria's President Olusegun Obasanjo warned that
Guei, who is standing in elections set for Oct. 22, could not be
both ''umpire and player'' in the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Simmering xenophobia and ethnic tensions have contributed to the
political crisis, which centers around concerns over whether Guei's
main rival Alassane Dramane Ouattara should be allowed to stand
against the military leader in presidential elections set for Oct.
22.
</P>
<P>
   The regime has suggested Ouattara may be ineligible under a new
constitutional provision because at least one of Ouattara's parents
was born in Burkina Faso. Ouattara, a northerner in a political
arena long dominated by southerners, insists both his parents were
Ivorian-born.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting African delegation, which also included the
presidents of regional powerhouses South Africa and Algeria,
proposed that all candidates be allowed to run.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of placard-waving Guei supporters who were campaigning
Tuesday in front of the presidential offices rejected that
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We say 'no' to foreigners in our country,'' said Stanislas
Tape, starting a similar chant among the crowd. Some among the
crowd chanted anti-foreigner slogans and angrily denounced the
African delegation for alleged meddling in Ivorian affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Guei thanked the crowd for showing their ''patriotism'' and
called on them to remain calm.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's show of support for Guei came despite a junta ban on
political gatherings. The supporters said they were members of a
study group.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's mission by Guei's fellow African leaders represented
unusually quick and concerted action by the normally conservative
Organization of African Unity. The OAU has long defended the
sovereignty of individual members.
</P>
<P>
   But leaders like South Africa's Thabo Mbeki and Nigeria's
Obasanjo have grown increasingly concerned that political upheaval
across the continent is hindering economic investment and growth.
</P>
<P>
   The trip also underscored African concerns that any conflict in
Ivory Coast could spill over into neighboring countries and deprive
the region of its economic engine.
</P>
<P>
   Guei insisted that Ivory Coast was a ''nation of peace'' that
would solve its own problems.
</P>
<P>
   Yet since taking power in a Dec. 24 coup d'etat that toppled
Henri Konan Bedie, Guei's junta has already weathered two mutinies
and a shooting last week that Guei said was a failed attempt on his
life. Dozens of soldiers were subsequently arrested.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, military officials claimed that two deposed members
of Guei's junta were on the run after the military seized a cache
of weapons from one of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Lassana Palenfo and Brig. Gen. Abdoulaye Coulibaly were
second and third in command, respectively, under Guei. They were
ejected from the junta last week in the wake of the alleged
assassination attempt. They are both from the north -- the base of
support for Ouattara's Rally of the Republicans party.
</P>
<P>
   Many supporters of Ouattara, a former International Monetary
Fund deputy managing director and prime minister, are fearful the
junta is planning a move against him and have surrounded his home
to protect it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
