<HEADLINE> Ministers Discuss N.Korean Food Aid  </HEADLINE>
By JAE-SUK YOO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEJU, South Korea (AP) -- A high-level government delegation
from North Korea arrived Wednesday to discuss improving ties with
South Korea and plans to send food aid to the hunger-stricken
communist North.
</P>
<P>
   The chief North Korean negotiator, Jon Kum Jin, flew to South
Korea via Beijing because there are no direct air links between the
Koreas. After a brief stopover at the Seoul airport, the Northern
delegation flew to the Southern resort island of Cheju.
</P>
<P>
   Jon's meeting with South Korean Unification Minister Park
Jae-kyu comes amid North Korean warnings that it will face a
seventh consecutive year of acute food shortages next year because
its farm industry was again devastated by bad weather this year.
</P>
<P>
   In August, North Korea asked the South to provide up to 1
million tons of grain in food loans. South Korean officials have
said they will announce their food aid plan within the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
   Park said the two Koreas have already completed negotiations on
food aid and the government was persuading political parties to
support new food shipments to the North.
</P>
<P>
   All major South Korean dailies, quoting unidentified government
sources, reported Wednesday that South Korea will buy 500,000 to
600,000 tons of Thai rice and Chinese corn at a cost of $100
million and began shipping the food to North Korea in October.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition lawmakers have accused President Kim Dae-jung of
pampering the communist regime in Pyongyang with massive food aid
at a time of economic uncertainty at home.
</P>
<P>
   They suspect the North of diverting outside food aid to its 1.1
million-strong military.
</P>
<P>
   Park and Jon planned to hold two days of official talks on
Thursday and Friday to follow up on an accord reached at a historic
summit in June. At that meeting, their countries' leaders pledged
to work together to promote peace and reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1990s, up to 2 million North Koreans have died of
starvation, according to U.S. officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
