<HEADLINE> 8 Cops Die in Maoist Rebel Attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) -- Maoist rebels ambushed a police patrol in
a remote village in Nepal on Wednesday, killing eight policemen.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-member patrol was scouting the area near Ghoretar village
when it was attacked, police said. A special police team was sent
in to investigate the assault, which took place about 125 miles
west of the capital, Katmandu.
</P>
<P>
   The patrol was ambushed two days after the rebels attacked a
police station in Dunai, 200 miles northwest of Katmandu, killing
at least 14 policemen and wounding 36 others.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Maoist rebels began their campaign four years ago,
they have killed at least 231 policemen and lost 979 of their own
fighters and supporters, the government says. In addition, 249
civilians have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are demanding an end to Nepal's constitutional
monarchy. They also allege police repression.
</P>
</TEXT>
