<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Open Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher Wednesday as the market
struggled to rebound from a selloff prompted by increasing concerns
about corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain hunting helped push the market higher, but it wasn't
clear how long-lived the gains would be. The market has spent much
of the month in a decline, reflecting uncertainty about how the
moderating economy will affect third-quarter results.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading, the Dow Jones industrial average
was up 27.47 at 10,658.79 after falling 176 points on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite rose
58.97 to 3,748.07 and the Standard and Poor's 500 stock-index
climbed 8.07 to 1,435.28.
</P>
<P>
   With third-quarter earnings reporting season less than two weeks
away, investors have been unloading stocks whose companies even
warn of lower-than-expected profits.
</P>
<P>
   The market has swung up and down, as investors, unsure where to
put their money, move in and out of technology and blue chip
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Micron Technology rose $2.50 to $49.56.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems was up $1.75 at $119.25.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft appeared to rebound for a second day, up 69 cents at
$63.38. On Tuesday, the U.S. Supreme Court said the software
company's appeal of a federal judge's decision to split the company
should be heard by a federal appeals court first. The Justice
Department had wanted the Supreme Court to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 3.17 at 513.06.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.81 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.04 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 rose 1.36 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.86 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
