<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The markets were mixed Wednesday as investors
concerned about corporate profits again sold off stocks of poor
performers.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain hunting helped push technology issues somewhat higher,
but it wasn't clear how long-lived the gains would be. The market
has spent much of the month in a decline, reflecting uncertainty
about how the moderating economy will affect third-quarter results.
</P>
<P>
   After advancing in the opening minutes of trading, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 16.28 at 10,615.04 in the first hour of
trading. It fell 176 points on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 4.75 at 1,431.96, and the
tech-focused Nasdaq composite index rose 47.13 to 3,736.23.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the market has been fixated on the approach of
third-quarter results. Increasing indications that the economy is
slowing, combined with high energy prices and Europe's weak
currency, have many investors looking to the third-quarter as a
sign of what is to come for many companies.
</P>
<P>
   A stronger-than-expected earnings report helped push 3Com up
$3.25 to $17.44 on the Nasdaq. The computer networking company
posted a first quarter loss of $59.2 million Tuesday but fared
better than Wall Street had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose $1.63 to $44.94, as the chipmaker struggled to
rebound from a slump that began Friday when it warned of
disappointing profits.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems also rallied, rising $3.06 to $120.56 after
ending Tuesday down.
</P>
<P>
   Corning announced it was buying part of the fiber optic
operations of Pirelli, an Italian company. The announcement sent
Corning down $8.75 to $316.25.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly a 5-to-3 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 135.87 million
shares, barely ahead of the 135.51 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 3.70 at 513.59.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.81 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.04 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 rose 1.36 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.86 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
