<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Dismisses Yugoslav Runoff  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton dismissed Yugoslav
government plans for a run-off election Wednesday as an apparent
attempt to steal a fair election.
</P>
<P>
   ''It certainly appears from a distance that they had a free
election and somebody's trying to take it away from them,'' Clinton
said at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Belgrade called a runoff election for Oct. 8 on
grounds no clear winner emerged from Sunday's balloting.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government's official election commission has no
credibility whatever,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Election Commission in Belgrade announced that
opposition presidential candidate Vojislav Kostunica finished first
in the voting but without enough votes to avoid a runoff with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said Kostunica finished with 48.22 percent to
40.23 percent for Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ''The opposition clearly believes it got over 50 percent,'' and
independent observers agree, Clinton said before leaving Washington
for fund-raising appearances in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that Kostunica does not plan to participate in a
runoff, but did not say what if anything the United States might do
to bolster Kostunica's position.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what Europe and the United States should do is support
the expressed will of the Serbian people,'' Clinton said, adding
later: ''Whatever we do should be consistent, I think, with the
wishes of the majority of the people there.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton said it seemed clear that Milosevic lost the
election ''despite government attempts to manipulate the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told a Senate committee
Tuesday that the authorities in Belgrade ''have used every trick in
the book to prevent a fair campaign, rig the election and distort
the results. In so doing, they have fooled no one.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly now, Milosevic is a figure of the past,'' Albright
said. ''For too long, his lawlessness has weakened Yugoslavia; his
cronies have robbed Yugoslavia; and his mismanagement has all but
bankrupted Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Election Commission statement:
http://www.gov.yu/e2000/index.html
</P>
<P>
   State Department:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/eur/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Albright's comments to Senate Foreign Relations Committee:
http://secretary.state.gov/www/statements/2000/000926.html
</P>
</TEXT>
