<HEADLINE> Commander Killed in Burundi Fighting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) -- A senior Burundi military commander
was killed in fighting between the Tutsi-dominated army and Hutu
rebels, an independent radio station said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Audace Basuzuguye was killed and at least nine soldiers
wounded during the fighting Tuesday near the village of Tenga,
seven miles northwest of the capital, Bujumbura, Radio Umwizero
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been important casualties on the rebels' side and
some on our side,'' military spokesman Maj. Edward Ntibigira told
The Associated Press. ''Fighting continues, and we have seized a
lot of weapons. We can no longer tolerate attacks near the
capital.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not have the exact number of casualties and could
not confirm whether Basuzuguye was among them. He said the army
would issue a statement later.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people, mostly civilians, have been killed
since civil war broke out in the tiny central African country in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   The war began when Tutsi paratroopers assassinated the country's
first democratically elected president, a Hutu.
</P>
<P>
   Two years of peace talks ended Aug. 28 with a power-sharing
agreement between Hutu and Tutsi political parties and the
government of President Pierre Buyoya. But the two main Hutu rebel
groups have refused to accept the agreement, and they and the
government have refused to sign a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The parties were meeting in Arusha, Tanzania this week to
determine how to implement the agreement as the violence continued
to escalate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1053 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
