<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Group GRAPO Blamed for Bombs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- An underground group known as GRAPO
exploded small homemade bombs Wednesday in temporary employment
agencies in three Spanish provincial capitals, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A caller in the name of the anarchist group claimed
responsibility for the attacks in Vigo, Seville and Valencia, which
caused minor damage and no injuries, police said.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, six similar attacks, also blamed on GRAPO,
struck temporary employment agencies in Madrid, Barcelona and
Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   GRAPO -- a Spanish acronym for October First Anti-fascist
Resistance Group -- has been blamed for other attacks on temporary
employment agencies in recent years. Police say they don't know why
employment agencies are targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Torres Hurtado, the central government's representative in
Seville, speculated the attacks Wednesday were to show support for
demonstrations against economic globalization in Prague at the
World Bank and IMF meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But the explosions also come on the 25th anniversary of the last
capital punishments in Spanish history.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 27, 1975, Spanish leader Gen. Francisco Franco ordered
the execution by firing squad of two members of the violent Basque
separatist group ETA and three members of FRAP, the anti-fascist
predecessors of GRAPO.
</P>
<P>
   GRAPO is associated with left-wing political movements, but its
political aims have never been clear.
</P>
<P>
   The group is thought to be behind the deaths of some 60 people
in bombing and shooting attacks over the last 25 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
