<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freeh, Reno Defend Government's Case  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal prosecutors had a choice: take
scientist Wen Ho Lee to court and risk nuclear weapon secrets or
give him a deal that would force him to tell what he did with the
information he downloaded on computer tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was clear-cut, FBI Director Louis Freeh said.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the moment we learned last year that our nation's nuclear
secrets were on missing portable tapes, we have had a central goal
in this matter: to find out what happened to the tapes,'' Freeh
told a Senate hearing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And, Attorney General Janet Reno said, ''This plea agreement is
our best chance to find out what happened to the computer tapes
containing some of the nation's most important nuclear designs.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Freeh defended the government's investigation and
treatment of Lee, who was held in solitary confinement without bail
for nine months before being released on a plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, their subordinates insisted at a Senate Judiciary
subcommittee hearing that the plea bargain to find the tapes was
the only choice. ''The answers were more important than prosecuting
Dr. Lee for his admittedly very serious crimes,'' Assistant
Attorney General James Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers had even threatened prosecutors with forcing a
trial, promising a ''long slow death march'' toward publicity on
the nuclear secrets, said U.S. Attorney Norman Bay of Albuquerque,
N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ''If someone had told me they were going to put me on a long
slow death march, I would have told them, 'Let's start walking,'''
said Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., a former prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe you,'' Bay replied, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Lee pleaded guilty to only one of the 59 counts of his grand
jury indictment. In exchange, he was sentenced to time served and
agreed to tell officials what happened to the information he
downloaded at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was not at the hearing. In a statement, his lawyers said
they wanted fair treatment for him from the government, and the
scientist hopes in time ''the world will better understand that he
has been and continues to be a loyal and proud citizen of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Dr. Lee is no hero,'' Reno said, rejecting his widespread
portrayal as a victim. ''He is no absent-minded professor. He is a
felon. He committed a very serious, calculated crime, and he pled
guilty to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The plea bargain, however, prompted U.S. District Judge James
Parker to apologize to Lee for the nine-month pretrial imprisonment
and to accuse government officials in charge of the case of
embarrassing ''our entire nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers at Tuesday's hearing also found much to complain
about.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe the FBI's counterintelligence investigation was a
gravely flawed exercise, characterized by inadequate resources,
lack of management attention and missed opportunities,'' the Senate
Intelligence Committee chairman, Richard Shelby, R-Ala., said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a textbook example of how not to conduct an
investigation,'' added Sen. Richard Bryan of Nevada, top Democrat
on Shelby's committee. He called it a ''Keystone Kops'' operation.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's supporters also contend the fired Los Alamos scientist, a
U.S. citizen born in Taiwan and educated in the United States, was
targeted because he is Asian-American. Some are demanding a
presidential pardon and an apology.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has refused to apologize but has ordered an internal review
of Justice Department actions. She and Freeh deny, however, that
Lee was targeted because he is Asian-American.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is critical to understand that Dr. Lee's conduct was not
inadvertent, it was not careless and it was not innocent,'' Freeh
said.
</P>
<P>
   Convicting Lee likely would have required revealing those
secrets in court to prove their importance, Freeh said, ''crossing
an exposure threshold we had already determined at the highest
level of government posed an unacceptable risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI director did acknowledge the agents who interrogated Lee
should not have reminded him that Julius and Ethel Rosenberg were
executed in the 1950s for espionage. ''Confrontational interviews
often call for tough statements by investigators, but that
implication was inappropriate,'' he said. Lee was never charged
with espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., asked Reno to appoint an
independent investigator, saying Congress and the Justice
Department are too close to the matter to be perceived as being
fair.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Energy Department: http://www.doe.gov
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department: http://www.usdoj.gov/
</P>
<P>
   FBI: http://www.fbi.gov
</P>
<P>
   Senate Select Committee on Intelligence:
http://intelligence.senate.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee: http://judiciary.senate.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
