<DOCNO> APW20000927.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auditor Independence A Key Issue  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Accountants are on the ramparts, with the Big
Five firms bitterly split. A parade of corporate leaders have
trooped through hearing rooms. Sympathetic lawmakers are pocketing
millions in donations from auditing firms this political season.
</P>
<P>
   It's all because of a proposal by the Securities and Exchange
Commission designed to keep accountants independent from companies
they audit. SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt, besieged over the issue,
says it is critical for ordinary investors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing less than the public interest is at stake,'' he said
in an interview. ''If investors cannot trust the sanctity of the
numbers, our markets lose their credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt has tangled with contentious issues for more than seven
years as head of the watchdog agency amid a booming stock market.
The SEC proposal would impose new limits on the kinds of consulting
services that accounting firms can provide their clients. ''I don't
think I've faced an issue which is of greater importance to
American investors,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When he testifies before Congress on the proposal Thursday he
likely will face heavy opposition. The chairman of the Senate
Banking Committee, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and its No. 2
Republican, Sen. Richard Shelby of Alabama, have complained to
Levitt in a letter that the proposed SEC rules would ''force
dramatic changes in the structure and business practices of
accounting firms'' and require corporations ''to pay increased
costs for some types of accounting services.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one Republican members of Congress have signed another
letter accusing Levitt of rushing the proposal through before a new
administration takes office next year.
</P>
<P>
   And the Banking Committee's chief economist, John Silvia, has
told the SEC its cost-benefit analysis of the proposal is ''wholly
inadequate given the significant impact the rule may have on the
U.S. economy.'' The proposed rules would bring more than $100
million in compliance and restructuring costs for the accounting
industry, Silvia said.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting industry, meanwhile, has contributed $6.9 million
to presidential, House and Senate candidates this election cycle,
including $4.1 million to incumbents, according to data compiled by
the Center for Responsive Politics. Nearly twice as much has gone
to Republicans as to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Among the top 20 recipients are Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn.,
chairman of the Senate Banking subcommittee on securities
($56,348); GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush (about $1
million); Democratic contender Al Gore ($354,050); Hillary Rodham
Clinton ($73,500); and her Republican rival in the New York Senate
race, Rep. Rick Lazio ($87,786). Gramm, who was not in the top
group, received $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in the midst of an election season and that's when
political pressure becomes the greatest,'' Levitt, a major
Clinton-Gore fund-raiser before joining the government, replied
when asked about the lobbying clout. ''The fact that enormous sums
of money have been spent on lobbying this issue is irrelevant'' to
the importance of auditor independence to protect investors, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt and other SEC officials are worried that accounting firms
are jeopardizing their independence by becoming more financially
dependent on the lucrative consulting work they do for companies
they audit. They say accounting firms need to be more independent
of their clients to avoid conflicts of interest and preserve the
integrity of company financial reports -- thereby upholding
investors' confidence in the stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of some big accounting firms and the industry's
trade group, the American Institute of Certified Public
Accountants, say the rules would bring an undesirable restructuring
of their industry by forcing firms to split off their valuable
consulting businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Securities and Exchange Commission: http://www.sec.gov
</P>
<P>
   American Institute of Certified Public Accountants:
http://www.aicpa.org
</P>
<P>
   Center for Responsive Politics: http://www.opensecrets.org
</P>
<P>
   Senate Banking Committee: http://www.senate.gov/committees
</P>
</TEXT>
