<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trying To Reawaken Regional Theater  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- When Nicholas Martin first walked into the
Huntington Theatre five years ago to see his friend Campbell Scott
play Hamlet, he remembers being struck by the stately if ramshackle
playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ''The building said 'theater' to me,'' says Martin. ''It had
real reverberation, like the Broadway theaters of my youth when I
first saw Ethel Merman and shows like 'Oklahoma!'''
</P>
<P>
   Now Martin has been given the chance to make other people notice
not only the building's special ambiance, but the Huntington
Theatre Company itself. As its new artistic director, Martin has
the formidable task of reawakening the slumbering regional theater
affiliated with Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a generation, the Huntington has had a minimal
national profile in a city that takes its culture very seriously.
The red-brick building borders the Fenway, a park-like area near
the Charles River, and its illustrious neighbors include Symphony
Hall and the Museum of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowed by the arty, ambitious American Repertory Theatre
across the Charles in Cambridge, the Huntington, if it was known at
all, was recognized outside of Boston for its stolid productions of
English and Irish playwrights as well as one of the stops on the
circuit that August Wilson's plays took in their journeys to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   That could change now that Martin has taken over from Peter
Altman, who left to run the Missouri Repertory Theatre in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-September, Martin opened his first season with a bang: a
production he directed of Sidney Kingsley's rarely revived 1935
social drama, ''Dead End,'' with a large cast of more than 40
actors. Boston critics threw around such adjectives as
''triumphant,'' ''breathtaking'' and ''stunning'' in describing
Martin's production, which has been extended an extra week, through
Oct. 15, because of the rave reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a 62-year-old, one-time actor who didn't
professionally direct his first play until nine years ago -- an
off-Broadway drama called ''Sophistry'' that featured a cast of
little-known performers including Ethan Hawke, Calista Flockhart
and Steve Zahn.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of winding down to retirement, the ebullient Martin is
winding up and facing a new career.
</P>
<P>
   ''Arthur Laurents said to me, 'Aren't you doing this
backwards?''' Martin says with a laugh, referring to a career that
is getting busier the older he gets.
</P>
<P>
   Born Joel Martin Levinson, Martin is a New Yorker, by way of
Brooklyn and New Jersey and back again. ''My parents were
middle-class Jewish people, who took me to the theater, including
the original 'Oklahoma!'''
</P>
<P>
   He spent his youth as an actor. Hence the stage name Nicholas
Martin, although everyone calls him ''Nicky,'' which more than
suits his impish sense of humor, large laugh and compact,
5-foot-5&AMP;frac12;-inch frame.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made a living most of the time, but took off seven to 10
years to be a drunk and then got some help -- and you can say
that,'' he instructs a visitor with disarming directness.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his early acting career was with APA-Phoenix, the
legendary troupe headed by director Ellis Rabb that featured such
performers as Helen Hayes, Rosemary Harris and Donald Moffat.
Later, Martin did regional theater, primarily in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a kid who should have been a musical comedy person. I
sang, but then I fell in love with Shakespeare and with the advent
of blank verse, my singing voice evaporated and I became this
little classical actor -- which was good because I was too odd to
have had a mainstream career.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin credits actor Victor Garber, best-known for his roles in
''Art,'' ''Sweeney Todd'' and ''Assassins,'' with jump-starting his
career as a professional director in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Martin had worked out a comfortable life teaching in
the fall and winter in colleges, doing shows with the students and
then acting in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   It was Garber who told Don Scardino, then head of off-Broadway's
Playwrights Horizons, that he should hire Martin as associate
artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   As Martin tells it, he first declined Scardino's offer, but then
Garber sat him down and said, ''First of all, you want to direct
professionally, and Don will let you do that. The other thing is:
I've heard you stand in front of your classes and say, 'The theater
as I knew it is dead, and it's up to you kids to bring it back to
life.' This is your chance to bring it back to life, and if you
don't do it you're a hypocrite.'
</P>
<P>
   ''There was nothing I could do,'' Martin concluded. ''So it
really is to Victor more than anyone else that I owe my directing
career and my success.''
</P>
<P>
   That success first registered on the New York radar screen in
1997 with his production of ''Full Gallop,'' Mary Louise Wilson's
tour de force impersonation of fashion maven Diana Vreeland.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same year Martin also first directed ''Dead End,'' in
a memorable production at the Williamstown Theatre Festival in
western Massachusetts. Martin's relationship with Williamstown has
been particularly fruitful. Since ''Dead End,'' he has gone on to
do acclaimed productions there of ''Camino Real'' by Tennessee
Williams and ''Hedda Gabler'' with Kate Burton as Ibsen's heroine.
</P>
<P>
   Actors delight in his deceptively easygoing manner.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nicky makes you feel that you already know how to play the
part,'' says Blair Brown, who appeared in his ''Camino Real.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He fills you with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Martin, ''Collaboration is everything to me. All directors
say that, but I mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet behind the charm and support, according to Brown, you know
Martin has worked the hardest of all, carefully researching each
play he is about to direct.
</P>
<P>
   What made Martin take the job in Boston -- just as his career in
New York solidified with such off-Broadway successes as ''Betty's
Summer Vacation,'' by Christopher Durang, and the one-man ''Fully
Committed'' and the Lincoln Center revival of Laurents' ''The Time
of the Cuckoo''?
</P>
<P>
   ''A couple of things. First of all, I can't resist a challenge
of any kind. The bigger the better,'' Martin says.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the dithering over what to do with ''Betty's
Summer Vacation,'' a black comedy that received excellent reviews,
but never was able to transfer for a commercial run, primarily
because, among other things, a suitable off-Broadway theater
couldn't be found. Martin found it frustrating -- and discouraging --
waiting for producers to produce results.
</P>
<P>
   ''At least now I can produce the plays I want and the writers I
want,'' he says, talking of his inaugural effort for the theater's
18,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This season sort of arranged itself,'' he says, in explaining
how he and the theater's veteran managing director, Michael Masso,
put the schedule together. ''It's not like we sat down and said,
'We'll do a classic and an English play and a black play.' It just
happened. The best seasons evolve in a mysterious way that isn't
programmatic.''
</P>
<P>
   How else to describe a mix that also includes ''A Fair
Country,'' a family drama set in South Africa, written by Jon Robin
Baitz, a young playwright little seen in Boston; an obscure Moliere
comedy, ''Amphityron'' in a new translation by Richard Wilbur; Tom
Stoppard's take on poet A.E. Housman in ''The Invention of Love'';
and another rarely seen play, James Baldwin's ''The Amen Corner,''
produced in association with Chicago's Goodman Theater.
</P>
<P>
   As a bonus, the season also includes ''Fully Committed,'' with
its original New York star, Mark Setlock, and directed by Martin.
The play, written by Becky Mode, looks at the frenzied world of a
telephone reservation clerk at one of New York's hottest
restaurants, with Setlock playing all the roles.
</P>
<P>
   As for next season and beyond?
</P>
<P>
   Martin has plans to bring ''Betty's Summer Vacation'' to Boston
during the 2001-2002 season. And he dreams of getting the use of
two more theaters in the nearby South End. One would be a 350-seat
proscenium house for new plays and the other a tiny 99-seat black
box that would be given to other local companies most of the year,
but which the Huntington would use occasionally for one-person
shows and to develop works.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I had my way, I would make a triangular arrangement between
Lincoln Center Theater in New York, the Williamstown Theatre
Festival and the Huntington,'' Martin says, of the three venues
where he has had the most success.
</P>
<P>
   Even with his busy schedule in Boston, he will return to New
York late next spring to direct a new play at Lincoln Center by
John Guare called ''Chaucer in Rome'' about three Americans in the
Eternal City at the end of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if it is an achievement but the thing that I
think is remarkable about me is that I have proven that it is never
too late,'' Martin says. ''You can go into your 50s and 60s and
completely change your life.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the net:
</P>
<P>
   http//:huntingtontheatre.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
