<DOCNO> APW20000927.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jayhawks Forced to Live in Past  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For a rock 'n' roll band with a compelling
present and promising future, the Jayhawks are forced to spend an
awful lot of time in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks led the alternative country movement that was a
counterpoint to grunge in the early 1990s. Yet when they never
became a big success, their debt-ridden saga was often cited by
writers as a metaphor for what's wrong with the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when co-leader Mark Olson quit in 1995 and the
Minneapolis-based band decided to carry on without him, the
decision splintered their loyal fans and became a subject for
near-endless debate.
</P>
<P>
   All irresistible fodder. Yet it would be a shame if these
stories overshadowed ''Smile,'' the band's most recent and -- get
ready for a fight -- best album.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times called ''Smile'' ''one of the most
beautifully ambitious rock records of the year, an exquisitely
melodic and literate concept album about wanderlust and the
distance people will go to run away from their problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The compliment, however, came under the headline, ''What If You
Made a Classic, and No One Cared?'' The story concentrated on why
it was unlikely many people would even hear the disc.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Louris, the band's chief songwriter, reacts to it all with
a polite fib.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't really worry too much about what people think, which
may be why we don't sell millions of records,'' he said. ''Maybe I
should calculate things a little more. We're so out of step with
the times that in certain ways, it's hopeless to even try.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe him, especially when you hear his evident
pride in the way devoted fans argue over which Jayhawks album is
the best, and the delight he feels when people respond to the new
music.
</P>
<P>
   In the old Jayhawks, Olson and Louris seemed inextricably bound.
They shared songwriting, and their tight harmonies were the
foundation of the band's pastoral music.
</P>
<P>
   The new Jayhawks are slightly tougher-sounding, led by the new
interplay of Louris' voice with those of drummer Tim O'Reagan and
keyboardist Karen Grotberg. The female voice has proven so crucial
that when Grotberg recently left to raise a family, the band looked
for another woman who could sing and found Jen Gunderman.
</P>
<P>
   Louris is careful not to say the Jayhawks are better now. Just
different.
</P>
<P>
   ''People in the band saw an opening and they went for it,'' he
said. ''Mark left, and they thought maybe it could be less of a
Mark and Gary thing. I think everybody stepped forward and filled
the void a bit, as opposed to just finding a Mark Olson sound-alike
guy and putting him up there saying, 'Hope nobody notices.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, some fans concentrate so much on the differences
between the two bands that they overlook the similarities.
</P>
<P>
   ''People kind of get taken aback by the frosting -- there's a
Neil Young solo on that album and this one has strings and samples,
so they've really changed,'' he said. ''But, really, the
songwriting's the same.''
</P>
<P>
   In making ''Smile,'' the Jayhawks were initially looking for a
bigger departure from their old sound. They contacted several
producers to gauge their interest, including the Minneapolis rhythm
'n' blues partners Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis, electronic wizard
Flood and even the eccentric genius, Phil Spector.
</P>
<P>
   They settled on Bob Ezrin, best known for his 1970s work with
Pink Floyd, Kiss, Alice Cooper and Lou Reed.
</P>
<P>
   All the prospective producers were sent a tape of about three
dozen songs. Ezrin wrote a detailed critique of each one, as well
as a general discussion about the band. Impressed with the
enthusiasm, the Jayhawks hired him.
</P>
<P>
   Louris had to get used to someone saying his songs weren't good
enough, to stop being lazy and get back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ''He energized us,'' Louris said. ''He focused us. He cracked
the whip on our songwriting. More than anything else, he was a real
confidence builder. The Jayhawks have a lot of ideas, and we can
definitely sing and play our instruments. What we get in trouble
with is decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks record ''became his life,'' he said. ''He was
laying carpet at my house, he was at my wedding. He becomes part of
your life. It's inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Laying carpet?
</P>
<P>
   You can't fault that enthusiasm. Ultimately, Louris believes
Ezrin has pushed the Jayhawks to a point where it has the freedom
to go in several different directions and not have it appear
unnatural.
</P>
<P>
   ''The next record we make could be a Folkways, Alan Lomax-style
country-blues record,'' he said. ''Or, we could go make a super pop
record and nobody would be surprised, which is kind of cool. I
think we just start trying to not repeat ourselves, which is
usually a sign of panic.''
</P>
<P>
   The future, where the Jayhawks are not chased around by a ghost
of themselves, is a nice place to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   First, one last piece of old business. Do the Jayhawks know
whether their old partner, Olson, who moved to California, has
heard the new music? Do they care?
</P>
<P>
   ''I sent him the record,'' Louris said. ''We've probably had
more contact this year than at any time since 1994 or 1995. He just
wrote back saying, 'Wow, this record is great.' He sent me his and
I think it's pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's good contact. It's not reuniting contact. I don't really
like when bands try to recapture something. Most of it is never
quite as good as what it was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1212 </TRAILER>
