<DOCNO> APW20000927.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sally Field Makes Directorial Debut  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- It took a lot of training and persistence for
Sally Field -- TV's Gidget and The Flying Nun -- to break into the
snootier world of feature films. She's taking the same methodical
pace now moving into directing.
</P>
<P>
   Field's directorial debut, the comedy ''Beautiful,'' which opens
Friday, comes after two smaller TV projects that the Oscar- and
Emmy-winning actress took on to see if she had the desire and knack
for directing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to do it sort of slowly, very gradually,'' Field said
during an interview at the recent Toronto International Film
Festival, where ''Beautiful'' played. ''I really started the way I
started to find out if I wanted to be doing it or if I could do it.
... I found that I very much want to and want to be able to get
better at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Beautiful'' stars Minnie Driver as an obsessive,
opportunistic, sometimes mean-spirited contestant on the
beauty-pageant circuit, a woman so committed to winning that she
goes to extremes to cover up a secret that would disqualify her
from competition.
</P>
<P>
   Field chose ''Beautiful'' for her behind-the-camera debut
because the script presented a rarity in Hollywood: a strong but
deeply flawed, at times unpleasant, female lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's boldly funny the way women don't get to be very often,
and very flawed and complicated, and walks a fine line between
being likable and not likable,'' Field said. ''I love seeing a
female character that doesn't come on the screen from the very
beginning and ask the audience to like them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really don't like having pleasant people thrown at me,
especially women. I like to see a woman be colors that are not
acceptable, not politically correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Field knows something about making the transition from pleasant,
politically correct roles to characters with substance and grit.
She began in television in the mid-1960s with the perky title role
in ''Gidget'' and later starred as the do-good, airborne Sister
Bertrille in ''The Flying Nun.''
</P>
<P>
   All the while, she was taking on serious training as an actor,
looking to break out of such campy TV parts into feature films. She
found a snobbery among Hollywood studios toward television actors
that was difficult to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''The motion-picture business was very against television people
coming in -- it gave a bad onus to the magic of movies,'' Field
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They weren't letting me in the room to audition. All I felt
was that when I got good enough, I would somehow change my own
fate, and that it was somehow resting in my own hands to do that. I
studied and studied and studied, and eventually there was a little
crack in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Field won a role opposite Jeff Bridges in ''Stay Hungry'' in
1976 (which was also Arnold Schwarzenegger's first movie). She made
a series of films with Burt Reynolds, including ''The End'' (1978)
and two ''Smokey and the Bandit'' flicks. She grabbed her first
Oscar for the union drama ''Norma Rae.''
</P>
<P>
   The title role in ''Sybil,'' about a woman with multiple
personalities, earned Field an Emmy, and she won her second Oscar
for the farmland drama ''Places in the Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Field played the mother of Tom Hanks' character
in ''Forrest Gump'' and the ex-wife of Robin Williams' character in
''Mrs. Doubtfire.'' She also had a brief, unbilled role as a
white-trash mother in ''Where the Heart Is.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up is another mother role, in ''Say It Isn't So,'' a
whacked-out comedy written by the Farrelly brothers and due out
next year. Field co-stars as the mother of a woman, played by
Heather Graham, who becomes involved with a man she thinks is her
brother.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a different kind of mother character,'' Field said.
''She's not Mama Gump, let's put it that way. She's pretty crazy. I
can't even tell you what the movie's about. It's the Farrelly
brothers, so it's completely out there. It's a kind of comedy I've
never done before. I was interested in doing something I'd never
done.''
</P>
<P>
   That was part of the appeal of directing, too. Like most
actresses, Field, 53, said she finds fewer interesting roles coming
her way as she ages.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a group of us still out there working here and
there,'' Field said. ''We are pushing the envelope as hard as it's
ever been pushed. But it's always been a fact: Even in the '30s,
women like Rosalind Russell were making 25 movies a year, but their
careers still ended when they started to get into their 40s.
Katharine Hepburn, thank God, would come back occasionally and do a
wonderful role, but her ongoing career changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're facing that today. I'm a baby-boomer female, and we're
changing things. Not fast enough, but the more women who begin
writing and directing, the more I believe the stories will be about
women in all the varied stages of their lives. ... I think
ultimately, instead of raising a fist and shaking it, the only
thing that changes anything is an individual, not necessarily me,
but the other people like me. The other women like me that have
stories to tell. If you don't see enough stories about you, get up
and tell your own.''
</P>
<P>
   Field's first directing effort was the TV movie ''The Christmas
Tree'' in 1996, which she co-wrote. Next was an episode of Hanks'
HBO series ''From the Earth to the Moon,'' an installment that
dealt with the wives of NASA astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   She said she plans to continue acting while looking for new
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly, right now, I'm more intrigued with directing,''
Field said. ''It's a more difficult task to me right now. But I
love acting. It's been my first love. I would wish directing would
take over and I would love it more, but I'm not as good a director
as I am an actor. I would like to be one day.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Official movie Web site:
http://www.beautifulthemovie.com/flash4page.html
</P>
