<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of Oct. 1-7:
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1941, ''The Maltese Falcon'' opened. The film starred
Humphrey Bogart and was directed by John Huston.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, the game show ''You Bet Your Life,'' with Groucho Marx
as host, premiered on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, ''Father Knows Best'' premiered on CBS. This classic
wholesome family sitcom starred Robert Young and Jane Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, ''Captain Kangaroo'' premiered on CBS. ''The Mickey
Mouse Club'' made its debut on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, ''The Twilight Zone,'' created and hosted by Rod
Serling, made its debut on CBS. Serling wrote many of the teleplays
that were presented on the program. The stories were unusual and
offbeat, often with ironic twists.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, Bob Dylan made his concert hall debut in New York City.
About 50 people attended, mostly his friends, and he earned $20.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, the Motion Picture Association of America adopted its
film-rating system, ranging from ''G'' for general audiences to
''X'' for adult patrons only.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, ''Soul Train'' went into national syndication. The
show, hosted by Don Cornelius, premiered a year earlier in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Mick Jagger apologized to the Rev. Jesse Jackson for
offensive lyrics in the Rolling Stones song, ''Some Girls.'' But he
refused to change the words.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, singer Carly Simon collapsed due to exhaustion onstage
in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, ''Beverly Hills, 90210'' premiered on the Fox network.
The series starred Shannon Doherty and Jason Priestley.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, an alleged shoplifter surrendered to actors Richard
Belzer and Clark Johnson after mistaking them for real cops. Belzer
and Johnson were filming an episode of the TV program ''Homicide:
Life on the Street.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
