<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibit Explores Tramp Photographer  </HEADLINE>
By SONJA BARISIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- Stage and screen stars like Lillian Gish
asked for James Abbe by name when they wanted their portraits
taken.
</P>
<P>
   Abbe also photographed the major European leaders of the 1920s
and '30s, from Stalin to Mussolini to Hitler, and pioneered the
photo essay before there was a Life magazine. Yet, the once-famous,
self-described ''tramp photographer'' is largely forgotten today.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks Johnson, curator of photography at The Chrysler Museum of
Art, is trying to change that with ''James Abbe: Photographer,''
the first American retrospective of Abbe's works.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit opened in June and runs through Nov. 5 at the museum
in Norfolk, about 15 miles from Newport News, where Abbe grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson first became intrigued by Abbe when he read about an
exhibit of Abbe's works at The National Portrait Gallery in London
in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''This looked like a really fascinating photographer, and I
didn't know anything about this guy,'' Johnson said. Johnson began
researching Abbe and by the time he saw the exhibit a year later
when it was in Wales, he had already determined to mount an exhibit
of his own in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Abbe's name may not have been forgotten if he had
covered World War II. It also didn't help that his private life was
problematic; he had four wives and pieces of his estate were left
with various parts of his families. In addition, many negatives and
prints were lost when Abbe could not pay shipping costs and
abandoned two trunks at the American Express office in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler exhibit contains 125 black-and-white, often
striking, photos. His subjects included such celebrities as Charlie
Chaplin, Mary Pickford, Douglas Fairbanks, Mae West and Rudolf
Valentino.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Maine, Abbe moved in 1892 to Newport News, where his
father, a traveling encyclopedia salesman, bought a bookstore. At
12, he persuaded his father to get a Kodak agency license to sell
cameras and develop film.
</P>
<P>
   Abbe made a name for himself as the ''boy photographer of
Newport News,'' using his $1 Kodak camera to photograph battleship
launchings in the shipyard town. He would get the film developed
quickly and sell postcards for 10 cents apiece to spectators as
they left the launch site.
</P>
<P>
   His postcard portrait of the battleship USS Maine, which he
photographed in Newport News, became a hot seller when the ship
blew up in Cuba during the Spanish-American War.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's that entrepreneur spirit that you see in the boy of 15
and younger that carries him throughout his whole career,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1911, Abbe moved to Lynchburg, where, as a yearbook
photographer at nearby girls' schools, he honed his skills,
learning how to pose and light his subjects to make them more
interesting and attractive, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Vanity Fair wanted to buy a photograph he took of ballet dancers
at Randolph-Macon College, but the college president asked him not
to publish the photo because it was revealing: The girls' knees
were visible.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somehow, my ballet girl setback, coupled with such
encouragement (from the magazine) ... influenced me to go all-out
and move to New York'' in 1917, Abbe wrote in an autobiography
excerpted in a book that accompanies the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   What made Abbe stand out in New York was that he was one of the
first people to photograph actors in costume on the stage, Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   That technique began with a challenge from actor John Barrymore
in 1919 to photograph him and his brother Lionel on stage rather
than in the studio, Johnson said. Abbe did so after dress
rehearsal, photographing the actors between 2 a.m. and 5 a.m., then
processing the film and enlarging the photos in time to displayed
in the theater lobby for the show's opening that night.
</P>
<P>
   Abbe also traveled between New York and Hollywood, selling
pictures of celebrities to fan magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ''He helped develop the idea of media-induced celebrity,''
Johnson said. ''Because of his photos, people got to know the
celebrities, or at least think they did.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lillian Gish went to Italy to film the movie ''The White
Sister'' in 1922, she requested that Abbe come along to take
photographs. In Italy, Abbe fell in love with the third of his four
wives and moved to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   He continued to photograph performers but also traveled the
world as a photojournalist, calling himself a ''tramp
photographer.''
</P>
<P>
   His work appeared in major publications such as London Magazine,
the Berliner Illustrire Zeitung of Germany and the French magazine
VU -- prototypes of Life.
</P>
<P>
   He covered the Spanish Civil War and chronicled the Nazis' rise
to power in Germany during the 1930s, from the burning of censored
books to portraits of Hitler. He also documented events in
post-revolutionary Russia and became the only photographer at some
battles of the civil war in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932, he persuaded Joseph Stalin to let him take a portrait
to quell rumors that the Soviet leader had been ill and died. The
photograph was reprinted around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly alarmed by Nazi tactics, he returned to the United
States in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   When World War II broke out, Abbe tried to get an assignment in
Europe, but at 58, he was told he was too old, Johnson said.
Instead, he began a career in radio broadcasting in the western
United States, eventually having his own commentary program in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He died in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.chrysler.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1213 </TRAILER>
