<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Poetry of Willis Barnstone  </HEADLINE>
By MORT ROSENBLUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- If Willis Barnstone does not exactly outsell J.K.
Rowling, he has written 12 times more books. And his wizard is no
fictional character but rather the author himself.
</P>
<P>
   Reading Barnstone's flights of poetic fancy is like playing
quidditch without a broom. If you look past snowy hair to his eyes,
he seems slightly younger at 72 than Harry Potter is at 14.
</P>
<P>
   ''No, is he good?'' Barnstone replies when asked if he has read
Harry Potter books. With a diffident chuckle, he adds, ''I've been
a little busy lately.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he is doing a fresh translation of the Bible from
Ancient Greek. It took 24 scholars to produce the King James
version, and he is doing his alone, although he is leaving out the
Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped in France for his first visit since 1956 and dashed
off lines in perfect French, a pleasant parody of Apollinaire. He
visited the grave of Antonio Machado, whose Spanish works he
brought to English.
</P>
<P>
   Barnstone also translates from Chinese, German and Italian. He
used to read Bengali. With his prolific son and daughter, he has
edited literature anthologies from every continent but Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing obsesses him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe we could talk about poetry,'' Barnstone says, hesitantly
and apologetically, when the subject lingers too long on magical
kids and musty old religious texts. ''I'm really quite a good poet,
you know.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, of course. While doing his day job as professor of
comparative literature at Indiana University in Bloomington, he
stayed up most nights until nearly dawn composing highly lauded
verse.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as professor emeritus with a part-time home in Oakland,
Calif., he is still at it.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Luis Borges, the great Argentine whom he also translated,
wrote: ''Four of the best things in America are Walt Whitman's
leaves, Herman Melville's whales, the sonnets of Barnstone and my
daily corn flakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Stone notes Barnstone's ''passionate wisdom and wit, scope
and cunning.'' She once praised ''this gorgeous energy of a poet of
genius ... (who) floats us to resonant surprise.'' She added: ''I
don't believe he sleeps.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Barnstone says, poetry may not be at its highest
literary level, but there is plenty of it -- more and more each year
-- and that is vital to keeping a fast-changing world on a
reasonable course.
</P>
<P>
   ''Poetry is another reality, a way to make sense of things,'' he
says. ''I see it everywhere. I drum meters on my fingers while
walking down the street. I tap it out on women's backs in bed at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   As an observer of a new Old World, Barnstone is rich in context.
</P>
<P>
   He saw baseball up close as a kid. Babe Ruth was his neighbor.
His father, an itinerant jewelry salesman, took him to Mexico as a
teen-ager. At 20, he moved to Paris and then on to Greece during a
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sunday Morning in Fascist Spain'' is a set of early memoirs,
missing such later moments as traveling the Chinese Silk Road and
teaching in Argentina as the ''dirty war'' raged in the background.
</P>
<P>
   In ''Funny Ways of Staying Alive,'' he messes with simple
whimsy: ''Smoke/And croak.'' Or: ''Doubt/And you're
out./Persist/And you exist.'' Or: ''If your shoes are tight,/You're
not so bright.''
</P>
<P>
   But his ''The Other Bible'' is an exhaustive study of gospels
edited out of the New Testament. He has also translated forgotten
scriptures of the Gnostics, early Christians who saw their own
revelations.
</P>
<P>
   His new Bible will stick close to the original texts, written in
the old Greek of the Holy Land, with Semitic names. Jesus is Jeshua
the Messiah. His parents are Yosef and Myryam.
</P>
<P>
   Barnstone -- whose family's name began as Bornstein -- was
raised a Jew, but the scholar in him prevents his tinkering with
what he regards as slanderous text in the four gospels.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I were a Christian, and I grew up reading the New
Testament, I'd want to kill every Jew in the world,'' he says. Then
he laughed at the notion of his slight frame and poetic soul
menacing even a mosquito.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 20 of Barnstone's 50 or so books are still in print.
Some sell well over 100,000 copies. But he is no household word.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as I have my family,'' he says of daughter Aliki and
sons Tony and Robert, ''I don't need any more audience.''
</P>
<P>
   His childhood was hard, but he remembers his father as in a poem
he calls ''Love Tent,'' imagining his own death:
</P>
<P>
   ''The sun on that black Monday will/forget to rise, I'll be
holed up in bed/yet scrawl a letter back to him. Dad went/except in
me. He takes my hand. I fill/his palm of dust with sun. And we're
not dead/because we love and chat in his blue tent.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from scholarly work, Barnstone burrows toward the essence
of reality with a poet's disdain for stingy facts.
</P>
<P>
   Once, in Chile, he messaged a magazine to which he often
contributed that he was only a short hop from Christmas Island. He
knew the subject well, he noted, and wanted to go write about it.
</P>
<P>
   The editors' reply came back: ''We assume you mean Easter
Island. Go ahead.'' To a wizard, what's the difference?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1213 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks' Decline Blamed on Profits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed Wednesday as investors
concerned about third-quarter profits again sold off shares of poor
performers.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain hunting helped push technology issues somewhat higher,
but it wasn't clear how long-lived the gains would be. The market
has spent much of this month in a decline, reflecting uncertainty
about how the moderating economy will affect third-quarter results.
</P>
<P>
   After advancing briefly when the market opened, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 16.37 at 10,614.95 in midday trading.
It fell 176 points on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators appeared to be having a mild recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 2.61 at 1,429.82. The
tech-focused Nasdaq composite index was up 19.03 at 3,708.13, after
moving in and out of negative territory all morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're seeing a little bit of a rebound from yesterday, as far
as the Nasdaq is concerned, and some pressure on blue chips,'' said
Dick Dickson, a technical analyst at Scott &AMP; Stringfellow Inc.
''It's just a continuation of what we've had over the last three
weeks. The market gets sold off, stocks get a little bit of a
bounce up and then we sell off again.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing particularly exciting going on today. It's
really just a little bit here and a little bit there.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the market has been fixated on the approach of
third-quarter reports. Increasing indications that the economy is
slowing, combined with high energy prices and Europe's weak
currency, have many investors looking to the third-quarter as a
sign of what is to come for many companies.
</P>
<P>
   Investors Wednesday again punished and rewarded companies
depending on their earnings outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline fell $8.14 to $10.50 -- a 43 percent drop -- after the
discount travel Web site said its bottom line would be hurt by weak
airline ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   A stronger-than-expected earnings report helped push 3Com up
$3.06 to $17 on the Nasdaq. The computer networking company posted
a first quarter loss of $59.2 million Tuesday but fared better than
Wall Street had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   There was also limited bargain hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose $2.06 to $45.38, as the chipmaker struggled to
rebound from a slump that began Friday when it warned of
disappointing profits. Micron Technology $3.81 to $51.50, a 7
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems rose $2.50 to $120.
</P>
<P>
   But financial and consumer product stocks had a tougher time as
investors sought profits and moved money out of blue chips into
technology issues or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup fell $1.13 to $52.38. Procter &AMP; Gamble tumbled $1.19
to $60.56.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies also suffered. Web portal Yahoo! fell $7.75
to $94.69, while e-tailer Amazon was down $1.50 to $38.25.
</P>
<P>
   And Corning tumbled $3.50 to $319.50 after it announced it was
buying part of the fiber optic operations of Pirelli, an Italian
company.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 523.26 million
shares, well ahead of the 482.63 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 2.20 at 512.09.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
