<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic May Use Army To Hold Power  </HEADLINE>
By DUSAN STOJANOVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- His rule badly shaken by an apparent
electoral defeat, Slobodan Milosevic may turn to his faithful army
commanders to help him hold onto power.
</P>
<P>
   But the tactic could backfire. Despite the loyalty of the top
brass, lower army ranks are not universally among the hard-line
Yugoslav president's allies.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the rank and file -- especially conscripts doing their
one-year compulsory military service -- support Vojislav Kostunica,
who claimed victory in Sunday's election.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Milosevic has decided to overturn the electoral will of the
people, he may try to do it by force,'' said Gen. Momcilo Perisic,
a former army chief of staff and now a Milosevic opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ''But he won't succeed,'' said Perisic, who was purged by
Milosevic from the military in 1998. ''There are many army officers
who applauded the opposition victory in the elections. I know what
I'm talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is difficult to verify Perisic's claim, sources
within the 60,000-member army confirm widespread soul-searching in
the ranks about how to respond to any order to use force against
the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's longtime communist leader, Josip Broz Tito,
promoted the image of the armed forces as an institution to defend
the nation and avoid internal political bickering.
</P>
<P>
   Although much of the old spirit has waned, commanders are
trained to see the military as an institution designed to confront
foreign -- not domestic -- enemies and to defend the constitutional
order.
</P>
<P>
   If the opposition convinces most Yugoslavs that it was robbed of
victory, the dilemma facing many in the ranks will be: Who is the
usurper? Milosevic or the opposition?
</P>
<P>
   Predrag Bulatovic, a Milosevic ally from Montenegro, which along
with Serbia forms Yugoslavia, rejected claims the army would step
in to safeguard Milosevic's stay in power.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think anyone in this country is going to defend power
with the use of force, nor do I believe the army will step in,''
Bulatovic said. ''The army has always adhered to the constitution
and I urge it to do so now as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, however, has used the army in the past when he was in
trouble. In March 1991, he called out tanks to disperse massive
opposition demonstrations against him in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The army -- which shares Milosevic's communist ideology -- was
also instrumental in his military campaigns in Slovenia, Croatia,
Bosnia and Kosovo. The army -- not trained to fight civil wars --
ended up as a loser against ragtag forces from the former Yugoslav
states.
</P>
<P>
   Amid growing fears that Milosevic may impose martial law to stay
in power, Serbian Orthodox Church Patriarch Pavle called on
''everyone, including the army and police, to defend the interests
of the people and the state rather than the individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, army commanders always felt they were playing
second fiddle to the powerful state police. Fiercely loyal to
Milosevic, the state police always had better salaries and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The ranks of the police -- which has repeatedly used brutal force
against anti-Milosevic demonstrators -- consists of less-educated
townspeople. The military ranks, especially the officer corps, come
mostly from villages and are considered less threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the disgruntled military might stage a coup against him,
Milosevic purged the top army echelons during last year's NATO
bombing of Yugoslavia, promoting his loyalists to command
positions.
</P>
<P>
   The generals, such as Defense Minister Dragoljub Ojdanic -- who,
like Milosevic, was charged with war crimes by the international
tribunal at the Hague -- have given unprecedented political support
to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   They have taken an active role in Milosevic's pre-election
campaign, claiming the army would never allow ''NATO lackeys and
Western stooges'' -- the phrases used by Milosevic to depict
Kostunica and other opponents -- to come to power in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But loyalty of the army's rank and file has remained suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ''The army will think hard before they decide to protect the man
who actually lost the elections,'' said opposition leader Zarko
Korac.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
