<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic's Opponents Rally  </HEADLINE>
By JOVANA GEC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Tens of thousands of banner-waving
opponents of Slobodan Milosevic poured into Belgrade's main square
Wednesday to protest his alleged moves to steal Yugoslavia's
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic stopped around Republic Square as the crowd streamed in
from all directions, carrying banners saying ''He is finished'' -- a
reference to Milosevic's apparent loss in Sunday's elections, in
which challenger Vojislav Kostunica claimed victory.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the rally began, Yugoslavia's foreign minister
tried to discourage protests, appearing on state television and
alleging strong pressure by foreign countries against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Zivadin Jovanovic said the pressure was being applied through
foreign media and independent news organizations at home, which he
said were trying to present a distorted picture of the country in
service of Western enemies.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared, however, that many people in Belgrade were unmoved
by that. Crowds covered the square after opposition leaders urged
them to take to the streets, despite an earlier police ban on the
original site for the rally.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition handed out 10,000 baby rattles for their
supporters to shake in the face of the Yugoslav leader and show
that despite his alleged efforts to rig the vote, he was a broken
figure -- playing on a Serbian language expression to describe
something defective as ''broken like a baby's rattle.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I can feel a lot of happiness in the air,'' psychologist Zarko
Trebjesanin said of Belgrade, the capital. ''The genie of freedom
and democracy has escaped from the bottle and it's impossible to
push it back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders, trying not to do anything that might give
Milosevic a pretext for a crackdown, did not contest a police order
to move the rally from the initial venue -- a platform in front of
Yugoslavia's federal assembly -- after authorities said it would
disturb work of the State Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our aim is to avoid clashes, but there are hard-liners in the
state leadership who want something to happen,'' said Zoran
Djindjic, a key Milosevic opponent. He said the opposition received
assurances from police that they would not intervene during the
rally. There was no visible police presence as the rally began.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, using figures from its poll watchers, claimed
Kostunica won 52.54 percent to Milosevic's 32.01 percent -- enough
for a first-round victory in the five-candidate field. But the
State Electoral Commission, which is loyal to Milosevic, says
Kostunica finished first with 48.22 percent while Milosevic polled
40.23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That would necessitate a runoff, since neither received more
than 50 percent. The opposition quickly rejected the idea, but the
government set the runoff for Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ''Elections are not car races, in which a contestant can catch
up in the second round,'' opposition spokesman Cedomir Jovanovic
said. ''Our victory is not negotiable.''
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders backed the opposition's claim. In Washington,
President Clinton dismissed Yugoslav government plans for a runoff
as an apparent attempt to steal a fair election.
</P>
<P>
   ''It certainly appears from a distance that they had a free
election and somebody's trying to take it away from them,'' Clinton
said Wednesday at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government's official election commission has no
credibility whatever,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade's ally Russia, however, warned Western countries not to
interfere. Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Moscow
''stands firmly for the peoples of Yugoslavia to have full freedom
to express their will without internal or external pressure'' and
urged other countries ''not to allow destabilization of the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   An opposition delegation attempted to inspect the election
commission's returns on Wednesday, claiming they are short some
400,000 pro-Kostunica votes. The guards, however, allowed only one
member of the opposition team to enter briefly.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is great fear among the commission,'' delegate Nebojsa
Bakarac said after coming out.
</P>
<P>
   Bakarac said he could not single-handedly inspect more than 5
million ballots and appealed to commission members to ''publish the
real results and act according to their conscience, without
creating tensions.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the cafes of this riverside Balkan capital buzzed
with theories on what Milosevic would do next. Many people went
about their business, quietly expressing optimism over the
political changes taking place.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all know he is done with,'' said Vladislava Vukovic, 48, a
lawyer. ''He cannot harm us any more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1529 </TRAILER>
