<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backdrop Rockwell House for Sale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. (AP) -- In 1952, the home inspired a Norman Rockwell
painting. Today, it's in foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   A brick townhouse that was the backdrop for a painting depicting
America's optimism and vibrancy was recently turned over to the
federal Department of Housing and Urban Development, which will
offer it for sale for six months. If no one buys the house, valued
at $66,876, the city of Troy can acquire it for $1.
</P>
<P>
   The painting ''The Street Was Never the Same'' shows
rambunctious children chasing Henry Ford in his first automobile
and adults gawking from the stoop and open windows. The scene was
painted for a calendar marking the automobile's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Pero, curator of the Norman Rockwell collection at the
Norman Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge, Mass., said Rockwell chose
Troy for several paintings because it was the nearest big city to
his home, first in Arlington, Vt., then in nearby West Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The building was last owned by a local businessman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
