<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Lower in P.M. Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices slumped Wednesday as investors
concerned about third-quarter results again punished the shares of
poor performers.
</P>
<P>
   A round of bargain hunting early in the day helped push some
issues higher, but the rebound did not hold. The lack of staying
power was not a surprise: the market has spent much of this month
in a decline, reflecting uncertainty about how the moderating
economy will affect corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average tumbled 34.78 to 10,596.54 in
late afternoon trading. It fell 176 points on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators struggled to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index dropped 43.92 to 3,645.18, after
spiking into positive territory earlier in the day. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 5.15 to 1,422.06.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a continuation of what we've had over the last three
weeks. The market gets sold off, stocks get a little bit of a
bounce up and then we sell off again,'' said Dick Dickson, a
technical analyst at Scott &AMP; Stringfellow Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing particularly exciting going on today. It's
really just a little bit here and a little bit there.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the market has been fixated on the approach of
third-quarter reports. Increasing indications that the economy is
slowing, combined with oil prices at decade-high levels and
Europe's weak currency, have many investors looking to the
third-quarter as a sign of what is to come for many companies.
</P>
<P>
   Investors Wednesday again punished or rewarded companies
depending on their earnings outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline fell $8.14 to $10.50 -- a 43 percent drop -- after the
discount travel Web site said its bottom line would be hurt by weak
airline ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   A stronger-than-expected earnings report helped push 3Com up $3
to $16.94 on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Energy stocks were up, as well, on persistent concerns about
fuel costs as winter approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil rose $2.25 to $88.88; Enron jumped $1.44 to $86.94.
</P>
<P>
   There was also limited bargain hunting, but most stocks weren't
able to hang on to their gains.
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose 68 cents to $44, as the chipmaker struggled to
rebound from a slump that began Friday when it warned of
disappointing profits. Micron Technology rose 88 cents to $50.56,
after failing to sustain a nearly $4 increase.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems rose $2.75 to $117.63. Hewlett Packard climbed
$3.44 to $102.44.
</P>
<P>
   But investors didn't blindly snap up technology-related stocks.
Web portal superstar Yahoo! fell $12.44 to $90, while e-tailer
Amazon was down $3.06 to $36.69. Both companies have faced
questions in recent weeks about profitability and whether their
business models will work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology is seeing some real concerted selling across the
board on profit-taking. It's fear of a slowdown,'' said Scott
Bleier, chief investment strategist at Prime Charter. He believes
Internet stocks and some of telecom and semiconductor issues are
especially vulnerable because they traded at such high premiums
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those sectors that are the most expensive will have the
biggest downside, and that includes technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial and old-economy stocks also had a tougher time as
profit-seeking investors moved money out of blue chips.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup fell $1 to $52.50. Caterpillar slipped $2.25 to $32.75
</P>
<P>
   And Corning tumbled $16 to $307 after it announced it was buying
part of the fiber optic operations of Pirelli, an Italian company.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 925.16 million
shares, well ahead of the 868.24 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.92 at 508.92.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
