<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading pediatrician Frank Disney dies at 88  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Dr. Frank Albert Disney, a pediatrician
for 59 years credited with popularizing office-based clinical
research, is dead at age 88.
</P>
<P>
   Disney died after a lengthy illness Sept. 18 at his home in the
Rochester suburb of Pittsford.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Disney and Dr. Burtis Breese started the longtime
practice in pediatrics of combining clinical practice with
office-based studies of strep throat and related childhood
diseases. He retired in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   A native of New York City, Disney grew up in Darien, Conn. He
earned his medical degree from the College of Physicians and
Surgeons at Columbia University. After interning at Babies Hospital
in New York, he moved here in 1939 to become a resident at Strong
Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of World War II, Disney directed the Rochester
Blood Bank, then one of less than a half-dozen blood collection
centers in the nation. He served with the Army in the Pacific
theater, on Guam and later in the Philippines, from 1943 to 1946.
</P>
<P>
   He never met his famous third cousin, animator Walt Disney,
because ''he was too busy seeing sick children,'' Noreen Ireland, a
clinical research colleague, said in Wednesday's Rochester Democrat
and Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife of 33 years, Rosemary Disney; a
daughter, Linda Bennett of Glenfield, N.Y.; two sons, Dr. George
Disney of Johnstown, N.Y., and Robert Disney of Aspen, Colo.; two
stepsons, David Johnston of California and Todd Johnston of
Georgia, and a stepdaughter, Susan Johnston of Rochester; and a
sister, Ruth Currie of Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-27-00 1538 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
