<DOCNO> APW20000927.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unions among those in new coalition to boost school resources  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state's strongest teachers' unions are
part of a new coalition dedicated to increasing resources so
schools in New York can help students reach new academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Quality Education said Wednesday that while the
state is demanding more from schools and students, those schools
and students have the right to demand more from the state. Namely,
said Sarah Hafensteiner of the group's steering committee, schools
need ''the necessary resources and tools to enable all children -
rich and poor, upstate and downstate, the rural and urban - to meet
the higher standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Hafensteiner, a school board member in the
Ravena-Coeymans-Selkirk district south of Albany, said the state
Board of Regents' new standards have left schools throughout the
state at a ''crossroads.'' More resources are needed in most
districts, or their students run the risk of failing to meet the
Regent's demands, she contended.
</P>
<P>
   Increases in state aid to education have been at record-high
levels in the past three years, but poorer urban and rural
districts still face a number of serious deficiencies, several
members of the group said at a news conference in Albany and in six
other cities Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The largest teacher unions in the state - New York State United
Teachers, the National Education Association-New York and the
United Federation of Teachers - are part of the 100-plus member
coalition. Other groups involved ranged from statewide consumer
groups like Citizen Action to neighborhood civic groups from
Buffalo, Harlem and Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Civil Liberties Union and the Fiscal Policy
Institute, a think-tank funded partly from union contributions, are
also in the group.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition members agreed on a four-point agenda they said they
would lobby for in the coming months with Gov. George Pataki and
the state Legislature: Reducing class sizes; improving the quality
and training of teachers; improving the quality of classrooms and
other school facilities; and making early childhood education
programs available to all youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   The group had no estimate how much it would cost to address all
four issues over the next five or 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not have a specific dollar amount at this time,''
Hafensteiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Per-pupil spending on public education in New York is typically
among the top two or three among all the states.
</P>
<P>
   But Frank Mauro, chief researcher with the Fiscal Policy
Institute, said that statistic is skewed by the high spending in
affluent, chiefly suburban, districts in New York. Schools in rural
and inner-city districts typically spend far below the state
per-pupil average, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have the right amount of per pupil spending in all
the districts where all the needs are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state is providing more than $13 billion in the 2000-01
fiscal year to public schools, a record. The year-to-year education
aid increases from the state the past three years, in fact, have
set records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-27-00 1543 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
