<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Seeks Limelight on Unity Day  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Scandal-tarnished Helmut Kohl stepped back into
the limelight Wednesday to recall his greatest accomplishment -- a
reunited Germany -- and appeared to blink back tears at an event
staged after he wasn't offered a chance to speak at the national
Unity Day celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Hailed as the ''Unity Chancellor,'' Kohl received polite
applause and a brief standing ovation from a crowd of supporters at
the event organized by a foundation allied with his Christian
Democratic party.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has said he will stay home for the national celebration in
Dresden on Tuesday, 10 years after the country became one again on
Oct. 3, 1990. Although he was invited as a guest, the ex-chancellor
wasn't offered the chance to take the podium.
</P>
<P>
   In one of two events planned this week to give him a chance to
take credit and recall his party's better days, Kohl criticized
leaders of the then-opposition Social Democratic and Greens parties
-- now running the country -- by saying East and West Germany would
never have reunited without the visionary policies of his Christian
Democratic Union.
</P>
<P>
   ''In contrast to many Social Democrats and most Greens, the
Union has since its founding considered itself the party of German
unity,'' Kohl said. ''And it has remained that way up to today.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohl singled out comments by Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, made before the collapse of the
Berlin Wall in 1989, in which they talked pessimistically about the
chances it would ever come down.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's event was held in a run-down hall that once served
as a border checkpoint on the communist side of the Wall and now is
a cultural center.
</P>
<P>
   The location prompted a quip from Kohl, 70, who said during his
nearly hourlong speech that he had once been refused entry into
East Germany at the building.
</P>
<P>
   ''You see how I enjoy the fact that today there is no unwelcome
person in this hall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl didn't have to leave the hall to find critics.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Merkel, now the leader of the Christian Democrats, said
the scandal that Kohl touched off by admitting he accepted
anonymous donations had led to ''difficult months for us all.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has grown to include revelations of off-the-books
campaign funds, money laundering, and an investigation by
parliament into whether decisions were bought during Kohl's 16
years in power. Prosecutors are considering criminal charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1548 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jurors Hear Suit Against Eastwood  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL, Calif. (AP) -- The jurors hearing a disabled woman's
federal lawsuit against Clint Eastwood got a tour of the actor's
ranch Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A woman with muscular dystrophy is seeking unspecified damages
from Eastwood because parts of his historic Mission Ranch hotel
were inaccessible to her wheelchair when she had dinner there in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors were driven 75 miles from their San Jose courtroom to
see for themselves whether Eastwood could have done more to
accommodate wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood was present but did not lead the tour and was not
allowed to talk to jurors. The plaintiff, Diane zum Brunnen, 51,
did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood bought Mission Ranch, which has buildings dating to the
1850s, in 1987 for $4.2 million and has spent more than $6 million
on renovations. He testified last week that he has tried to provide
wheelchair access while maintaining the historic feel of the
property.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments were expected Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1551 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll shows Hillary Clinton hitting 50 percent for first time  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Clearing a psychological as well as a
statistical hurdle, Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton on
Wednesday hit the 50 percent support mark for the first time this
year in a major statewide independent poll.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Carroll, head of the Quinnipiac University Polling
Institute, termed it ''the magic 50 percent mark.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The days of wine and roses are here for Hillary, if they
stick,'' Carroll said. ''With 50 percent, you can't lose. You can
tie, but you can't lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican opponent Rick Lazio, professing a lack of concern as
he campaigned in upstate New York, did call himself ''the underdog
in this race'' - a term he hasn't used in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinnipiac poll showed the first lady leading the
congressman from Long Island, 50 percent to 43 percent, among
likely voters. A Sept. 12 poll from the Hamden, Conn.-based
institute had Clinton leading, 49 percent to 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign was crowing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know this race is going to be close, but it's nice to hit
the big five-oh,'' Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What a difference a point makes,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Lazio campaign has made much of Clinton's
failure to hit 50 percent in the polls. On Wednesday, his campaign
downplayed the new poll with spokesman Dan McLagan noting that
statistically ''there's no change from the last Quinnipiac poll.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's numbers have been edging up in recent weeks after
being stalled for most of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some polls detected a bounce for her in the wake of their first
debate, a Sept. 13 faceoff in Buffalo notable for Lazio's striding
across the stage and demanding she sign a pledge to ban soft money
from the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters, especially women, were offended by what Wolfson
called a ''menacing'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was for her already before the debate and it made me feel
for her even more,'' said Fran Goodstein of Yonkers as she shopped
Wednesday at the Galleria Mall in White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Not all women at the mall agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He thought he had to do what he did and you can't tell me it
was so terrible,'' said Serena Maglio of suburban Greenburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 46 percent of voters surveyed by Quinnipiac who
watched the debate, Clinton had the edge, 44 percent to 34 percent.
While earlier polls had found her struggling among white women, the
new one had her up slightly, 49 percent to 45 percent, in that
group.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's push for the soft-money ban did pay off when Clinton
agreed on Saturday to stop using such funds for advertising in her
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But some voters were unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what soft money is and neither does anybody else,
so to me they're both wasting a lot of time,'' undecided voter
Dolores Ray of Lewisboro said Wednesday. ''Talk to me about taxes,
(if) you want me to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   While other recent polls have shown Clinton edging close to the
50 percent mark, two out last week disagreed on the closeness of
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion had the two tied
at 48 percent each while a New York Times/CBS News poll had Clinton
leading Lazio, 48 percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a disheartening note for Lazio, the Quinnipiac poll found the
race extremely close - he at 46 percent, she at 44 percent - in
traditionally more conservative upstate New York. She has been
campaigning widely in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''The upstate stuff shouldn't be that close'' if Lazio is to
win, Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban-based congressman did lead, 53 percent to 40
percent, in the suburbs surrounding New York City, but she was
ahead in the heavily Democratic city, 67 percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   She led, 60 percent to 35 percent, among Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   While 38 percent of voters said they viewed the first lady
unfavorably - no real change from past polls - his unfavorable
rating reached 29 percent in the wake of the debate and heavy
anti-Lazio TV advertising from the Clinton campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And while Lazio has been making much of the ''trust''' issue,
his work in Congress and her lack of electoral experience, 67
percent of voters said a candidate's position on issues was more
important than ''experience and personal qualities'' or
''character.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-nine percent of voters said Clinton shared their views on
key issue while 51 percent said that about Lazio. He had the edge,
72 percent to 57 percent, on understanding the issues and problems
facing New York. She only moved into the state in January.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac's telephone poll of 889 likely voters was conducted
Sept. 20-25 and has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-27-00 1557 </TRAILER>
