<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Offspring Abandons Internet Release  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The rock group The Offspring has abandoned
plans to release an entire album for free on the Internet before it
goes on sale in stores.
</P>
<P>
   The band will instead release only one song online but will
proceed with a $1 million Web-based contest designed to promote the
album, Sony Music Entertainment, the band's distributor, said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are extremely happy that Sony Music has worked out a
solution with The Offspring and its management that supports the
integrity of the band's creative idea and enables them to proceed
with their promotion,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   A call to the band's publicist was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement with Sony, the band will post the single
''Original Prankster'' from the new album on its Web site on
Friday. The album, ''Conspiracy of One,'' will go on sale in stores
Nov. 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
