<DOCNO> APW20000927.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Oneida Land Claim, 1st Ld-Writethru,0560  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki on Wednesday joined other
politicians to ask the federal government to withdraw from Native
American land claims in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki called on the Clinton Administration to end the U.S.
Justice Department's involvement in all land claim lawsuits against
land owners in New York, noting that a judge had scolded the
federal government for acting in ''bad faith'' in the Oneida Indian
Nation land claim.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Clinton Administration should not wait for another federal
judge to say their actions amount to bad faith before dropping
these outrageous claims that threaten the private property rights
of thousands of innocent New York State citizens,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, U.S. District Judge Neal McCurn rejected the Oneida's
motion to add 20,000 individual property owners as parties to their
claim seeking compensation for 250,000 acres of lost ancestral
lands in Madison and Oneida counties. The Oneidas have said they
sought to add landowners to their claim as a negotiating strategy
and would not actually seek any evictions.
</P>
<P>
   McCurn, however, allowed the Oneidas to add the state of New
York as defendants in their 26-year-old lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said adding landowners to the lawsuit ''would only
unnecessarily further prolong this litigation and increase
community tensions in the claim area.'' He said he could not
''countenance'' needlessly keeping 20,000 innocent landowners in a
state of legal limbo.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas could appeal McCurn's decision, but representatives
for the three bands of the Oneidas said they have reached no
decisions. Mark Emery, spokesman for the Oneida Indian Nation of
New York, said lawyers were still studying McCurn's 66-page
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The justice department, required by federal law to represent the
interests of Native Americans, has supported the Oneidas in their
claim.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer, a Democrat, and
Republican Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, the local congressman, wrote
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno asking the justice department not
to appeal McCurn's ruling. They also asked the justice department
to drop all claims against property owners in Indian land claim
cases, including the Seneca Nation case in Grand Island, in western
New York, and the Mohawk Nation, in northern New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now that Judge McCurn has released the landowners from this
suit, it is high time for the department to begin serving as a
mediator in these cases, and stop acting as a litigant threatening
innocent landowners,'' Schumer wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, landowners took it upon themselves to write a
letter to Congress asking for a law that would permanently protect
property owners from eviction in Indian land claim cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want (Congress) to pass a bill which will remove eviction
and, more importantly, clear our titles so we can have transferable
titles,'' said John Ben Carroll, the lawyer for the group,
Madison-Oneida Landowners.
</P>
<P>
   Some players in the case are hopeful the decision will reopen
the door to a negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would hope it would make a difference and that (the Oneidas)
would come back to the bargaining table,'' said Madison County
Board of Supervisors Chairman Rocco DiVeronica.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-27-00 1613 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Accused of Obstruction  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House subcommittee chairman accused a Labor
Department official Wednesday of ''serious obstruction'' by
lobbying against proposed legislation to revamp veterans employment
and training programs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Terry Everett, R-Ala., chairman of the House Veterans
Affairs Investigative Subcommittee, told Assistant Labor Secretary
Espiridion ''Al'' Borrego at a hearing that he asked the
department's inspector general to investigate whether the official
violated the law.
</P>
<P>
   A statute prohibits use of federal funds for lobbying campaigns
intended to influence a member of Congress' position on
legislation. Borrego has opposed the bill -- now expected to die in
committee -- that would have imposed performance standards for
veterans job counselors whose pay is funded by the Labor
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Everett said he was concerned about allegations that Borrego
attempted to persuade Miss America, Heather French, to change House
testimony she was giving in favor of the bill; threatened to
withhold grant money from a homeless veterans organization unless
the group backed his view on the bill; and used federal funds to
lobby against the legislation in Everett's district.
</P>
<P>
   Everett said it appeared that Borrego was ''orchestrating active
opposition'' to the legislation despite the anti-lobbying law.
''This is serious obstruction to Congress doing its business. Who's
going to run the country, duly elected members of Congress or
overzealous bureaucrats?''
</P>
<P>
   Borrego, who is in charge of veterans employment and training
programs in the Labor Department, responded that the agency's chief
lawyer concluded earlier this month that no rules or laws were
broken by Borrego in his conversation with French. Borrego said he
made ''no attempt to have Ms. French advance any position in her
testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not address other allegations, but previously has denied
through a department spokesman that he threatened to withhold grant
money.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general acts independently of the labor secretary,
unlike the department solicitor who conducted the initial review;
that official who works directly for the secretary.
</P>
<P>
   French, who has made homeless veterans her cause, had told The
Associated Press in July that on the eve of her testimony in favor
of the legislation, Borrego tried in a telephone call to persuade
her to change her position. The AP reported last week that the
director of the National Coalition for Homeless Veterans, Linda
Boone, has told Labor Department investigators that Borrego had
threatened to withhold grant money.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 13, the department rejected a request from Boone's
coalition for a $121,277 grant to assist community groups serving
homeless veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph McGowan, a spokesman for the inspector general, said the
office is evaluating Everett's request.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Labor Department site on veterans employment:
http://www.dol.gov/dol/vets/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1614 </TRAILER>
