<DOCNO> APW20000927.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors: Lee Plea Best Choice  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Letting scientist Wen Ho Lee leave jail on a
plea bargain was the best way to recover missing nuclear secrets,
prosecutors insisted Wednesday, but that failed to persuade
senators to drop their criticism of the government's handling of
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''This case was not handled appropriately or he would not have
pleaded to only one of 59 counts,'' Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.,
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But officials from the Justice Department, the FBI and the
Energy Department insisted at a Senate Judiciary subcommittee
hearing that their only choice was a plea bargain to get Lee to
tell them what he did with the tapes. Lee has sworn he has
destroyed them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The answers were more important than prosecuting Dr. Lee for
his very serious crimes,'' said James Robinson, assistant attorney
general overseeing the criminal division.
</P>
<P>
   Lee pleaded guilty to one of the 59 counts of his grand jury
indictment. In exchange, he was released after being held for nine
months. He also agreed to tell officials what happened to the
information he downloaded at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Director Louis Freeh and Attorney General Janet Reno told
the Senate Select Intelligence and Judiciary committees Tuesday
that they had decided that they couldn't reveal nuclear secrets in
court to prosecute Lee. The presiding judge had indicated he would
force the government to do so, said U.S. Attorney Norman Bay of
Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ''Had that happened, our indictment would have been gutted,''
Bay said, because prosecutors would not have any evidence, other
than the secrets they were unwilling to use. ''At the end of the
day, we would have had nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers took advantage by threatening prosecutors with a
trial, promising a ''long slow death march'' toward publicity on
the nuclear secrets, Bay said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If someone had told me they were going to put me on a long
slow death march, I would have told them, 'Let's start walking,'''
said Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., a former prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The plea bargain prompted U.S. District Judge James Parker to
apologize to Lee for the nine-month pretrial imprisonment and to
say that government officials in charge of the case had embarrassed
''our entire nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers had offered prosecutors a similar bargain earlier,
Specter said. ''The underlying question is ... whether the
government could have gotten the same deal in December if you had
pursued it,'' Specter said, and spared Lee the time spent in jail
and the government the cost of prosecution since then.
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson said: ''I don't have any doubt in the world ...
that the government could not have gotten this arrangement any time
before it was negotiated in this very extensive way over this very
extended period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeh also said Tuesday one of the reasons they decided against
going to court was that FBI Agent Robert Messemer had admitted
giving false testimony during a bail hearing for Lee. ''While we do
not believe this error significantly undercut the overall evidence
against Doctor Lee, it did affect the agent's creditability and
thereby damaged the prosecution,'' Freeh said.
</P>
<P>
   But Messemer simply made a mistake, FBI lawyer Larry Parkinson
said. ''He said he made an honest mistake and the judge did not
challenge his characterization of it,'' he said. ''I know Agent
Messemer has been flatly condemned as a liar and that is unfair to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Messemer is now being investigated by the FBI's Office
of Professional Responsibility, which is triggered any time a judge
questions an agent's testimony, Parkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to Tuesday's hearing, the hearing was halted after
Democrats invoked a Senate rule that limits committee hearings when
the Senate is in session. Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., asked for the
action to protest what he called the Republicans' failure to
approve judicial nominees.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Energy Department: http://www.doe.gov
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department: http://www.usdoj.gov/
</P>
<P>
   FBI: http://www.fbi.gov
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee: http://judiciary.senate.gov/
</P>
<P>
   WenHoLee.org: http://www.wenholee.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1616 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia To Halt Afghan Refugee Flood  </HEADLINE>
By LIDA ISAMOVA
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUSHANBE, Tajikistan (AP) -- Tens of thousands of frightened
Afghanis fled intensified fighting toward Tajikistan on Wednesday,
and Russian and Tajik troops braced to turn back a refugee flood at
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov called for the United
Nations to push for talks between Afghanistan's warring factions,
saying there is no military solution to the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian envoy, Sergei Yastrzhembsky, was in Islamabad and
urged Pakistan to help close training camps for Islamic militants
in Afghanistan. Pakistan is considered an ally of the Taliban
militia that claim to control 95 percent of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Russia fears that a Taliban victory in all of Afghanistan would
boost the spread of armed Islamic movements throughout Central
Asia. Tajikistan is still scarred from a five-year civil war with
Islamic forces that ended in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Russia also contends that the Taliban have been aiding rebels
fighting Russian forces in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 135,000 Afghanis were believed to be heading toward
the Tajik border Wednesday, a flood that could overwhelm the
country's resources.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has about 25,000 troops and border guards in Tajikistan.
Their commander, Gen. Alexander Markin, declared that ''we will
take all the necessary measures to prevent border violations and
keep refugees from getting into Tajikistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Some refugees from the fighting were already camping on islands
in the Pyandz River that marks the boundary between Tajikistan and
Afghanistan, Markin said. He said the fighting they were fleeing
was getting closer -- tanks and artillery were seen in combat just
six miles from the border.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russian border guards are strong enough to stop any
provocations,'' he said, but Russia and former Soviet Central Asian
states are clearly concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov's call for greater U.N. efforts was echoed by Uzbek
President Islam Karimov, who lambasted the world organization for
limiting its efforts on Afghanistan to ''sanctions that don't
frighten anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurgents trying to carve out an Islamic state in the area
where Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan meet are believed to
have received training in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, although apparently few in number, have been
tenacious fighters. Uzbek and Kyrgyz troops have failed to wipe out
the rebels in fighting that has dragged on since last month.
</P>
<P>
   Russian and Tajik troops began joint four-day maneuvers Tuesday.
Border guards say there have been no major incidents since last
week, when artillery shells fired by the Taliban at the opposition
landed in Tajikistan. No one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban have won a string of victories this month, driving
the northern-based opposition alliance into an isolated northeast
corner of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1625 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Refugees Flee to Tajikstan  </HEADLINE>
By LIDA ISAMOVA
