<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FTC To Allow Boeing To Buy Hughes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. and European regulators will allow Boeing
Co.'s $3.75 billion purchase of Hughes Electronics Corp.'s space
and communications division, though Boeing will have to undertake
measures to prohibit a competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC said Wednesday that the moves are necessary to prevent
Boeing from potentially raising costs to other competitors or
having access to information that would reduce competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''This consent agreement will ensure that competition in the
highly specialized markets for satellites and launch vehicles will
be maintained,'' said Richard Parker, the FTC's competition bureau
director.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing president Harry Stonecipher said the restrictions would
not be a problem for the acquired company, which will be run
separately as a subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ''The restrictions themselves don't cause us any anguish,''
Stonecipher said. ''They're the kinds of things we would be doing
in the business anyway. But, certainly, having them written down
made the outside world feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately on Wednesday, European Union antitrust regulators
approved the deal after its own probe into its impact on the
European satellite market.
</P>
<P>
   ''The investigation dismissed earlier doubts that the operation
could significantly strengthen Hughes' position in commercial
geostationary communication satellites as well as the concern that
the parties might induce Hughes' satellite customers to procure
launch services from Boeing,'' said a statement from the European
Commission in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The EC said it had worked closely with the U.S. antitrust
authorities on the case and that its decision ''does not prejudice
the outcome of the assessment in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the U.S. agreement, Boeing could no longer provide systems
engineering and technical assistance services to the Defense
Department for a classified program. The FTC said Boeing is the
sole supplier of a particular unidentified classified program and
Hughes is one of two competing contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's launch vehicle division also could not have access to
nonpublic information its satellite division receives from
competing suppliers and must ''erect firewalls'' between its
satellite and launch vehicle divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also would be required to provide satellite interface
information to all other launch vehicle suppliers. The agreement
also appoints a trustee to ensure Boeing complies.
</P>
<P>
   Stonecipher said integrating satellite building with Boeing's
launch facilities wasn't Boeing's intent when it agreed to buy
Hughes' satellite arm. He cited Hughes' ''intellectual capital'' as
a huge asset, pointing to the joint contract for new U.S. spy
satellites recently won by Hughes and Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Stonecipher noted that their communications expertise would help
Boeing to provide wireless Internet access on board its commercial
jetliners.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to be the Yahoo! in the air,'' Stonecipher said.
''That means if somebody's eyeballs fall on a screen on an
airplane, they're going to be able to participate in e-commerce
right from their seat. We're going to be in that revenue stream and
Hughes is going to be a player in helping us be there.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is subject to public comment until Oct. 27. The
FTC then will decide whether to give final approval.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing shares closed down $1.50 Wednesday at $64.56 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1745 </TRAILER>
