<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Partisanship on Drugs Resumes  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans and Democrats in Congress agreed
Wednesday that prescription drug coverage for Medicare recipients
is more important than partisan politics, then swiftly resumed
campaign-season warfare over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''Democrats were AWOL'' when Republicans pushed their
legislation through the House earlier in the year, charged Rep.
Bill Thomas, R-Calif. As for Vice President Al Gore and his
campaign rhetoric on the subject, Thomas said the Democratic
presidential candidate ''appears to be a pathological
prevaricator'' -- a liar in plainer, dictionary terms.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats rolled wheelbarrows piled high with empty drug
vials along a sidewalk outside the Capitol in a made-for-television
event designed to dramatize the urgency of helping Medicare
recipients cope with the high cost of medicine. Senior citizens
walked alongside, some holding their pill bottles aloft.
</P>
<P>
   ''For months Republicans in Congress have blocked these benefits
in the name of sham bills that don't provide universal coverage --
that don't help people who truly need it -- and that the president
will not sign,'' said Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri.
''They have blocked these benefits as a favor to the pharmaceutical
companies and the insurance industry.''
</P>
<P>
   With rhetoric hardening on both sides, the prospect for
legislation appeared dim beyond an effort to allow reimportation of
drugs from Canada, where they are less expensive than in the 50
states.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, several Republicans said during the day that a
plan to pass year-end prescription drug coverage for low-income
seniors, possibly by tacking it onto an unrelated spending bill,
was losing favor among GOP leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats generally favor establishment of prescription drug
coverage under Medicare, a system in which seniors would pay a
monthly premium in exchange for a standard benefit. Republicans
generally oppose that approach.
</P>
<P>
   The House has passed a GOP measure that relies on subsidies to
the insurance industry as an inducement to offer prescription drug
coverage. Several proposals are circulating in the Senate,
including one that would help low-income seniors while deferring
further action until next year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent exchanges of letters among President Clinton and
congressional leaders, Democrats and Republicans have each rejected
the other's approach and stepped up the political maneuvering
despite periodic declarations that partisanship isn't important.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's too important for partisan politics,'' said Rep. Ernie
Fletcher, R-Ky., a physician in a tough re-election fight.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that helping all seniors with skyrocketing
prescription prices is more important than partisan politics,''
Gephardt and 179 other Democrats wrote House Speaker Dennis
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   But six weeks before the election, the prescription drug issue
has emerged as a key concern among voters, and while most polls
show Democrats hold a preference over Republicans on the issue, the
GOP has been making a strong effort to gain ground.
</P>
<P>
   The debate mirrors the presidential campaign, where Gore and
Bush have swapped charges over their differing approaches to the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans criticize the Democratic approach as a ''big
government'' solution to the problem, and liken it to the plan for
universal health care that Clinton sought in 1994. ''The Bush plan
provides seniors prescription drug coverage without a
'Hillary-style' national drug plan,'' says one piece of mail the
Republicans sent to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the Gore plan you have no choice, no flexibility,'' it
says. ''You get one chance to join his proposed prescription drug
plan - at age 64 1/2. After that, you are left out forever. It's
the Gore plan for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats seized upon the same letter during the day to
underscore their claim that Republicans have historically opposed
Medicare, and are attacking a proposed benefit that would be a
companion to existing coverage for doctor bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Republicans' dirty little secret is finally out. The only
problem that they have with Al Gore and the Democrat prescription
drug plan is that it's run by Medicare,'' said Jenny Backus, a
Democratic spokeswoman. ''We've always knon that they were opposed
to Medicare. Now they're saying it in TV ads and mail pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the letter suggested Republicans were
sharpening their attack on Gore's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   It describes the monthly premium as an ''access fee,'' and says
it would be ''deducted from your Social Security check.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare premiums are currently paid from Social Security
benefits.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   House of Representatives: http://www.house.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Senate: http://www.senate.gov/
</P>
<P>
   To search bills by keyword: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
