<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Up Before Denmark Referendum  </HEADLINE>
By MIRANDA LEITSINGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro edged slightly higher against the
dollar and other major currencies Wednesday, an indication that
Friday's joint intervention was providing a solid short-term base
for Europe's ailing currency.
</P>
<P>
   ''It at least has broken the psychology,'' said Ricardo Gomes,
head of foreign exchange at HSBC USA. ''Those people that were
hedging are starting to come to the market. They know that the
Central Bank is going to act as a base.''
</P>
<P>
   The euro maintained its post-intervention gains Wednesday,
supported by steady yen and dollar sales.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 88.30 cents, up
from 88.27 cents late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Compared to the activity over the last few days, it was a
relatively calm day,'' Gomes said. ''The ranges were reasonably
narrow. In New York, it stayed in the 87.00 and 88.60 range.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Federal Reserve unexpectedly joined the European
Central Bank and the Bank of Japan Friday to stop the euro's free
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Now all eyes are on the next event that could affect the euro:
the Danish referendum on the single currency. On Thursday, Denmark
will vote on whether to join 11 other European Union countries in
replacing its national currency with the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democratic-led government strongly favors replacing
the 125-year-old Danish krone, but the latest polls show the
referendum remains too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   The market has already prepared itself for a 'no' vote, Gomes
said, adding that he did not expect any dramatic changes if the
Danes reject the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of Thursday's vote, Gomes said that currency traders
expected there to be a ''continued upside pressure on the euro.
It's the idea that with the euro, people are working on a short
term bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   In other trading, the dollar also was quoted at 107.29 Japanese
yen, down from 107.64 yen.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 1.7253 Swiss francs, down from
1.7290, and 1.4968 Canadian dollars, almost unchanged from 1.4869.
The British pound rose to $1.4620 from $1.4607.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth 2.2153 German
marks, down from 2.2220; 7.4301 French francs, down from 7.4524;
and 2193.20 Italian lire, down from 2,198.93.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
