<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giordano campaign chief dismissed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATERBURY, Conn (AP ) - With just six weeks to go in his
long-shot bid for U.S. Senate, Waterbury Mayor Philip Giordano has
dismissed his campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Longino, who left his job as mayoral chief of staff to
run Giordano's campaign, left the campaign last week, campaign
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing Longino's departure earlier this week, Giordano
initially denied any rift and said the two men parted by ''mutual
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Waterbury Republican-American reported Wednesday that
Longino lost his job because he failed to disclose that his
girlfriend's father runs a printing company Longino hired to print
campaign literature. Giordano's campaign paid Totalgraphics Inc. of
South Norwalk more than $300,000, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Company president Richard Marino is the father of Longino's
girlfriend, Jennifer Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Totalgraphics received $305,000 in business from the Giordano
for U.S. Senate Committee to print campaign literature, the
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Longino said he has been dating Jennifer Marino for a little
more than a year, but that he's used Totalgraphics for at least two
years.
</P>
<P>
   But Giordano said there have been discrepancies with invoices
from Totalgraphics and that some bills were overpaid. Campaign
officials were scheduled to visit Totalgraphics Wednesday to seek
reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're working with the company to clear up the invoice
problem. They have agreed there were errors and they will be
returning money to the campaign,'' Giordano said. ''I'm glad we can
work this out...and get back to the mission of winning on Nov. 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials said Wednesday that Longino had long been
planning to leave his $2,500-per-week campaign post and return to
his job as captain in the Waterbury Fire Department, but that the
disclosure over the printing issue hastened his departure.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano's friends told the newspaper he is angry and hurt over
what he perceives as a betrayal by a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   But Longino said Wednesday that the printing controversy had
nothing to do with his decision to leave the campaign. Instead,
Longino said he left because the campaign didn't have enough money
to pay him.
</P>
<P>
   Longino, a divorced father of three, told the Associated Press
that he could not afford to rely on the struggling campaign to pay
his bills. Giordano, who trailed Lieberman by 53 percentage points
in a recent Quinnipiac University poll, has had trouble raising
money.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano himself provided the campaign's biggest boost with a
$300,000 line of credit that he secured with his house and a
savings certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The campaign doesn't have any money. They can't pay me,''
Longino said.
</P>
<P>
   Longino also said he has reimbursed the campaign $250 for
personal calls he made on a campaign cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Longino, who ran all three of Giordano's mayoral campaigns and
briefly served as his chief of staff, acknowledged that his
relationship with Giordano has been ''strained'' by the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's very frustrated,'' Longino said of Giordano. ''On a
personal note I think he's finally realizing that after nine
campaigns, you can't always win. It's a tough road running against
a guy who's running for vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Longino's departure leaves campaign manager Jim Paolino as the
top staffer. Paolino said Wednesday that Giordano will
''definitely'' air TV ads in the next few weeks criticizing
Lieberman. Paolino also predicted that the race will tighten as
voters grow weary of Lieberman's insistence on running for two
offices at the same time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-27-00 1813 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
