<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Blocks Bailey NHTSA Bid  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain is blocking a vote on
President Clinton's nominee to lead the government's auto safety
agency, saying that Sue Bailey did not completely disclose to his
committee all the contributions she has made to Democratic
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey wrote McCain, chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee,
on Wednesday to apologize for the ''most embarrassing oversight.''
She included a complete list of her political giving.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always intended to provide a complete list of information
about my 10 years of contributions, and it was an oversight that
that didn't happen,'' said Bailey, the former assistant secretary
of defense for health affairs who is line to head the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
   A McCain aide said Wednesday that the Arizona Republican was
reviewing Bailey's documents.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's committee last week recommended approval of Bailey,
acting administrator since August. But McCain, R-Ariz., learned
later that Bailey had contributed more than $119,000 to Democratic
campaigns since 1992 instead of the $53,000 she reported to the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Using Senate rules, McCain has blocked his colleagues, who must
approve the nomination, from voting on Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ''We find this discovery especially troubling in light of the
fact that you swore to the accuracy of your statements to the
committee,'' McCain wrote Bailey on Tuesday. ''A number of these
contributions were very recent, so there should not be much cause
for confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute comes amid Capitol Hill's focus on the agency for
its investigation of Bridgestone/Firestone Inc.'s recall of 6.5
million Firestone tires that have been linked to 101 U.S. traffic
deaths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
