<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Mideast Peace Is Possible  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton says a Middle East peace
agreement remains possible but elusive, and success requires all
sides to ''leap off into the future together.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Palestinian official offered little hope for continuing
negotiations, predicting that the meetings would end Thursday after
just three days.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that these negotiations will end tomorrow,'' Hassan
Abdel Rahman, the Palestinian representative in Washington, said
Wednesday. But he added, ''Efforts are ongoing to breach gaps
between the Israeli and Palestinian positions on all the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Israeli and Palestinian negotiators returned here at
Clinton's request Tuesday to try once more to arrange a
comprehensive peace settlement. The two sides remain deadlocked
over the future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't say there will be; I can't say there won't be,''
Clinton said when asked if an agreement is reachable. ''We're
working as hard as we know how,'' he told reporters in the Rose
Garden of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can do it,'' he said. ''But it will require what these
difficult things always require: a remarkable convergence of both
sides willing to make difficult decisions and kind of leap off into
the future together.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, actions by lawmakers on Capitol Hill threatened to
hamper the negotiations. The House voted 385-27 Wednesday to cut
off all except humanitarian aid to the Palestinians should Yasser
Arafat unilaterally declare a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said they were concerned Arafat would act after
Congress adjourns for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's vote reaffirms that the United States will not support
any Palestinian entity that is not created through peaceful
negotiations with Israel,'' said Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But Abdel Rahman said, ''Without any doubt this vote will affect
the credibility of the United States as a mediator in the peace
process and the possibility of playing a more active role in this
process.''
</P>
<P>
   The House measure does not allow for U.S. recognition of a
Palestinian state in any way. The president also would be
authorized to withhold payment and U.S. contributions to any
international organization that recognizes a unilaterally declared
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli delegation was headed by Foreign Minister Shlomo
Ben-Ami, and the Palestinians' by senior negotiator Saeb Erekat.
</P>
<P>
   The parties met with Clinton in New York earlier in the month,
but the deadlock over Jerusalem persisted. In July, Clinton was
unable to persuade Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to compromise on that and other issues at a summit
meeting at Camp David, the presidential retreat in western
Maryland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1820 </TRAILER>
