<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine's TV spending no guarantee for ultimate ratings in election </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Jon Corzine is spending an average of $1.7
million a week to tell people who watch television he should be the
U.S. senator from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic contender is even ponying up about $5 million for
commercials aired during coverage of the Olympic games.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he's done, the one-time Wall Street financier will
have spent almost $12 million on TV advertising in New York and
Philadelphia for the nine weeks of the fall campaign. That could
put the Corzine campaign's total outlay close to $50 million for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   TV contracts might guarantee Corzine viewers, but they won't
necessarily deliver voters.
</P>
<P>
   And all that money might be wasted if New Jersey voters do what
they did in 1996: Turn out to vote and then tune out the Senate
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all living through a first. None of us have ever seen
anything like this before,'' said Ingrid Reed, director of the
Eagleton Institute's Project New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden State is home to a traditionally independent
electorate, a majority of which makes its mind up in the days
before Election Day, not weeks or months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   So are Corzine's millions being spent now in advertising wasted?
No one is really sure.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe this is just a waste of money. You just really don't
know,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Election watchers have seen enough for them to know what might
prompt a large voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   One example is the last statewide race for U.S. Senate in 1996,
when 72 percent of registered voters actually voted. Only 31
percent voted in the 1999 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the Senate race between Democrat Bob Torricelli
and Republican Dick Zimmer drew national attention for its negative
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   But it appeared to be competitive, one reason people say they
feel compelled to vote, according to Reed.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of voter turnout seems to depend on whether people feel
their vote will be important,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 election also featured the presidential election, which
usually draws a larger turnout. But many New Jersey voters skipped
over the choice for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers can't be certain, but ''it's likely there was a
connection'' between the negative campaign and the voter drop off,
Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Jerseyans have a reputation for being able to tiptoe their
way around the ballot,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Voters do want to know their candidates and Corzine's
advertising on television can help there, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But voters might see the spending itself as an issue and avoid
either Corzine the candidate or the Senate race altogether, Reed
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At what point do people say enough already. We don't know if
that turns them off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One early return is in, at least on a portion of Corzine's
advertising. And the number's aren't necessarily good for the
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   National Nielsen ratings for the Olympic games are 35 percent
lower than those from Atlanta in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In one early stretch, a week when television contracts showed
Corzine paid $63,000 for several 30-second commercial spots,
ratings were the lowest for any Olympics since the 1960s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-27-00 1836 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
