<DOCNO> APW20000927.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill for Auto Industry Passed  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Auto industry executives who withhold
information on defective products that kill or injure consumers
could be sentenced to up to 15 years in prison under legislation
that passed a House Commerce subcommittee on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed unanimously 23-0, originally did not
contain criminal penalties -- a provision strongly opposed by the
auto industry, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and other business
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., offered the amendment to add them, but
admitted he is not an expert at criminal law and said that the
House Judiciary Committee would review the provision.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin said the goal was not to punish executives after someone
is killed, but to use the threat of jail time to get company
officials to admit problems when they are discovered. He said if
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. and Ford Motor Co. had gone to U.S.
regulators earlier with information about defects in Firestone
tires, some of the 101 deaths and more than 400 injuries being
investigated in the case might have been prevented.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our job is to try to prevent casualties in the first place,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would increase the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration's authority to collect information about possibly
defective products and expand its budget for investigations.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA is investigating Bridgestone/Firestone's Aug. 9 recall of
6.5 million ATX, ATX II and Wilderness AT tires. The agency has
received more than 2,200 complaints about tread separations,
blowouts and other problems with Firestone tires, usually on the
Ford Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin, a co-sponsor of the legislation and chairman of the
House Commerce consumer protection subcommittee that passed it,
said he amended the bill so that it would be more in line with one
sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., that already cleared the
Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment and the bill were approved without objection. The
bill advances to the full House Commerce Committee, and its
sponsors hope it will pass before Congress adjourns next month.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal penalty provision in the House version is different
from the one in the Senate version. McCain's bill would punish
executives from a company that knowingly produced a defective
product that killed or injured a consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry lobbyists had objected to the wording, saying that
punishing for a ''defect'' is too vague. In the House version,
sponsored by Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., company officials would not
be punished for producing a defect, but for withholding information
from federal regulators about a defect.
</P>
<P>
   Upton's bill also addresses another auto industry concern -- that
the threat of criminal penalties will keep officials from sharing
information with regulators -- by exempting whistleblowers from
being charged.
</P>
<P>
   ''I happen to believe that the approach we took will identify
bad products before we get to serious injury or death versus
punishing someone after the horse is out of the barn,'' Upton said.
</P>
<P>
   Eron Shosteck, spokesman for the Alliance of Automobile
Manufacturers, a coalition of 13 automakers, said Upton's bill was
an improvement over McCain's because it provides a clearer
distinction for when criminal penalties would apply. But he said
the Alliance still opposes criminal penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our members are concerned about legislation moving this
quickly without full consideration of its real-world
consequences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone: http://www.bridgestone-firestone.com
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co.: http://www.ford.com
</P>
<P>
   National Highway Traffic Safety Administration:
http://www.nhtsa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 1841 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group says New Jersey has highest cost for apartment rent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey is tops in the nation when it
comes to the cost of renting apartments and leaders of an advocacy
group said Wednesday that makes affordable housing a crisis in the
Garden State.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of those renting apartments can't afford the
payments on a three-bedroom apartment, said Peter Kasabach, an
executive board member of the Housing and Community Development
Network.
</P>
<P>
   The figure is based on federal standards that say housing is
affordable if rent is less than 30 percent of a person's income,
Kasabach said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Families are working harder, longer hours, yet they continue
to fall further behind in making their housing payments,'' he said
at a Statehouse news conference.
</P>
<P>
   A person being paid the minimum wage would have to work 131
hours a week to earn enough to afford rent, Lucy Voorhoeve said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Or more than three full-time jobs,'' said Voorhoeve, the
group's associate director.
</P>
<P>
   Higher costs force people into substandard housing, Voorhoeve
said. Others face eviction or homelessness, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates cited a study by the National Low Income Housing
Coalition that said the average rent in New Jersey was $878 in
1999. That figure was up $51 from the year before, enough to move
New Jersey above Hawaii for the highest average in the country,
Kasabach said.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people in New Jersey are suffering from this,'' he
said. ''If you don't see that as a crisis, as a major issue, I
don't know what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Adair is a 30-year-old father of two now living in a
shelter with his family in Toms River.
</P>
<P>
   Adair told reporters he earns $1,500 a month, but can't afford
to rent an apartment or house and then pay other costs, including
medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ''My monthly bills come out to $2,000. So what's the answer?''
Adair said.
</P>
<P>
   Kasabach suggested more housing and tax credits for developers
to promote building.
</P>
<P>
   The working poor would also be helped by an increase in state
and federal voucher programs to use in market rentals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also need to be more aggressive to promote the state's
existing affordable housing regulations, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-27-00 1846 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel OKs Auto Penalties  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Auto industry executives who withhold
information on defective products that kill or injure consumers
could be sentenced to up to 15 years in prison under legislation
that passed a House Commerce subcommittee on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed unanimously 23-0, originally did not
contain criminal penalties -- a provision strongly opposed by the
