blowouts and other problems with Firestone tires, usually on the
Ford Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin, a co-sponsor of the legislation and chairman of the
House Commerce consumer protection subcommittee that passed it,
said he amended the bill so that it would be more in line with one
sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., that already cleared the
Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment and the bill were approved without objection. The
bill advances to the full House Commerce Committee, and its
sponsors hope it will pass before Congress adjourns next month.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal penalty provision in the House version is different
from the one in the Senate version. McCain's bill would punish
executives from a company that knowingly produced a defective
product that killed or injured a consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry lobbyists had objected to the wording, saying that
punishing for a ''defect'' is too vague. In the House version,
sponsored by Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., company officials would not
be punished for producing a defect, but for withholding information
from federal regulators about a defect.
</P>
<P>
   Upton's bill also addresses another auto industry concern -- that
the threat of criminal penalties will keep officials from sharing
information with regulators -- by exempting whistleblowers from
being charged.
</P>
<P>
   ''I happen to believe that the approach we took will identify
bad products before we get to serious injury or death versus
punishing someone after the horse is out of the barn,'' Upton said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone: http://www.bridgestone-firestone.com
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co.: http://www.ford.com
</P>
<P>
   National Highway Traffic Safety Administration:
http://www.nhtsa.gov
</P>
