<HEADLINE> Summit Bancorp's shares up another 11 percent on sale rumor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) - Summit Bancorp's shares rose more than 11
percent Wednesday on rumors that FleetBoston Financial Corp. is in
talks to acquire the company.
</P>
<P>
   Summit's stock also rose by 11 percent Tuesday as word of the
potential sale circulated.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported in Wednesday's editions that
the Boston-based Fleet was in talks to acquire Princeton-based
Summit, which has a market capitalization of $5.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Citing unnamed sources, the newspaper also reported that Summit
may be in talks with other potential buyers as well, and cautioned
that talks with Fleet could fall apart ''at any time.''.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a rumor that was reported,'' said Summit spokesman Steve
Lubetkin. ''We don't comment on rumor and speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet spokesman James Mahoney also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Summit closed at 34.31 on the New York Stock Exchange, up $3.56,
or 11.58 percent. On Tuesday, Summit's shares rose another 11
percent, or $3, to $30.75.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's stock rose by .025, or 0.64 percent at Wednesday's close
of 38.93.
</P>
<P>
   Summit operates more than 500 branches in New Jersey,
Connecticut and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston is the nation's No. 8 bank, with $180 billion in
assets and about 1,200 branches.
</P>
