<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capano seeks to overturn death penalty; cites U.S. Supreme Court decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) - Convicted murderer Thomas Capano has
asked the Delaware Supreme Court to throw out his death sentence on
the grounds that a recent U.S. Supreme Court decision effectively
voids the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed this week, Capano's lawyers said the June 26
ruling by the high court leaves the decision of whether capital
punishment should be meted out in the hands of a jury, not a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding Judge William Swain Lee ordered Capano to death row
after the wealthy, politically influential lawyer was convicted in
January 1999 of killing his 30-year-old mistress, Anne Marie Fahey.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend Capano shot Fahey, then stuffed her body in
a cooler and dumped it in the Atlantic Ocean off the coast of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   With neither the body or the murder weapon ever recovered,
prosecutors relied on circumstantial evidence to prove that Capano
planned to kill Fahey because she wanted to end their affair.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the jury voted 11-1 that Fahey's murder was
premeditated by Capano. Capano's lawyers say the jury should have
decided unanimously that Capano had planned out the murder in order
for capital punishment to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court this summer, the justices
decided in a New Jersey case that only a jury may decide whether a
case contains special circumstances, such as premeditation of
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Also, that jury's decision must be unanimous, according to the
papers filed by Capano's nine-member defense team.
</P>
<P>
   The question of premeditation in Capano's case was crucial
because it was the single aggravating factor that made him eligible
for capital punishment. In Capano's case, it was Lee, not the jury,
who made the decision that Capano was eligible for death by
injection.
</P>
<P>
   Capano's lawyers are asking for a new penalty phase, where
Capano may be considered for life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Delaware Supreme Court is expected to hear Capano's appeal
on Oct. 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
