<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Famed theater organist's death doesn't signal an end of the art  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - When Lee Erwin played the theater organ in old
fashioned movie palaces, friends say his boney hands resembled two
tarantulas fighting on the keyboard but the sounds he created were
like a string of pearls massaging your ears.
</P>
<P>
   Those close to Erwin say the former Alabama boy who went off to
study music in France and became famous plying his trade in
Cincinnati, then in New York City, and finally across the country,
really, truly, was that good.
</P>
<P>
   With a twinge of sadness but mostly awe and gratitude, family
and friends celebrated Erwin's life at a funeral Wednesday at a
Harlem church. He died at age 92 on Sept. 21, nearly 18 months
after a fall left him incapable of playing publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Some may worry that since Erwin was one of the last remaining
original theater organists, his death might signal an end to the
art. But due in part to people like him, the love for the theater
organ is still alive - even if most people don't know a thing about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I met Lee 20 years ago when I became interested in silent
film, which is not a field you go into,'' Ben Model told mourners
at St. Luke's Episcopal Church. Model, 37, added that Erwin prodded
him to expand his interest in silent films to playing the
instrument, saying ''There are no young organists!''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the lack of knowledge about the art results because few
people these days other than devotees have heard a theater organ
accompanying silent movies.
</P>
<P>
   Gillian Anderson, an orchestra conductor and film restorer, says
she doesn't approve of the label ''silent films'' because organs
almost always played throughout the show. A former music archivist
at the Library of Congress, she prefers the term ''early films.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Anderson, theater organ enthusiasts are like other
serious collectors - but more fanatic. It's not uncommon for people
to knock walls out of their homes to install an organ, or even
build a new house around the instrument. The fervor grows out of
fans' love for the instrument's peculiarity, says Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ''The theater organ, far more than the piano, when it's played
at its best, is really capable of getting the power of an
orchestra,'' she said. ''But it also requires a lot of maintenance.
I guess though if you're prepared to take out the side of your
house to install it, you definitely are the sort who will be
prepared to keep it maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   Theater organs are similar to church organs but typically have
fewer sound-emitting pipes. In later models, however, each pipe
could make multiple sounds. And some were equipped to create sound
effects like honking cars, train whistles, sleigh bells and police
sirens.
</P>
<P>
   But Erwin took theater organ playing in a different direction.
He believed the music should never call attention to itself and
complained when other organ players used gimmicks, as if to scream
''look at me!''
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Erwin told The New York Times: ''It's always a
compliment after a film when people come up and say, 'You know, I
completely forgot that you were playing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, his innovations continued, whether it was
playing at Radio City, on the radio for a late-night show in
Cincinnati entitled ''Moon River,'' or on TV for the ''Arthur
Godfrey Show.''
</P>
<P>
   After many huge old theaters were knocked down around the
country, Erwin championed their past by traveling to places like
Atlanta, or Wichita, Kan., or Akron, Ohio, where he played
surviving instruments. He also helped start a silent film festival
at the Cathedral of St. John the Divine in New York that has become
an annual event on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had a marvelous sense of imagination and he had a subtle
ear that made him able to improvise anything,'' said Joseph Erwin,
who showed his own organ skills by performing a few of his older
brother's favorites during the funeral. ''He never played what was
on the page, unless it was classical. He could make pop music of
his day to be as moving as the New York Philharmonic with a great
conductor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-27-00 1922 </TRAILER>
