<HEADLINE> Three killed in crash near Conshohocken identified  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CONSHOHOCKEN, Pa. (AP) - Two men and a woman in their early 20s
were identified through dental records Wednesday as victims in a
fiery 13-car, chain-reaction accident in the Philadelphia suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   James Millard, 23, and Nicholas Litterio, 22, both of East
Stroudsburg, died when their pickup truck was hit from behind by a
tractor-trailer while traveling early Monday on Interstate 76. The
impact pushed their vehicle into a Hyundai driven by Tiffany
Davies, 20, of Mt. Laurel, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Several others were injured, one critically, in the early
morning accident that shut down the highway used heavily by
commuters traveling to and from Philadelphia, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   A tractor-trailer and about 10 more vehicles were involved in
the accident in the westbound lanes of the highway at about 12:30
a.m. Monday near the Conshohocken exit in Montgomery County, police
said. The area of the highway is known as the Conshohocken curve
and is a frequent spot for traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Several vehicles and the cab of the tractor trailer caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from the scene indicated the accident may have happened
after traffic slowed from an earlier accident, which happened just
after midnight. Debris was spread over about 100 yards of the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   State police in Philadelphia identified the tractor-trailer
driver as Walter Seifert, 64, of Groton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Seifert was hauling 18,000 pounds of soy products.
Montgomery County District Attorney said Tuesday that Seifert was
cooperating with investigators. He told them he did not have time
to stop when he saw the traffic jam.
</P>
</TEXT>
