<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NiMo, National Grid face Assembly leaders over proposed NiMo acquisition </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - It is too early to say how National Grid
Group's proposed purchase of Niagara Mohawk would affect the rates
of NiMo customers, officials of the power companies told Assembly
leaders examining the planned merger Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after National Grid announced the $3 billion cash
and stock deal, the British firm is just beginning to assess
consumer impact, said Lawrence Reilly, director of National Grid
USA.
</P>
<P>
   While National Grid expects to save about $90 million a year
through consolidation and improved efficiency, it is unknown
whether the savings will translate into lower rates for customers,
Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   At the first in a series of planned public hearings, Reilly and
Niagara Mohawk's chief financial officer, William Edwards, said the
merger would strengthen Niagara Mohawk, allowing it to stabilize
energy delivery prices and improve customer service. Niagara Mohawk
provides electricity to 1.55 million New York customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think this agreement offers benefits and opportunities for
our customers, our shareholders, our employees and all other
stakeholders,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Sheldon Silver, presiding over the hearing, said
ratepayers have too often been forgotten in agreements reached
between utilities and the state's Public Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''At a time when businesses and families are dealing with rising
oil, gas and natural gas prices, it is time to put the customer
first,'' the Manhattan Democrat said.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Chairman Paul Tonko said the proposed merger, the first
of its kind in New York state, ''requires an unprecedented level of
scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only should its effects on shareholders and ratepayers be
assessed, Tonko said, but also its potential impact on the economy
of upstate New York and Niagara Mohawks' work force.
</P>
<P>
   National Grid said it anticipates trimming 500 to 750 positions
over a four-year period through attrition and voluntary programs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, Niagara Mohawk would merge with another
electric system that National Grid owns and operates in three New
England states. The resulting company would be the ninth largest
utility in the country, with more than 3.3 million customers over
29,000 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk would continue operating under its present name
and retain its operating headquarters in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   National Grid USA expects that within four years, it will save
as much as $90 million annually through consolidation and improved
efficiency across its New England and New York operations.
</P>
<P>
   Future hearings will focus on the effects of the proposed merger
on workers, the upstate economy, change-in-control issues, local
community impacts and the role of regulators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
