<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accused money launderer asks court to drop racketeering charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - A Colombian accused of being one of the
''most significant money launderers in the world'' is seeking to
have racketeering charges against him dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Stroh claim the statute of limitations on the
charges, which date back to the 1980s, has expired. In U.S.
District Court Tuesday, they urged Senior U.S. District Judge Alan
H. Nevas to dismiss the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in Bridgeport indicted Stroh and two of his
Panamanian corporations in July 1996. They are charged with
violation the federal Racketeer Influenced Organizations Act by
running a money-laundering operation and structuring financial
transactions to avoid federal reporting rules for the Cali drug
cartel.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment remained sealed until Stroh's arrest in Miami on
Feb. 14, 2000. It identifies 20 banks between Stamford and
Bridgeport where $271,000 was exchanged in 64 transactions between
July 14 and July 21, 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Appleton argued that in 1987
alone Jose E. Stroh's operations laundered $129 million for the
Cali drug cartel.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not low-level,'' Appleton said. ''This is one of the
most significant money launderers in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Slotnick of New York, a lawyer for Stroh, told the judge
his client withdrew from the conspiracy and returned to Israel in
1988. Slotnick said he has a passport, witnesses and government
documents to prove that.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge said Slotnick's request was unprecedented.
''You've cited no cases in which a trial judge has dismissed an
indictment under these circumstances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge reserved decision on Slotnick's request and gave him
until Monday to submit additional documentation.
</P>
</TEXT>
