<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wheel guards lacking at garage where car crashed through wall  </HEADLINE>
By SONJA BARISIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) - A parking deck where four New York
nurses were killed when their car crashed through a wall lacked
concrete wheel guards designed to prevent vehicles from hitting the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   But it was unclear whether the Sandcastle Resort Hotel's garage
had to have such wheel guards under the national building code in
force when it was built. City officials confirmed the absence of
wheel guards but said Wednesday they had not yet determined whether
any building codes were violated.
</P>
<P>
   The four women died Sunday when their car broke through a
3-foot-tall wall and plunged 41 feet, landing on a beach access
path.
</P>
<P>
   Building Officials and Code Administrators International, based
in Country Club Hills, Ill., drafts and updates construction codes
that many states have adopted. The codes have the force of law in
Virginia. The garage was built in 1985, under 1981 code rules.
</P>
<P>
   The 1981 BOCA code requires parking garages with open sides to
have a parapet wall or guardrail to prevent vehicles from going off
the side, said Ken Schoonover, BOCA's vice president of codes and
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The code also requires a wheel guard at least six inches high to
prevent vehicles from striking the wall or guardrail, Schoonover
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the wall is strong enough to handle the impact of a
vehicle, such wheel stops are not needed and the building would
comply with the intent of the code, Schoonover said.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the garage wall and how it was built need to be
determined, Schoonover said. ''You can't draw a firm conclusion
just based on the fact that it was cinder block,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There also may be questions as to whether the rooftop originally
was intended for parking and whether wheel stops were there and
were removed at some point, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Scott, the city's planning director, added, ''We want
to have a discussion with code officials so we get to the bottom of
this. This should not be a rush to judgment here. We need to get
the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotel manager Varshid Vachhani did not return a telephone call
seeking comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   City real estate records show that John W. Vakos Sr., who owned
the hotel when the garage was added, sold the hotel to Sandcastle
Resorts L.L.C. for $7.5 million last year. A telephone number for
Vakos could not be found Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Driver Joan Ellen Walsh, 56; Mary Ann Going, 60; Kathleen M.
Mollick-Kelly, 63; and Mary Ann Dono, 60, died upon impact. They
had been vacationing from their jobs at St. Vincent's hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the car was moving no faster than 10 mph when it
struck the wall, which had no reinforcement and crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the crash has not been determined, but police have
ruled out mechanical failure and alcohol as factors. Some witnesses
said it appeared that the driver failed to brake in time or stepped
on the accelerator instead of the brake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-27-00 1929 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0203 </DOCNO>
