<HEADLINE> Film actors rally for striking colleagues  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A bevy of faces famous from movies and
television gathered Wednesday to lend support to some of their
less-celebrated colleagues, commercial actors who are striking
against the advertising industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''In this most visible of industries, in this most visible of
unions, they are the people who are overlooked,'' Richard Dreyfuss
said at a rally sponsored by the Screen Actors Guild and the
American Federation of Television and Radio Artists.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts, Mia Farrow, Rosie O'Donnell, Susan Sarandon, Tim
Robbins and Billy Baldwin were among the celebrities who came out
to support the strikers, who they emphasized were not famous
millionaires but poorly paid workers trying to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ''This industry can afford an honest wage,'' Dreyfuss said.
''They can afford a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders continued meeting with advertising industry
representatives in an effort to end a strike that is nearly five
months old, the longest in Hollywood history.
</P>
<P>
   ''The little guy is not going to roll over for corporate
America,'' Sarandon said, drawing loud cheers from union members.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Shepard, a negotiator for the advertisers, did not
immediately return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   SAG and AFTRA want actors to be get ''pay-for-play'' residuals
for ads on cable television, as they are now paid for network
spots, and also want jurisdiction over commercials shot for the
Internet. Advertisers are seeking to pay actors a flat fee for all
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Actors say that would make it nearly impossible for them to make
a living.
</P>
<P>
   ''The question will ultimately become whether this will be able
to be a profession or a hobby,'' said union member Russell Horton,
who until the strike started did commercial voice-overs.
</P>
<P>
   The strike is the first major Hollywood walkout in 12 years. It
affects only radio and TV commercials, not movies or television
series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
