<HEADLINE> Verizon service complaints up nearly ninefold from 1995-99  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Complaints about Verizon Communications
repair and installation service in New Jersey rose nearly ninefold
in five years, but still remain a tiny fraction of its 4 million
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Public Utilities received 1,995 complaints
about service in 1999, compared to 205 in 1995. Some 2,365
complaints have been recorded so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995-99, the number of Verizon lines rose 25 percent, to
6.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon, formed in June by the merge of Bell Atlantic Corp. and
GTE Corp., controls 99 percent of local phone service for homes in
New Jersey. Verizon provides telephone service to some 95 million
U.S. homes in 30 states and to an additional 25 million wireless
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Service complaints involve phone repair, delayed or improper
installation, tree trimming and missed appointments, BPU
spokeswoman Angela Adekola said. They do not involve billing.
</P>
<P>
   The figures were reported Wednesday in The Record of Hackensack.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon-New Jersey president Dennis Bone told The Associated
Press on Wednesday he was uncertain why the increase in complaints
outpaced the growth of the state network, but believes part of it
is related to the changing role of telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   ''Customers use their telephone service, and rely on it today,
far, far differently than they did in the past,'' he said, noting
that few people were connected to the Internet in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, many students do research from home computers, and
if their line is out even a two-day wait makes it difficult to meet
deadlines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know that it explains the phenomena. I know it
explains a little bit of it,'' Bone said.
</P>
<P>
   Bone said that 98 percent of the 200,000 service orders the
company gets a month in the state are processed on time.
</P>
<P>
   Service orders have increased over the past five years, Bone
said, but he could not immediately say by how much.
</P>
<P>
   ''We care about individual customers. But we run a huge and
complex organization, and things happen: a truck breaks down,
someone calls in sick, and you have to reschedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Verizon is seeking permission from the BPU to raise its basic
telephone rates. Bone said the company's proposal would not provide
it with additional revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The BPU has scheduled a third public hearing to hear comments on
the proposal, 1 p.m. Oct. 18 in the Marlboro Township
Administration building.
</P>
<P>
   Senior citizens and consumer advocates complained at hearings
over the past week in Newark and Trenton that the two hearings were
not publicized enough and, for senior citizens, held too late in
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon has proposed raising its basic telephone rate from $8.19
a month to as much as $17.50 a month. The new price would include
three premium services like call waiting and caller ID.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
