<HEADLINE> Joyce becomes a hurricane as Isaac rebuilds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) - Joyce, the 10th named Atlantic storm of the season,
developed into a hurricane Wednesday while Hurricane Isaac rebuilt
its strength after weakening for three days.
</P>
<P>
   Both storms were far out at sea and posed no immediate threat to
land.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was a chance that Joyce, which formed as a
tropical storm Monday off West Africa, could reach the northeastern
Caribbean islands in five to six days, said James Franklin, a
hurricane specialist at the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's still a possibility that it could turn sharply enough
to miss the islands altogether,'' Franklin added.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce's top sustained wind reached 85 mph Wednesday - the
threshold for a hurricane is 74 mph - and it was likely to continue
strengthening into Thursday as it moves across warm ocean water,
forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday evening, Joyce was about 1,270 miles east of the
Windward Islands and moving west at about 14 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac, about 925 miles northwest of Joyce, reached top sustained
winds of 110 mph Wednesday. It had top wind of 120 mph on Saturday
but weakened as other weather systems affected it. Satellite
photographs Wednesday showed Isaac had developed a new eye wall,
signaling a new intensification stage, Franklin said.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac was about 1,125 miles southeast of Bermuda on Wednesday
evening and moving northwest at about 16 mph. Forecasters expect it
to turn northward in a few days, and Franklin said it should pass
well east of Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
