<HEADLINE> Parents of abducted boy sue city, three agencies for $75 million  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The parents of a 4-year-old boy taken last year
from a West Side playground by a registered sex offender have filed
a $75 million lawsuit against the city for giving the suspect a
''workfare'' assignment there.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers filed Tuesday, Steven Johnson and Michelle
Montes accuse the city and three of its agencies of ''gross
negligence'' for assigning Tony Sanchez to the Chelsea Park
playground, which is frequented by children.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth E. Ramseur, lawyer for Johnson and Montes, said the
workfare assignment ''was the same as putting the king cobra of
perverts in the hen house. The city couldn't have been more
negligent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez told police after his arrest for abducting the boy that
he is a registered sex offender, court papers say. He also said he
was a volunteer worker at the park where he formerly had been
assigned a maintenance job as part of the requirements for
receiving welfare benefits, court papers say. The playground is on
10th Avenue between 27th and 28th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   Papers filed in Manhattan's State Supreme Court say Sanchez took
the boy from the park around 3:30 p.m. on Oct. 23, 1999, and
brought him to the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, 40, left the boy, apparently unmolested, with a token
clerk at a subway station the next day, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Sanchez on Oct. 24 after witnesses said they had
seen him with the boy on a Bronx-bound train the previous
afternoon. He was charged with second-degree kidnapping and
endangering a child's welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lawson, a Parks Department spokesman, said Sanchez was a
workfare employee at several sites, including Chelsea Park, January
1995 to October 1997. Lawson said he does not know why Sanchez'
workfare stint ended.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not registered with our volunteers,'' Lawson said. ''If
he was working there, it was not under the direction of out
volunteer program. We have a comprehensive data base of volunteers,
and he's not in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Goodman of the city's Law Department said she was unaware
of the lawsuit, but added, ''If he was not working for the city at
the time of the alleged abduction, then I don't believe the city
has any liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Glenn Abolafia said Sanchez was found fit for
trial following a psychiatric exam ordered by a judge after his
arrest. Sanchez is due to appear before Justice Bonnie Wittner on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez completed a five-year probation period late last year
after pleading guilty to sex abuse in a 1994 Bronx incident
involving a 7-year-old boy and a 5-year-old girl, court records
show.
</P>
<P>
   Court records also show that in April 1999, Sanchez was charged
with endangering the welfare of a child after he allegedly offered
a 12-year-old girl $10 to give him a massage. He is due in court
Oct. 19 on that case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
