<HEADLINE> Physician pleads guilty to hindering prosecution of colleague  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan physician pleaded guilty Wednesday
to hindering the prosecution of a colleague and countryman who was
indicted on charges of drugging and sodomizing two female Swedish
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Turker Sengul, 28, a St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital
anesthesiology resident, admitted that he obstructed the
investigation to help Dr. Selim Can Alkoc, 29, flee the country.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Carol Berkman, scolding Sengul for
his reluctance to admit his crimes, promised him a sentence of one
to three years. She scheduled sentencing for Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Alkoc, a psychiatry resident at St. Luke's-Roosevelt, met the
two 21-year-old women in Canada and invited them to his West 59th
Street apartment, prosecutors say. While the women were there on
May 23, Alkoc allegedly drugged, raped and sodomized them.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, a Manhattan grand jury indicted Alkoc on charges of
rape, sodomy, sexual abuse and assault. Prosecutors say the
defendant fled to his native Turkey before he could be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Sengul was accused of going to Alkoc's apartment after he was
indicted and removing several videotapes of the sexual encounters,
which were hidden under a bed and in a vacuum cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   A law enforcement source who spoke on condition of anonymity
said after the indictments were announced that the tapes show Alkoc
having sex with many different women who appeared to be drugged.
</P>
<P>
   Sengul, who lived in the same hospital-subsidized building as
Alkoc, collected his colleague's mail, got clothing from his
apartment and even carried his pager to mislead police, prosecutors
have said.
</P>
<P>
   Alkoc's lawyer, Brian Perskin, said his client did not flee. He
said Alkoc hadn't been charged two weeks after the Swedish women
complained to police, so he moved back to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Perskin said he believes extraditing Alkoc may be impossible
because he is a Turkish national.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mandler, spokesman for St. Luke's-Roosevelt, said after the
indictments were announced that Alkoc and Sengul were suspended
without pay pending resolution of the charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
