<HEADLINE> Civil rights trial attracts the attention of federal prosecutors  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A police officer who says she was harassed
because she was a lesbian testified Wednesday at a trial being
watched by federal prosecutors for violations of the New York
Police Department's pledge to properly investigate sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Elizabeth Bryant told a jury in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan that she was continually harassed by supervisors and
peers after she bonded with her ''life partner'' in a Central Park
ceremony three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She testified that other police officers in her South Bronx
precinct mocked her repeatedly after learning of the June 24, 1997
ceremony, and supervisors failed to investigate and stop the
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Among items shown to the jury was a photograph Bryant said she
found posted in the station house after officers learned she was a
lesbian. The picture featured the body of a male body builder with
Bryant's head superimposed above it and male genitalia drawn below.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was feeling humiliated,'' she said of seeing the picture.
''I wanted to rip it down. I felt embarrassed, very alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with examples of derogatory remarks allegedly made by
fellow officers, Bryant was trying to show through her $5 million
lawsuit that the police department has violated its pledge to
eradicate harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The department in 1998 signed an agreement with the federal
government promising to greatly expand its Office of Equal
Employment Opportunity, revise its policy on the display of
sexually explicit materials, and improve investigations into sexual
harassment complaints.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White said at the time that the deal would
help ensure that police officers were free ''to do their jobs
without fear of sexual harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Smilon, White's spokesman, on Wednesday would only say
that White's office was watching the trial.
</P>
<P>
   During her day of testimony before Judge Lewis A. Kaplan, Bryant
described numerous incidents in which she said her co-workers and
bosses made her feel unwanted.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was told that if she ever put out a radio call
requesting emergency assistance, which summons scores of officers,
''nobody's going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, she said, officers made derogatory references to her
sexual orientation. An officer once told her to ''mind your own
lesbian business,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   On cross examination, city attorney Patricia Miller portrayed
Bryant as a habitual liar and questioned whether much of what she
had described had ever occurred.
</P>
<P>
   She forced the officer to tell how she had once married a man
from England so that both of them could more easily participate in
theater in each other's countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's what it was,'' Bryant said. ''It's what we both wanted -
to work on opposite stages. I wasn't married in my mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-27-00 1938 </TRAILER>
