<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State could profit from high energy costs  </HEADLINE>
By RIK STEVENS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - While consumers keep a wary eye on heating
expenses this winter, the state stands to collect a windfall of $30
million due to high energy costs, according to critics of a
much-maligned state tax.
</P>
<P>
   A repeal of the gross receipts tax on energy and the 4 percent
state sales tax on electricity and gas distribution would help ease
the minds of homeowners and small businesses who head into winter
uncertain of how much they'll pay to stay warm, Assembly
Republicans said.
</P>
<P>
   Faso said the average homeowner could save $100 this heating
season, about two-thirds of the anticipated cost increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''By cutting these energy taxes now, we'll be protecting both
jobs and homeowners and preventing a state tax windfall,'' Assembly
Minority Leader John J. Faso said.
</P>
<P>
   The state anticipated $650 million in revenues from the taxes
this fiscal year. A $30 million windfall represents a 4.7 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Energy Information Administration estimates someone
using 680 gallons of heating oil - assuming moderate temperatures -
will spend $900 this season, about $140 more than last.
</P>
<P>
   ''These skyrocketing costs will hurt upstate consumers and
businesses and New York state has a responsibility to help keep the
costs as low as we can, not profit from the increase,'' said
Republican Assemblyman James Tedisco of Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
   The gross receipts tax is among the state's most debated levies,
opposed by those who say it scares away businesses and hurts
consumers. Under the law that created it, utilities are not allowed
to show on bills how much the tax costs rate payers.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2000-01 budget, the state eliminated the gross receipts
tax on energy for manufacturers and cut the tax on energy for
non-manufacturing commercial customers by 25 percent each year
until its elimination on Jan. 1, 2005. It also reduced the tax for
residential electric rate payers by $75 million immediately and $50
million to be phased in over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Democrats called the repeal of the tax a small step in
the right direction and they joined with a public advocacy group in
the call for comprehensive energy reform in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact remains that the $3 (per $100 billed) we're talking
about is a drop in the bucket compared with what the consumer is
going to begin to face,'' Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said
Wednesday in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Silver has called for an energy summit to focus on long-term
solutions to high prices and stopgap measures like putting extra
money into state programs that help low-income families pay heating
bills and improving the energy-efficiency of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Paul Tonko, chairman of the Assembly Energy
Committee, said Gov. George E. Pataki was responsible for imposing
a tax on the delivery of natural gas, something Assembly Democrats
fought. Tonko said that in budget negotiations there was only so
much room for tax cuts and energy didn't make the final threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's office did not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   There is no gross receipts tax or state sales tax on home
heating oil and no sales tax on natural gas for residential
consumers, Tonko said, adding that the Republican plan would be a
short-term, punchless solution.
</P>
<P>
   Tonko said failing to address the spectrum of energy needs and
problems could leave the state vulnerable to a ''full-blow energy
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe we need a comprehensive strategy that puts together
a blueprint that will allow for drastic reductions in the bills
that energy consumers pay,'' the Amsterdam Democrat said. ''Not
just a standalone tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   The repeal ''should only be done as part of a comprehensive plan
that must include energy-efficiency and conservation efforts,''
agreed Jason K. Babbie, environmental policy analyst for the New
York Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   A repeal of the tax is supported by utilities and the New York
State Business Council, Albany chief corporate lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   ''This would be a timely occasion,'' said Nicholas Lyman,
spokesman for Niagara Mohawk Power Corp. ''Everybody knows home
heating costs are going to be up significantly this year and as the
price of the product goes up, the tax levy goes up.''
</P>
<P>
   The utility is warning its customers who heat with natural gas
to expect bills about 20 percent higher this winter than last
winter due to energy price spikes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
