<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman Promises To Help Seniors  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Joseph Lieberman met Wednesday with senior
citizens so strapped by the cost of prescription drugs that they
boarded buses for Canada to buy their medication. He called the
situation ''an embarrassment'' and said Al Gore's Medicare plan
would help.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Gore endorsed his Democratic vice presidential
running mate's controversial decision to stick with his
simultaneous Connecticut campaign for re-election to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I agree with his view on that,'' Gore told reporters as he
traveled to Washington from Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has argued that to quit now would leave a handful of
party leaders to choose an alternative Democratic candidate because
there's no time for a primary before Nov. 7. Gore agreed: ''I think
if you have just 20, 30 people making the decision then it's not
democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lieberman is elected vice president, Connecticut's Republican
governor, John G. Rowland, gets to appoint a placeholder until a
special election can be held.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people ought to have a chance to fill it and the best
thing would be to set a special election early, but that will be
for the people of that state to determine,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   At Lieberman's Milwaukee campaign stop, George McKinney, 70,
said he takes high blood pressure and prostate medicine and his
wife needs heart medicine. Together, they pay $500 per month in the
United States for their drugs but saved 63 percent in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel a little ashamed sometimes,'' McKinney said. ''We're
the richest country in the world. Why do we have to go all the way
to Canada?''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman assured McKinney and five other seniors participating
in a forum at the Wilson Park Senior Center that, if he and Gore
are elected, help is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is one of the great areas of unmet human need in
this country,'' Lieberman said. ''It's an embarrassment, isn't it?
It's an embarrassment, and it makes me angry.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' competing Medicare plans have become a focus of
the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman propose adding a $253 billion prescription
drug plan to Medicare to give free complete coverage to the elderly
poor and a cost-sharing benefit to others. It would cover half the
cost of drugs up to a $5,000 annual limit and offers a catastrophic
benefit that caps a person's annual costs at $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   The $198 billion Medicare plan of Republican presidential
candidate George W. Bush and running mate Dick Cheney would let the
states administer a program covering the full prescription drug
costs of the elderly poor and subsidizing a choice of drug plans
for other Medicare beneficiaries. The Bush plan also has a
catastrophic benefit that caps drug costs at $6,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   After the forum, Lieberman was attending a fund-raiser expected
to raise $250,000 for Wisconsin Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 2022 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $Adv01  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Alex Ramos is a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in the blighted South Bronx, he escaped via the boxing
ring. A four-time Golden Gloves winner, the middleweight contender
swapped jabs with Michael Nunn and jibes with Howard Cosell. When
he wound up in jail after becoming an alcoholic and drug addict,
Alex Ramos fought on.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will die a boxer,'' he once vowed.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, his biggest fight seemed won. A newly sober
Ramos had discovered his life's purpose by starting a foundation to
aid ex-fighters. Despair gave way to delight - until Ramos took a
sucker punch from his past.
</P>
<P>
   The fighter was blindsided by Alberto Lugo.
</P>
<P>
   Lugo, a childhood neighbor of Ramos, receded into the South
Bronx scenery as the fighter exploded out of it. When Ramos won a
big fight, Lugo was inevitably among the triumphant crowd that
filled Willis Avenue to greet its conquering hero.
</P>
<P>
   He was a hanger-on, a wannabe who longed for a taste of the
boxer's high life: the attention, the money, the women.
</P>
<P>
   When he couldn't make it happen, he simply made it up.
</P>
<P>
   Across nearly two decades, in bars and casinos and parties, Lugo
impersonated Alex Ramos. Like a fighter donning his trunks and
robe, he slipped easily into the skin of his old acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   ''My name is Alex Ramos,'' Lugo said, over and over, parlaying
his performance into fight tickets, hotel rooms and cash.
</P>
<P>
   When Lugo was arrested for a 1983 rape, he used Ramos' name. He
did his prison time under Ramos' name. When he was released four
years ago, he became Alex Ramos again.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1999, when Lugo was arrested for drugging and
sexually assaulting women, he informed the cops they had found
their man: Yes, he was Alex Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   ''I boxed for a while,'' he boasted to a Manhattan prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The real Alex Ramos, reborn and living in California, was
unaware of his East Coast doppleganger's return. When he finally
heard, the retired middleweight knew there was one more battle to
wage - the fight to reclaim his name.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Ramos was born in January 1961, two months after the Lugos
welcomed their son, Alberto. When the Ramos family moved from
Manhattan to the South Bronx, the two families became neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Their sons crossed paths on the playground behind P.S. 40, where
Alex's mother taught and the local kids hung out.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was not one of my boys,'' Ramos says now of Lugo. ''I've
said hello to him, even shaken his hand. But he was never a
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Ramos was the son of a fighter. At age 11, the 90-pound kid
followed his old man into the ring, punching his way to four local
Golden Gloves titles and a spot on the national amateur boxing
team.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every time Howard Cosell did my fights,'' he recalls proudly,
''I won by first-round knockout.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos' shot at the 1980 U.S. Olympic team was lost in America's
boycott of the Moscow Games. Undaunted, the 19-year-old Ramos
turned pro in late 1980, knocking out his first two opponents
within 16 days.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had the potential to go far,'' remembers Hall of Fame
fighter Jose Torres, the ex-light-heavyweight champ. ''He was a
good puncher - oh, yeah. He had the physical ability.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood followed Ramos intently. A sign on a local
candy shop proudly proclaimed, ''Ramos - The East 136th Street
Champ.'' His loose-knit South Bronx fan club included Lugo, dubbed
''Spooky'' for the vacant look that sometimes crossed his face.
</P>
<P>
   By November 1981, Ramos' record stood at 12-0 with 7 knockouts.
An August 1982 eighth-round KO loss put a crimp in his title shot
plans, but an undeterred Ramos moved to Scottsdale, Ariz., and
began working with Sugar Ray Leonard's trainer, Janks Morton.
</P>
<P>
   Back home in New York, Alberto Lugo was discovering that just
five words - ''My name is Alex Ramos'' - could catapult him from
obscurity to instant celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're going to impersonate someone, you're going to pick
something with glamour,'' says Richard Lapchick, head of the Center
for the Study of Sports in America. ''Athletes, with the amount of
money they command and the star power - perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, a variety of athletes were victimized by
impersonators: football stars Lawrence Taylor and Charles Mann,
basketball's Dee Brown, former boxing champion Freddy ''Red''
Cochran.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a huge segment of American men who would have loved to
be professional athletes,'' Lapchick says of the impersonators.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Lugo was among them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, as Ramos did roadwork in Arizona, Lugo was on the prowl
in Manhattan. He was charming, articulate, charismatic. He was, as
he told everyone, Alex Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   One evening, the phone in Scottsdale rang. A Manhattan rape
victim had told detectives that she was attacked by the boxer, Alex
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos had an alibi, and police had a suspect. The fighter flew
back to his hometown, where police showed him an array of pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew only one guy,'' Ramos recalls. ''I knew Spooky.''
</P>
<P>
   Lugo, convicted in 1985, began a 3-to-9-year prison stretch on
Jan. 8, 1986. Throughout the process, Lugo insisted that he was
Alex Ramos; nobody ever corrected him. State correction officials
still list him under a combination of his birth and bogus names:
''Ramos, Alberto.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Ramos, struggling with his career and his own demons, put
the bizarre impersonation behind him when Lugo was jailed. Ramos
relocated to California, where his life in and out of the ring soon
crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he earned the United States Boxing Association
middleweight crown - and lost it the next year, taking a vicious
beating in a second-round TKO defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Cocaine and booze became a devastating one-two that Ramos
couldn't slip as the fighter blew through an estimated $500,000 in
earnings. He spent too much time chasing women, too little time in
the gym.
</P>
<P>
   A 1986 title shot ended with a loss to future two-time champion
Michael Nunn, and the big money fights disappeared. Two years
later, Ramos received word that his mother was dying back in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos needed money for a flight home. There was none, his
managers said. Alex Ramos was broke.
</P>
<P>
   Stranded in California, Ramos waited helplessly as his mother
died. A drunken and enraged Ramos accused his managers - rightly,
he still says - of stealing a $54,000 purse. And then brutally beat
them.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos was convicted of assault with a deadly weapon - his fists
- and spent 22 months in Corcoran State Prison. After his release
in 1990, he returned to the ring. He also returned to cocaine, and
then returned to prison on a 1993 parole violation.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, released and reinvigorated, Ramos won nine
straight fights before heading to Argentina for a $25,000 payday
and a WBA title shot against Jorge Castro. He was knocked out in
the second round in what became his last professional fight.
</P>
<P>
   His lifetime record was 39-10-2, with 24 KOs.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring, Ramos awoke one morning ''in a sweat and in
tears'' after a nightmare that he had died penniless, like the
great heavyweight Joe Louis. He longed to escape the drugs, the
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1995, and Ramos spent the next six months in a free Santa
Monica rehabilitation clinic. Now clean, the ex-pug decided to give
something back to the fight game: he helped create the Retired
Boxers Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit organization lends a hand to needy ex-fighters -
those battling drug and alcohol woes, those left penniless or
homeless, those who just took too many shots to the head.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos reclaimed his prominent position in the boxing community.
Flashing a wide smile and raising a boxer's fist, he posed for
pictures with referee Mills Lane, ex-heavyweight contender Gerry
Cooney, Olympic boxing champion Mark Breland.
</P>
<P>
   He began raising funds for his new project.
</P>
<P>
   As Ramos rebuilt his life, Lugo resurrected his own version of
the Ramos saga. He endured a failed marriage, according to one of
his lawyers, and did his time on the rape conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Lugo was released on Christmas Eve 1989, but couldn't avoid
trouble: city and state records show he was jailed repeatedly for
violating parole and probation, including once for selling drugs.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 13, 1996, Lugo was released after three months behind
bars on his latest violation.
</P>
<P>
   Lugo moved into an apartment complex near the Hudson River in
Manhattan. He was single, childless, and ready to party. Lugo took
to the town as Alex Ramos yet again.
</P>
<P>
   ''He held himself out to be Alex Ramos on a daily basis,''
acknowledged Lugo's latest attorney, Kyle Watters.
</P>
<P>
   One night, Lugo arrived for dinner at a friend's home. There he
introduced himself to one and all as boxer Alex Ramos, a happy
spiel that only served to infuriate one guest.
</P>
<P>
   Her name was Miriam Martinez, and she was Ramos' sister. Lugo
left the party.
</P>
<P>
   Other nights, Lugo headed to the bars of the Lower East Side.
There, buying drinks and holding court for the ladies, he was again
Alex Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   He was still in training for a title shot, explained
Lugo-as-Ramos. He talked up his manager, Shelly Finkel, who also
handled Mike Tyson. (Lugo mistakenly thought that veteran boxing
impresario Finkel was a woman).
</P>
<P>
   Lugo found a number of women quite willing to say ''yes'' to a
successful athlete's sexual overtures, his lawyers said. For those
who said no, Lugo used another technique, authorities charged.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 15, 1998, Lugo lured a 19-year-old woman to a Manhattan
hotel room with a promise of a job as a ring-card girl. Once in the
room, Lugo gave her a soda and asked her to strip to her underwear
- a preview of how she would look in a bikini.
</P>
<P>
   The teen sipped her drink and collapsed in the room, where Lugo
tried to rape her, the girl said.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 11, 1999, a 26-year-old woman visiting from Atlanta met
Lugo at a bar. He bought her a beer, insisting she drink it. When
she woke up later, she was naked from the waist down and knew she
had been raped.
</P>
<P>
   There was a third incident, although Lugo later insisted all
three involved consensual sex.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities disagreed. Lugo, still identifying himself as Alex
Ramos, was arrested in February 1999 for rape, kidnapping and
sodomy. When Lugo was taken into custody, two police detectives
asked for an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Word spread around New York in the weeks before the March 13,
1999, Madison Square Garden title fight between Lennox Lewis and
Evander Holyfield: Alex Ramos was a rapist.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Lugo sitting in Rikers Island on $250,000 bail, even
if no one knew him by that name. In court papers, in an NYPD press
release, in conversations with his lawyer, he remained Alex Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Alex Ramos took a call from his panicked father
about the rape case. Ramos' reputation, and his fledgling
foundation, suffered a major hit.
</P>
<P>
   ''A large donor called from New York and said they would not
contribute to any foundation with a rapist,''' Ramos recalls.
''This was really damaging to me, to my family, to my foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time around, Alex Ramos had shrugged off Lugo's
identity swapping. His attitude had changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt it was the last fight of my life,'' Ramos says. ''I had
lived in the darkness. I'm trying to move forward, do the right
thing. And here it is, 20 years later, and I'm going back to
court.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, Ramos returned to his hometown and went toe-to-toe
with Lugo in a Manhattan courtroom. Sitting in the witness chair at
Lugo's rape trial, he stared down his one-time fan.
</P>
<P>
   ''He would not look at me,'' Ramos says. ''My eyes were burning
holes in his soul, in his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Jose Muniz, looking back and forth, noticed a
slight resemblance between the pair: ''A little bit, not
striking.'' Ramos' chin was more chiseled, his eyes brighter, his
hair a little grayer
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Martha Bashford, who had called
Ramos to testify, began her questions.
</P>
<P>
   No, Ramos said, he never committed the crimes charged against
Lugo.
</P>
<P>
   No, Ramos said, he had never given permission for Lugo to use
his name.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Muniz asked if he was Alex Ramos, the
middleweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
   It was over quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Lugo didn't testify, but Bashford played a videotaped interview
with Lugo insisting he was Alex Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   ''I boxed for a while,'' he boasted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Amateur? Professional?'' Bashford asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both,'' he replied. ''Amateur and professional.''
</P>
<P>
   During the week-long trial, not a single friend or family member
appeared in court to support Lugo. The only face familiar to the
defendant belonged to Alex Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   It took a Manhattan jury just five hours to convict Lugo and
return Alex Ramos his name. Lugo seemed surprised by the guilty
verdict, squinting at the jurors as each conviction was read.
</P>
<P>
   He then leaned over toward Muniz.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jose,'' he asked, ''how could they find me guilty?''
</P>
<P>
   Muniz offered a one-word answer: ''Credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing a 50-year prison term, Lugo decided to start fighting,
too. After the conviction, he hired a new lawyer and planned an
appeal that he will watch from behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   For Alex Ramos, the fight is finally over: his name is again
his, and Lugo is going to jail. If Lugo ever abuses his name again,
Ramos vows, there will be one last brawl.
</P>
<P>
   ''Put me in a room with this guy, and I'll tell you for a fact -
I'm the only one coming out of that room,'' Ramos says, his voice
hard. ''You'll know who the real Alex Ramos is.''
</P>
<P>
   On the web:
</P>
<P>
   Retired Boxers Foundation, http://www.globalaffairs.com/rbf/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
