<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Homolka Being Transferred To Maximum Security Prison
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Karla Homolka, notorious for her role in the
deaths of Ontario schoolgirls Leslie Mahaffy and Kristen French, is
being transferred to a maximum security prison for psychiatric
evaluation, says a Correctional Service of Canada official.
</P>
<P>
   She will be transferred from the medium-security Joliette
Institution, 70 kilometers northeast of Montreal, where she had
been serving a 12-year sentence for manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections officials were notified of the move Wednesday and
arrangements are being made, said Michele Pilon-Santilli,
spokeswoman for Correctional Service of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The move is unrelated to pictures published in newspapers last
week of Homolka enjoying a birthday party with other sexual
offenders at the prison, said Pilon-Santilli.
</P>
<P>
   An outraged public flooded the correctional service with calls
and Solicitor General Lawrence MacAulay was called to account in
the House of Commons after the photos were published.
</P>
<P>
   The warden of Joliette requested the evaluation after it was
recommended by a prominent outside psychologist following many
psychiatric and psychological assessments on Homolka,
Pilon-Santilli she said.
</P>
<P>
   Homolka will have served two-thirds of her sentence by July 6,
2001 and would normally be eligible for release.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Experts: Biker Summit May Lead To More Crime
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- A bold courthouse summit between rival biker
gangs might bring an end to their bloody turf war but could also
lead to more street-level crime, experts warned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hells Angels and Rock Machine leaders surprised and angered
Quebecers on Tuesday when they met, of all places, at the Quebec
City courthouse. Among those upset by the meeting's location was
Premier Lucien Bouchard, who called it ''totally unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll look into what happened and how the solicitor general
regards the matter,'' said Bouchard, who was questioned by
reporters in Milwaukee at the windup of a Quebec trade mission to
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Police and biker experts agreed the gangs were probably trying
to reach a truce and agree on a division of territories for their
crime rings.
</P>
<P>
   The gangs were likely responding to increased public pressure
for tougher anti-gang laws that followed the shooting this month of
a reporter who covered the biker war.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that these negotiations were held in the courthouse
is a snub at society,'' Yves Lavigne, who has written extensively
on organized crime, said in an interview from Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ''The message to society from the bikers was that they're not
afraid of society's institutions, be it the courts or the police .
. . this was grandstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
Aboriginals Fight For Return of Blood Samples
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) -- Scientists using human
materials to conduct groundbreaking genetic research need to brush
up on their manners, says a medical ethicist.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael McDonald said simple courtesy might have avoided a
current dispute between members of a Vancouver Island aboriginal
group and an English researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists regularly get so wrapped up in research they forget
to mention how donations can end up in unrelated experiments, said
McDonald, director for the Center for Applied Ethics at Vancouver's
University of British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuu-chah-nulth is fighting for the return of almost 900
blood samples provided to an Oxford University researcher by
aboriginals in the early 1980s who believed they were participating
in an arthritis study.
</P>
<P>
   The blood was never returned and the aboriginals discovered it
was being used in genetic experiments beyond the local arthritis
study.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not supposed to happen that way, but it is going on,''
McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuu-chah-nulth Tribal Council, representing 13 Vancouver
Island First Nations, is meeting this week in an effort to have the
blood samples returned.
</P>
<P>
   Geneticist Richard Ward, who originally took the samples from
the aboriginals, apparently used the blood for anthropology
research beyond arthritis. He could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
