<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, Sept. 27, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Offers End To 'Soft Money' Ads
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore offered today to pull the plug on all presidential
campaign radio and TV ads paid for by political parties with unregulated ''soft
money'' -- but only if George W. Bush does likewise. Bush had signaled his
reluctance to do so just a day earlier, saying he wanted to get rid of such ads
but that Gore couldn't be counted on to abide by such a deal. ''I don't trust
him, to be frank with you,'' the Texas governor said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Polls: Gore, Bush Race Close
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new Los Angeles Times poll gives Republican George W.
Bush a 48-42 percent lead over Democrat Al Gore in the presidential race, but
the candidates are about even in other national polls. Both Republicans and
Democrats said today they feel the race is very close, maybe the closest since
1960. After several weeks when the Bush campaign appeared to be moving in the
Democrat's direction, evidence pointed to a comeback fueled largely by his
renewed appeal to female ''swing voters'' and seniors.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Executes Inmate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- A condemned man who won an unprecedented reprieve
from Gov. George W. Bush for DNA tests that only confirmed his guilt was
executed today for killing his 12-year-old stepdaughter. Ricky McGinn, 43,
received a lethal injection for raping Stephanie Flanary and bludgeoning her
with an ax. He insisted evidence was planted or tampered with, but DNA tests
completed in August again linked McGinn to the 1993 crime. The McGinn case drew
attention because of the June 1 reprieve by Bush.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Milosevic Opponents Rally in Belgrade
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- More than 200,000 joyful opponents of Slobodan
Milosevic swarmed the capital's downtown district Wednesday, supporting an
opposition claim of an electoral triumph over the Yugoslav president. The
biggest demonstration ever against Milosevic completely blocked Belgrade's main
streets around Republic Square. Much of the downtown area teemed with people
waving flags and chanting: ''He's finished.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chavez Rallies OPEC Leaders
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez rallied OPEC
leaders Wednesday to demand equal footing with industrialized nations and a just
price for oil, calling the oil cartel's rebound on the back of rising crude
prices a ''resurrection.'' Chavez, a driving force behind the resurgence of a
cartel that was on the brink of collapse in 1998, urged oil producing nations to
use their newfound influence in this era of high crude prices to improve their
citizens' standards of living and that of developing nations in general.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lieberman Promises To Help Seniors
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Joseph Lieberman met today with senior citizens so strapped
by the cost of prescription drugs that they boarded buses for Canada to buy
their medication. He called the situation ''an embarrassment'' and said Al
Gore's Medicare plan would help. The candidates' competing Medicare plans have
become a focus of the presidential race. Separately, Gore endorsed his
Democratic vice presidential running mate's ontroversial decision to stick with
his simultaneous Connecticut campaign for re-election to the Senate. ''I agree
with his view on that,'' Gore told reporters as he traveled to Washington from
Iowa.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 3; Nasdaq Falls 33
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices failed to rebound today as investors concerned
about third-quarter results again punished the shares of poor performers. The
Dow closed down 2.96 at 10,628.36. On the NYSE, gainers led losers by an
11-to-10 margin. The Nasdaq dropped 32.80 to 3,656.30.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NBC's Olympics Ratings Hit New Low
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC's 12th night of Olympic coverage from Sydney had the
worst rating for Summer Games competition in at least 16 years. The network's
taped telecast, including the gymnastics champions' gala, diving, and a U.S.
gold-medal victory in beach volleyball, drew a 12.4 rating and 21 share last
night. That's 23 percent below what advertisers were told the Sydney Olympics
would average and even further off the 17.5 to 18.5 rating NBC Sports chairman
Dick Ebersol predicted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arrests in Rocker-Bottle Incident
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A man imprisoned in the death of his newborn son pleaded
innocent today to a charge of interfering with police after a friend allegedly
threw a bottle at Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker. Police said the bottle was
thrown from the first-base box seats. It landed about 10 feet from Rocker as he
warmed up on the mound at Shea Stadium, where the Braves played the Mets on last
night. When police tried to arrest Raymond Maniaci, of Wyckoff, N.J., his
hometown friend Brian Peterson got between them and his friend and refused to
step away, police told newspapers.
AP NewsBrief By GRETCHEN SCHWARTZ 
</P>
