<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inmate accused of stabbing two prison workers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STORMVILLE, N.Y. (AP) - A convicted murderer on Wednesday
allegedly used homemade knives to stab both a high-level official
and officer at the Green Haven Correctional Facility maximum
security prison.
</P>
<P>
   Inmate Tyrone Walker, a 31-year-old committed out of Brooklyn,
is accused of the 2 p.m. attack in the prison's exercise yard.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Superintendent for Security George S. Schneider, 52,
sustained puncture wounds to the back, shoulder, and above the
right eye; Corrections Officer Gary L. Mitchetti, 28, wounds to the
back of the head and base of the skull.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials said Schneider was making his daily round of
the yard when Walker called to him and then attacked him wielding
knives in both hands. When Corrections Officer Glen Williams struck
Walker with his baton, Walker allegedly circled behind Schneider
and began attacking Schneider from behind. As Williams again used
his baton to protect Schneider, Walker allegedly stabbed Mitchetti.
</P>
<P>
   Walker is serving a sentence of 32&AMP;frac12; years to life for crimes
that include fatally shooting a woman as she loaded her car in
Manhattan in 1993 and the 1993 murder of a man in Ulster County.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations by the state Department of Correctional Services,
the New York Division of State Police and the Dutchess County
District's Attorney's Office are underway.
</P>
<P>
   Stormville is 95 miles south of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
