<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Questions GOP on Medicare  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTOONA, Iowa (AP) -- Winifred Skinner won kisses -- three on the
forehead, two on the cheek -- from Al Gore Wednesday for her tale of
making ends meet with the recycling-center nickels she gets for
soda cans picked from the roadside.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, 79, didn't want Gore or the IRS to know how many
nickels, though. ''I withdraw that question,'' the vice president
chuckled. ''Because I'm all for you.''
</P>
<P>
   That sweet exchange at Gore's campaign stop at a community
center here juxtaposed the Democratic presidential candidate's
sharp indictment of Republican rival George W. Bush for allegedly
having it in for Medicare, the government health program upon which
39 million seniors and disabled Americans rely.
</P>
<P>
   At a community center here, Gore described seeing on television
in his Des Moines hotel that morning a Bush ad accusing Gore of
wanting, through his proposal to add a prescription drug benefit to
Medicare, to turn the program into a ''government-run HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the way they describe Medicare. There's no big
government HMO,'' Gore huffed. ''You get to choose your doctor. You
get to choose your pharmacy.''
</P>
<P>
   His Republican opponents, Gore continued, ''never really have
liked Medicare and putting it down that way is in keeping with the
opposition on the other side to the creation of Medicare in the
first place -- and their support of Newt Gingrich's plan to let it
wither on the vine in 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This proposal that (Bush) put out this year would have
essentially the same effect,'' Gore finished.
</P>
<P>
   That loaded charge, aimed at riling senior citizens who vote in
reliably large numbers, came as Gore looked for ways to break out
ahead in a very tight race against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett, in turn, said Gore's Medicare plan
''creates more than 400 government regulations and gives federal
bureaucrats greater control over medical decisions for seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett added that Gore is ''lashing out by trying to fight
five-year old budget battles with Newt Gingrich. Governor Bush has
said that Medicare is one of the most successful programs for our
seniors and his reforms will make sure that it is successful for
the next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   At a lunchtime rally with more than 1,000 supporters in a
downtown Des Moines square, Gore counted the time remaining, ''40
days 8 hours and 20 minutes,'' before polls close on Nov. 7 in this
state, which awards just seven of the 270 electoral votes needed to
win.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party pitched in with a new TV ad -- airing in
Delaware, Michigan, Missouri, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Oregon,
Washington state and Wisconsin -- noting that Bush came from the oil
business and says he supported laws to let the industry regulate
itself. It also says Texas is No. 3 in water pollution and No. 1 in
air pollution while Gore has fought for the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ''America's environment is cleaner now,'' an announcer says.
''Do we really want it to look like Texas?''
</P>
<P>
   In Altoona, where local unions and senior centers had gathered
an invitation-only crowd of 200, Gore tossed his sportcoat over the
lectern and roamed the room fielding supportive questions about his
proposal to add a drug benefit to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, recruited by the United Auto Workers to attend, told
Gore that, because she pays around $250 each month for
prescriptions, she walks Des Moines' city streets ''an hour and a
half to two and a half hours -- sometimes three hours -- seven days a
week and I pick up cans and that's what puts the food on my
table.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, she added, a ''smart aleck'' driving past ''looked at
me and he yelled back and says, 'Get a life!' And I thought, if I
wasn't picking up these cans I wouldn't have a life. ... I don't
get food stamps or nothing like that. I want to earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, putting his arms around her and gently kissing her
forehead, said: ''Well, you're going back to work. ... How much do
you earn a week, seven days of picking up cans?''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner worried: ''You're not going to tell the government are
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gore: ''You know, I don't want to know the answer to that.
I withdraw that question. Because I'm all for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Washington, D.C., Gore contrasted his supported for
abortion rights with Bush's opposition in remarks before about 500
people at a Women Leadership Forum reception. He also previewed the
economic speech he plans for Thursday, boasting of budget surpluses
and record low unemployment. ''I'm not satisfied,'' Gore said.
''You ain't seen nothing yet.
</P>
<P>
   He and running mate Joseph Lieberman also were attending a
dinner benefiting the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
