<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officer pleads innocent to extortion, drug distribution charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Schenectady police officer Michael Siler
pleaded innocent Wednesday to the latest charges in a six-count
federal court indictment alleging he used drugs seized from a
dealer to bribe an informant.
</P>
<P>
   Siler, 32, insisted he would be exonerated once the case went to
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''I fully expect to be cleared because I've done nothing
wrong,'' Siler said.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-year-old Richard D. Barnett, Siler's former partner, has
already pleaded guilty to extortion and drug charges, admitting in
court that he and Siler traded 3.5 grams of crack cocaine for
details about criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett has since been fired from the force. The U.S. Attorney's
office has ordered a plea agreement with him sealed. He will be
sentenced Jan. 12, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, together with high-ranking members of the police
department, have been conducting a joint investigation into the
department since August 1999. The probe was sparked by complaints
that black residents were being mistreated and abused by some
officers. As part of the probe, Siler is accused of having heroin,
crack cocaine and marijuana in his locker.
</P>
<P>
   Siler faces a maximum of 30 years in prison for allegations that
include extortion, narcotics trafficking, and carrying a firearm
during the incidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
