<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Leaders Mull Easing Cuba Embargo  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican congressional leaders agreed
Wednesday to a compromise aimed at easing four-decade-old
restrictions on U.S. food and medicine sales to Cuba, a GOP
lawmaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Roy Blunt, R-Mo., said the deal would ban Cubans from using
credit from American banks or the U.S. government for such sales,
but let American financial institutions help arrange third-country
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from farm-state lawmakers, House GOP leaders
agreed last summer to support lifting the ban but barring U.S.
financing. Many lawmakers from farm states, particularly in the
Senate, had complained that simply barring U.S. financing would
make it nearly impossible for trade to occur.
</P>
<P>
   Blunt told reporters that the accord would provide ''a
significant opening'' for trade with the Caribbean island nation. A
ban against trading most products to Cuba has been in effect since
1963, after Fidel Castro became the country's leader and Cuba
became a Soviet satellite.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said he favors drug and food sales to
Cuba. White House spokesman P.J. Crowley said administration
officials had not seen the agreement yet and would not comment on
it.
</P>
<P>
   Blunt said he expected the White House to support the provision,
which is part of an agriculture spending bill for the coming fiscal
year that is expected to exceed $75 billion. The measure could be
considered by the House next week.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear how congressional Democrats would
react to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jo Ann Emerson, R-Mo., who with Rep. George Nethercutt,
R-Wash., helped lead the effort to liberalize Cuban trade, said the
compromise would write into law regulations that currently restrict
U.S. tourist travel to Cuba. Many Democrats have said they oppose
such an action.
</P>
<P>
   The move to ease the sanctions against Cuba had been strongly
opposed by anti-Castro members of Congress and GOP leaders,
including House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, and Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   But their position was weakened in July when the House voted
overwhelmingly to stop enforcing the restrictions against food and
drug sales to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also approved legislation in July that would lift
sanctions against food and medicine sales to Cuba. It also would
prevent presidents from blocking shipments of food and medicine to
any country without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has entered the realm of presidential politics. GOP
nominee George W. Bush has said he opposes lifting sanctions, while
Democratic candidate Vice President Al Gore has said he favors more
contacts with Cubans ''without helping the Castro government.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of medicine to Cuba have been allowed since 1992, with
some restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, eight prominent Republicans called for an end
to restrictions on food and medicine sales to Cuba and on travel by
Americans to the island.
</P>
<P>
   They also recommended that a time limit, or ''sunset''
arrangement, be placed on a 1996 Cuban sanctions law so the next
president and the new Congress could have ''an unfettered
opportunity to determine how best to approach the Cuba issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy shift was recommended by John Block, a former
secretary of agriculture; Frank Carlucci, a former defense
secretary and national security adviser; William Clark, also a
former national security adviser; Carla Hills, former U.S. special
trade representative; Illinois Gov. George Ryan; John Whitehead, a
former deputy secretary of state; Clayton Yeutter, a former U.S.
special trade representative, agriculture secretary and chairman of
the Republican National Committee; and Jim Courter, a former New
Jersey congressman who served on the House Armed Services Committee
for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   The eight said in a statement that in the post-Cold War era, the
policy of isolating Cuba no longer makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today, with the Soviet bloc gone and Cuban military
capabilities vastly reduced, it is possible to use a different mix
of policy measures to serve important American interests such as
promoting human rights, assisting the Cuban people, and building
contacts with the generation that will govern Cuba in the new
century,'' the eight said.
</P>
<P>
   Their statement was released by the Lexington Institute, a
nonpartisan public policy research organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 2155 </TRAILER>
