<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, Sept. 27, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Offers To Pull 'Soft Money' Ads
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore offered today to pull the plug on all presidential
campaign radio and TV ads paid for by political parties with unregulated ''soft
money'' -- but only if George W. Bush does likewise. Bush had signaled his
reluctance to do so just a day earlier, saying he wanted to get rid of such ads
but that Gore couldn't be counted on to abide by such a deal. ''I don't trust
him, to be frank with you,'' the Texas governor said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Drug Industry Gave $800,000 to GOP
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The pharmaceutical industry gave more than $800,000 to
Republican Party committees last month after the Senate voted to allow reimports
of lower-priced U.S.-made drugs -- something the companies oppose. In addition,
the president of Bristol-Myers Squibb co-chaired a fund-raising dinner today for
Senate Republicans. But despite the intensive lobbying effort, Congress is
likely to pass the legislation. The pharmaceutical industry also is fighting a
Democratic proposal to expand Medicare, the health care program for the elderly,
to cover the cost of prescription drugs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Milosevic Opponents Rally in Streets
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- More than 200,000 joyful opponents of Slobodan
Milosevic swarmed the capital's downtown district Wednesday, supporting an
opposition claim of an electoral triumph over the Yugoslav president. The
biggest demonstration ever against Milosevic completely blocked Belgrade's main
streets around Republic Square. Much of the downtown area teemed with people
waving flags and chanting: ''He's finished.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Inmate Executed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- A condemned man who won an unprecedented reprieve
from Gov. George W. Bush for DNA tests that only confirmed his guilt was
executed today for killing his 12-year-old stepdaughter. Ricky McGinn, 43,
received a lethal injection for raping Stephanie Flanary and bludgeoning her
with an ax. He insisted evidence was planted or tampered with, but DNA tests
completed in August again linked McGinn to the 1993 crime. The McGinn case drew
attention because of the June 1 reprieve by Bush.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Crew of Fatal Ferry Crash Arrested
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PAROS, Greece (AP) -- Greek authorities on Wednesday arrested the captain and
four crew members of a ferry that struck a rocky outcrop marked by a light
beacon that could be seen for seven miles. At least 66 people were killed.
Searches continued throughout the night for possible survivors. Some survivors
said crew members were watching a soccer match on television Tuesday night when
the ship, holding more than 500 people, went aground in a gale in the Aegean Sea
just two miles from shore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dell To Cut Computer Prices
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Dell Computer announced plans to slash prices on some
computer servers and PCs, passing on savings to consumers as parts become less
expensive. But investors hardly celebrated Dell's announcement today -- a day
many tech stocks were down -- as shares of Dell fell to a 52-week low midday on
the Nasdaq Stock Market. The stock recovered somewhat to end regular trading at
$32.44, down $1.19, or 3.6 percent. Round Rock, Texas-based Dell said it was
reducing prices on its PowerEdge servers 14 to 47 percent. The servers, or
computers used to host Web sites, now will sell for as low as $1,199 to $13,000
or more.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose early Thursday, rebounding modestly from the
previous day's sharp decline. The dollar was lower against the yen. The Nikkei
gained 126.61 points, or 0.81 percent, to 15,766.56 points in the first 30
minutes of trading. On Wednesday, the average closed down 288.67 points, or 1.81
percent. The Nasdaq fell 32.80 points to close up at 3,656.30 on Wednesday. The
Dow Jones industrial average fell 2.96 points to close at 10,628.36.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mets Clinch NL Wild Card
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For the first time ever, the New York Mets are going to the
playoffs in consecutive years after beating the Braves 6-2 tonight to clinch the
NL wild card berth. Rick Reed limited Atlanta to four hits in eight innings and
pinch-hitter Darryl Hamilton singled in the go-ahead run in the fifth. After
slumping for the third straight September, the Mets survived and will open the
playoffs Oct. 4 at San Francisco or St. Louis.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gymnast Must Await Medal Decision
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The Court of Arbitration for Sport needed more time
after Wednesday's hearing to decide whether 16-year-old Romanian gymnast Andreea
Raducan can reclaim the Olympic gold medal she lost for taking cold medicine
that contained a banned substance. Court reconvened Thursday (Wednesday night
EDT). ''It's too much to give back a medal for only one pill taken for cold and
influenza,'' Romanian coach Octavian Belu said.
AP NewsBrief By GRETCHEN SCHWARTZ 
</P>
