<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gambino Family, Associates Indicted  </HEADLINE>
By TERRY SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Nine alleged members and associates
of a New York crime family have been indicted on federal charges,
including involvement in a stripper's murder and plotting the death
of her accused killer.
</P>
<P>
   All nine men, including the alleged head of the Gambino family's
Florida operations, are charged with racketeering, U.S. Attorney
Guy A. Lewis announced Wednesday. Some are also charged with
loansharking, counterfeiting checks and being accessories to
murder.
</P>
<P>
   ''This indictment should send a message to organized criminals
who are targeting South Florida that they will be prosecuted and
punished,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony ''Tony Pep'' Trentacosta, 61, who prosecutors say has
run the family's Florida operations since March 1999, is charged
only with racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, a Sunny Isle restaurant owned by
Frederick J. Massaro, 60, was used as a front to procure
information for counterfeiting checks, sell stolen merchandise,
conduct loansharking and plot the March 1999 slaying of 22-year-old
Jeanette Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The man accused of killing Smith, Ariel A. Hernandez, 35, is
jailed facing first-degree murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Massaro knew about the plan to kill Smith and
solicited Carlos Garcia, 33, to kill Hernandez the week Smith's
body was found in the Everglades. Police arrested Hernandez before
the hit could be carried out, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis wouldn't discuss possible motives for either case.
</P>
<P>
   Massaro's attorney, Fred Haddad, told The Miami Herald his
client intends to fight the charges against him: murder, conspiracy
to murder, racketeering, bank fraud, loansharking, theft and
illegal possession of firearms. Prosecutors didn't know who was
representing Trentacosta and Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Also arrested Tuesday on racketeering and other charges were
Julius B. Chiusano, 52, charged with bank fraud and counterfeiting
checks; Charles P. Monico, 43, and Anthony R. Banks, 27, both
charged with helping dump Smith's body; and Francis ''Little
Frankie'' Ruggiero, 62, charged with loansharking.
</P>
<P>
   Police were searching for Garcia, charged with conspiracy to
commit murder and loansharking, and Adam T. Silverman, 33, who is
charged with loansharking and helping dispose of Smith's body.
</P>
<P>
   Chiusano's attorney, Don Spadero, said he had not spoken to his
client in detail about the charges but said the counterfeit checks
his client allegedly helped pass totaled less than $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Public defenders and attorneys representing the other men could
not be immediately reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 2213 </TRAILER>
