<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, Sept. 27, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Offers To Pull Plug on 'Soft Money' Ads
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore offered today to
pull the plug on all presidential campaign radio and TV ads paid for by
political parties with unregulated ''soft money'' -- but only if George W. Bush
does likewise. Bush had signaled his reluctance to do so just a day earlier,
saying he wanted to get rid of such ads but that Gore couldn't be counted on to
abide by such a deal. ''I don't trust him, to be frank with you,'' the Texas
governor said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-KLA Chief Warns Yugoslav Leaders
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Any attempts by Yugoslav leaders to return
police or military units to Kosovo would ''bring another war'' that could trap
NATO-led forces in the middle, the former Kosovo Liberation Army political chief
warned today. The increasingly sharp comments by Hashim Thaci are part of
efforts to tap into pro-independence sentiments and memories of the KLA's
struggle against Serb forces before Oct. 28 municipal elections. Thaci's
Democratic Party of Kosovo is particularly critical of the more moderate
positions of ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Drug Industry Gave $800,000 to GOP
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The pharmaceutical industry gave more than $800,000 to
Republican Party committees last month after the Senate voted to allow reimports
of lower-priced U.S.-made drugs -- something the companies oppose. In addition,
the president of Bristol-Myers Squibb co-chaired a fund-raising dinner today for
Senate Republicans. But despite the intensive lobbying effort, Congress is
likely to pass the legislation. The pharmaceutical industry also is fighting a
Democratic proposal to expand Medicare, the health care program for the elderly,
to cover the cost of prescription drugs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Milosevic Opponents Rally in Streets
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- More than 200,000 joyful opponents of Slobodan
Milosevic swarmed the capital's downtown district today, supporting an
opposition claim of an electoral triumph over the Yugoslav president. The
biggest demonstration ever against Milosevic completely blocked Belgrade's main
streets around Republic Square. Much of the downtown area teemed with people
waving flags and chanting: ''He's finished.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Inmate Executed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- A condemned man who won an unprecedented reprieve
from Gov. George W. Bush for DNA tests that only confirmed his guilt was
executed today for killing his 12-year-old stepdaughter. Ricky McGinn, 43,
received a lethal injection for raping Stephanie Flanary and bludgeoning her
with an ax. He insisted evidence was planted or tampered with, but DNA tests
completed in August again linked McGinn to the 1993 crime. The McGinn case drew
attention because of the June 1 reprieve by Bush.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Crew of Fatal Ferry Crash Arrested
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PAROS, Greece (AP) -- Greek authorities today arrested the captain and four
crew members of a ferry that struck a rocky outcrop marked by a light beacon
that could be seen for seven miles. At least 66 people were killed. Searches
continued throughout the night for possible survivors. Some survivors said crew
members were watching a soccer match on television Tuesday night when the ship,
holding more than 500 people, went aground in a gale in the Aegean Sea just two
miles from shore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose early Thursday, rebounding modestly from the
previous day's sharp decline. The dollar was lower against the yen. The Nikkei
gained 126.61 points, or 0.81 percent, to 15,766.56 points in the first 30
minutes of trading. On Wednesday, the average closed down 288.67 points, or 1.81
percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Devil Rays 11, Yankees 1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Jose Guillen, Ozzie Timmons and Fred McGriff
homered Wednesday night as the Tampa Bay Devil Rays once again prevented the
Yankees from clinching the AL East, beating New York 11-1. Cory Lidle limited
the two-time defending World Series champions to five hits in seven innings.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mets Clinch NL Wild Card
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For the first time ever, the New York Mets are going to the
playoffs in consecutive years after beating the Braves 6-2 tonight to clinch the
NL wild card berth. Rick Reed limited Atlanta to four hits in eight innings and
pinch-hitter Darryl Hamilton singled in the go-ahead run in the fifth. After
slumping for the third straight September, the Mets survived and will open the
playoffs Oct. 4 at San Francisco or St. Louis.
</P>
