<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister Talks About Freeman's Win  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- Cathy Freeman's gold-medal run in the
Olympics will not pressure the federal government to apologize to
the ''stolen generation'' of Aborigines, a cabinet minister said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, whose grandmother was removed from her family as a
child, has criticized the government's refusal to say sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Freeman's heightened Olympic profile, including a
win the women's 400 meters, would increase pressure on the
government, Reconciliation Minister Philip Ruddock told Australian
Broadcasting Corp., radio: ''I don't think it changes the issues at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the point I would make is that Cathy is a great example to
other young people about what can be done, what can be achieved,
and is an outstanding role model for all Australians, but
particularly for indigenous Australians.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1910 until the 1970s, authorities placed about 100,000
Aboriginal children in the care of white families. State and
federal law declared it was humane to save children of a doomed
race.
</P>
<P>
   Ruddock said Freeman's run showed Australia was an inclusive
society in which all are able to participate fully.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's regrettable that in the past that's not always been
possible for indigenous Australians,'' he said. ''What we have been
seeking to do is to have through the reconciliation process a
unifying approach to Australia in which Aboriginal self-esteem is
lifted, that there are role models that people can follow, and I
think Cathy Freeman exemplifies all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Aborigines say it is not possible to achieve reconciliation
until conservative Prime Minister John Howard offers a formal
apology for past government injustices -- something he has refused
to do.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's original inhabitants, Aborigines number about
360,000 of a total population of 19 million people. After 212 years
of white settlement, Aborigines have a life expectancy 20 years
shorter than the rest of society and are the community's poorest,
least educated and most jailed people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 2310 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SLOC Billed for Bid Execs' Lawyers  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL FOY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Salt Lake Organizing Committee stopped
payments to defense lawyers for two indicted bid executives after
covering $542,070 of the $762,635 in fees.
</P>
<P>
   The figures, released Wednesday to The Associated Press,
underscore a dispute over SLOC's obligation to pay to defend Tom
Welch and Dave Johnson from criminal bribery charges. Organizers
suspended payments after the bid leaders were indicted in July.
</P>
<P>
   SLOC president Mitt Romney has offered to resume the payments if
Welch and Johnson renounce any legal claims against organizers for
past compensation or wrongful termination.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have refused, with Welch saying he was owed $1 million
in deferred compensation. Both men insist SLOC must cover their
defense costs under a liability policy.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute remained under negotiation Wednesday, when SLOC
disclosed it paid $542,070 to Welch lawyers Tom Schaffer and
William Taylor and Johnson lawyer Max Wheeler, and had accumulated
another $220,565 in unpaid bills.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor replaced Schaffer after the bid leaders were indicted.
Wheeler has represented Johnson since the Olympic scandal broke 22
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The costs are only a small part of SLOC's scandal-related legal
costs. The total, by Romney's count, exceeds $4.2 million,
including more than $2 million spent on a string of lawyers for
Welch and Johnson, the committee, other Olympic trustees and
officers. The lawyers were hired in December 1998 when U.S. Justice
Department attorneys began interviewing witnesses and issuing
subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   Romney has said SLOC doesn't have to pay for Welch and Johnson's
attorneys if the two men are found guilty by a jury of criminal
wrongdoing. He also maintains organizers can wait until after a
trial to determine whether they have to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Welch, 55, who was president of the Salt Lake bid committee, and
Johnson, 41, vice president, were indicted July 20 by a federal
grand jury on charges that $1 million in cash, gifts, scholarships
and other inducements were given to International Olympic Committee
members who in 1995 awarded Salt Lake the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-27-00 2338 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000927.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-27 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Isler Claims Women's 470 Silver  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- J.J. Isler of San Diego rode Sydney
Harbor's shifting wind to a dramatic comeback on the final leg to
claim the women's 470 Olympic silver medal behind a dominating
Australian boat.
</P>
<P>
   In 10th place and out of the medals at the top mark, Isler
sailed close to Bradley's Head and passed four boats on the
spinnaker run to the finish, with the Sydney Opera House and Harbor
Bridge in the distance Thursday (Wednesday night EDT). She finished
sixth, enough to beat Ukraine by one point for the silver.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian crew of Jenny Armstrong and Belinda Stowell ran
away with the race and handily won the gold, the country's first in
sailing since 1972. Passing ferries and spectator boats blasted
their horns to salute the winners.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second Olympic medal for Isler, 36, who took the 470
bronze in 1992. Her crewmember, Pease Glaser, 38, of Long Beach,
Calif., was in her first Olympics and matched the silver medal won
by her husband, Jay, in the Tornado Class in 1984. Glaser had tried
and failed to make the Olympic team three previous times.
</P>
<P>
   Isler and Glaser were unsure of their chances coming into the
games, because they lost training time after Isler became pregnant
with her second daughter. But they also figured that their
experience would be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second American sailing medal in these games,
matching the total of 1996 when the United States underperformed in
its home waters.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Jonathan and Charlie McKee won the 49er bronze medal
here.
</P>
<P>
   Isler was in good position sailing upwind on the first leg, but
got into bad air coming off other boats' sails as the boats
approached the mark. She never recovered until the final leg.
</P>
<P>
   The deciding races had been scheduled for Wednesday, but the
wind died to practically nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was a more typical Sydney Harbor day, with a stiff
nor'easter blowing between 15 and 17 knots.
</P>
<P>
   The men's 470 race was started after the women's race finished.
Paul Foerster of Rockwall, Texas, and crewman Bob Merrick of
Portsmouth, R.I., were in second place coming in, behind the
Australian crew. Foerster was the Flying Dutchman silver medalist
in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
