<HEADLINE> Man Sentenced in Student Slayings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEUBENVILLE, Ohio (AP) -- One of two men convicted of kidnapping
and murdering two Franciscan University students was sentenced to
death Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Yarbrough, 20, of Pittsburgh, was convicted on Friday in
the kidnapping and killings of Brian Muha, 18, of Westerville,
Ohio, and Aaron Land, 20, of Philadelphia. The jury recommended the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence showed the students were beaten and then abducted from
their home near campus in May 1999. Both were shot to death in the
woods after being driven a short distance over the Pennsylvania
border.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Joseph Bruzzese imposed the sentence Wednesday in
Jefferson County Common Pleas Court.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I'm going to die, let me die,'' Yarbrough said shortly
before sentencing. He subsequently said he would appeal the
conviction and hire a private attorney. He was represented by a
court-appointed lawyer during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Yarbrough instigated the murders and then
bragged to friends. His companion in the case, Nathan Herring, 19,
of Steubenville, was found guilty and sentenced earlier to life in
prison without parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
