<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kouchner Candidate for Top UN Post  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Bernard Kouchner, the U.N. administrator
in Kosovo, confirmed Wednesday he is a candidate for the top U.N.
refugee post.
</P>
<P>
   Sadako Ogata of Japan completes her nine-year term as U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees at the end of the year, and there has
been much speculation about a successor in the high-profile job.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he was a candidate, Kouchner replied: ''It
has been well known -- so yes I am.''
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly added: ''Well, it depends on my country. It
depends mainly on the secretary-general's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Under U.N. procedures, Secretary-General Kofi Annan will propose
a nominee to the General Assembly, which normally rubber-stamps the
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Annan appointed Kouchner, who is French, to head the U.N.
civilian administration for Kosovo in July 1999, after NATO bombing
forced Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to pull his troops
out. In August, his contract was renewed for a year.
</P>
<P>
   A former French health minister and a founder of the aid group
Doctors Without Borders, Kouchner was an outspoken proponent of
humanitarian objectives during the Bosnian and Kosovo wars and has
a history of high-profile humanitarian intervention in conflicts in
Africa and Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
